ww.mao-qc.ca\">{{cite web |title=Liste des Macromyc\u00e8tes \u2013 Outaouais Qu\u00e9bec 1984\u20142006 |publisher=Les mycologues amateurs de l'Outaouais |url=http://www.mao-qc.ca/myco/images/Macromycetes%201984-2006.pdf |accessdate=2009-08-18 |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090902083926/http://www.mao-qc.ca/myco/images/Macromycetes%201984-2006.pdf |archive-date=2009-09-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Vozzo 1961\">{{cite journal |author1=Vozzo, J.A. |author2=Hackskaylo, E. |year=1961 |title=Mycorrhizal fungi on ''Pinus virginiana'' |jstor=3756310 |journal=[[Mycologia]] |volume=53 |issue=5 |pages=538\u2013539 |doi=10.2307/3756310 |url=http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/cyberliber/59350/0053/005/0538.htm |access-date=2012-11-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923224810/http://www.cybertruffle.org.uk/cyberliber/59350/0053/005/0538.htm |archive-date=2015-09-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Yang 1999\">{{cite journal |author1=Yang, Z.-L. |author2=Doi, Y. |year=1999 |title=A contribution to the knowledge of ''Amanita'' (Amanitaceae, Agaricales) in Japan |journal=Bulletin of the National Science Museum of Tokyo Series B |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=107\u2013130}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Zhang 2004\">{{cite journal |author1=Zhang, L. |author2=Yang, J. |author3=Zhuliang, Y. |year=2004 |title=Molecular phylogeny of eastern Asian species of ''Amanita'' (Agaricales, Basidiomycota): taxonomic and biogeographic implications |journal=Fungal Diversity |volume=17 |pages=219\u2013238 |url=http://eticomm.net/~ret/amanita/pdfs/Zhang%20Amanita%20phylogeny.pdf }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n===Cited books===\n* {{cite book |author=Jenkins, D.B. |title=''Amanita'' of North America |publisher=Mad River Press |location=Eureka, California |year=1986 |isbn=0-916422-55-0}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Metzler, V. |author2=Metzler, S. |title=Texas Mushrooms: A Field Guide |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |location=Austin, Texas |year=1992 |isbn=0-292-75125-7}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1943327}}\n\n[[Category:Amanita|abrupta]]\n[[Category:Fungi described in 1897]]\n[[Category:Fungi of North America]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Charles Horton Peck]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "-> lower case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amanita_abrupta"}
{"title_page": "City of Bayswater", "text_new": "{{About|a local government area|the suburb|Bayswater, Western Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = lga \n| name     = City of Bayswater\n| state    = WA\n| image    = Bayswater LGA WA.png\n| image_upright = 0.81\n| caption  = \n| pop      = 66,050\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"Census2016\">{{Census 2016 AUS|id=LGA50420 |name=Bayswater (C) |accessdate=26 November 2017 |quick=on}}</ref>\n| area     = 34.6\n| est      = 1897\n| seat     = [[Morley, Western Australia|Morley]]\n| mayor    = Dan Bull\n| region   = [[Eastern Metropolitan Regional Council|Eastern Metropolitan Perth]]\n| logo     = Bayswater logo.jpg\n| logo_upright = 0.6\n| url      = http://www.bayswater.wa.gov.au\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Maylands|Maylands]], [[Electoral district of Bassendean|Bassendean]], [[Electoral district of Morley|Morley]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Perth]]\n| near-nw  = [[City of Stirling|Stirling]]\n| near-n   = [[City of Swan|Swan]]\n| near-ne  = [[City of Swan|Swan]]\n| near-w   = [[City of Stirling|Stirling]]\n| near-e   = [[Town of Bassendean|Bassendean]]\n| near-sw  = [[City of Vincent|Vincent]]\n| near-s   = [[Town of Victoria Park|Victoria Park]]\n| near-se  = [[City of Belmont|Belmont]]\n}}\n\nThe '''City of Bayswater''' is a [[Local government areas of Western Australia|local government area]] in the [[Western Australia]]n capital city of [[Perth]], about {{convert|7|km|mi|0}} northeast of [[Perth central business district|Perth's central business district]]. The City covers an area of {{convert|34.6|km2|sqmi|1}} and has a population of 65,050 as at the [[2016 Australia Census|2016 Census]]. The City of Bayswater is a member of the [[Eastern Metropolitan Regional Council]].\n\n==History==\nThe Bayswater Road District was created on 5 March 1897. On 1 July 1961, it became a shire following the enactment of the ''Local Government Act 1960''. On 29 October 1983 it attained city status.<ref>WA Electoral Commission, ''Municipality Boundary Amendments Register'' (release 2.0), 31 May 2003.</ref><ref>{{Gazette WA|title=Local Government Act 1960\u20131982. City of Bayswater (City Status) Order 1983|date=3 June 1983|page=1983:1704}}</ref> In 1998 the suburb of Maylands was transferred into the City of Bayswater from the [[City of Stirling]]. The portion of the suburb of [[Noranda, Western Australia|Noranda]] north of Widgee Road was transferred to the City of Bayswater from the [[City of Swan]] on 1 July 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pascual Juanola|first1=Marta|title=Noranda joins Baysy|url=https://perthvoiceinteractive.com/2016/03/31/noranda-joins-baysy/|accessdate=9 April 2016|work=The Perth Voice|date=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Past Mayors===\n\n* [[John D'Orazio]] (1984-2001)\n* Terry Kenyon (2005-2007)\n* Lou Magro (2007-2009)\n* Terry Kenyon (2009-2013)\n* Sylvan Albert (2013-2015)\n* Barry McKenna (2015-2017)\n\n==Wards==\nThe City is divided into 4 wards. The Mayor and Deputy Mayor is each elected from among the councillors.\n\n* Central Ward (3 Councillors) Cr Barry McKenna (1991\u2013present), Cr Steven Ostaszewskyj (2019\u2013present), Cr Sally Palmer (2015\u2013present)\n\n* North Ward (3 Councillors) Cr Brent Fleeton (2015\u2013present), Cr Stephanie Gray (2017-present), Cr Filomena Piffaretti (2017-present)\n\n* South Ward (2 Councillors) Cr Catherine Ehrhardt (2015\u2013present), Cr Elli Petersen-Pik (2017-present)\n\n* West Ward (3 Councillors) Cr Dan Bull (2015-present), Cr Lorna Clarke (2017-present), Cr Giorgia Johnson (2017-present)\n\nCurrent Mayor: Cr Dan Bull (Oct 2017\u2013present). \nCurrent Deputy Mayor: Cr Filomena Piffaretti (Oct 2019\u2013present)\n\n==Suburbs==\n* [[Bayswater, Western Australia|Bayswater]]\n* [[Bedford, Western Australia|Bedford]]\n* [[Embleton, Western Australia|Embleton]]\n* [[Maylands, Western Australia|Maylands]]\n* [[Morley, Western Australia|Morley]]\n* [[Mount Lawley, Western Australia|Mount Lawley]] *\n* [[Noranda, Western Australia|Noranda]]\n*[[Dianella, Western Australia]]*\n\n<div class=small><nowiki>*</nowiki> indicates suburb partially located within City</div>\n\n==Population==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n|- \n| 1911 || 1,790 \n|- \n| 1921 || 2,392 \n|- \n| 1933 || 4,138 \n|- \n| 1947 || 6,453 \n|- \n| 1954 || 14,555 \n|- \n| 1961 || 19,296 \n|- \n| 1966 || 26,112 \n|- \n| 1971 || 34,261 \n|- \n| 1976 || 38,302 \n|- \n| 1981 || 38,526 \n|- \n| 1986 || 41,331 \n|- \n| 1991 || 43,810 \n|-\n| 1996 || 43,573 \n|-\n| 2001 || 54,008 \n|-\n| 2006 || 55,801 \n|-\n| 2011 || 61,262 \n|-\n| 2016 || 64,677\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://lgam.wikidot.com/bayswater-city-council City of Bayswater Asset Management Information]\n\n{{Local Government Areas of Western Australia}}\n{{Cities of Western Australia}}\n{{coord|-31.887|115.907|type:adm2nd_region:AU-WA|format=dms|display=title}}<!-- coords of seat -->\n\n[[Category:Local government areas of the Perth region of Western Australia|Bayswater]]\n[[Category:City of Bayswater]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a local government area|the suburb|Bayswater, Western Australia}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox Australian place | type = lga \n| name     = City of Bayswater\n| state    = WA\n| image    = Bayswater LGA WA.png\n| image_upright = 0.81\n| caption  = \n| pop      = 66,050\n| pop_year = {{CensusAU|2016}}\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=\"Census2016\">{{Census 2016 AUS|id=LGA50420 |name=Bayswater (C) |accessdate=26 November 2017 |quick=on}}</ref>\n| area     = 34.6\n| est      = 1897\n| seat     = [[Morley, Western Australia|Morley]]\n| mayor    = Dan Bull\n| region   = [[Eastern Metropolitan Regional Council|Eastern Metropolitan Perth]]\n| logo     = Bayswater logo.jpg\n| logo_upright = 0.6\n| url      = http://www.bayswater.wa.gov.au\n| stategov = [[Electoral district of Maylands|Maylands]], [[Electoral district of Bassendean|Bassendean]], [[Electoral district of Morley|Morley]]\n| fedgov   = [[Division of Perth]]\n| near-nw  = [[City of Stirling|Stirling]]\n| near-n   = [[City of Swan|Swan]]\n| near-ne  = [[City of Swan|Swan]]\n| near-w   = [[City of Stirling|Stirling]]\n| near-e   = [[Town of Bassendean|Bassendean]]\n| near-sw  = [[City of Vincent|Vincent]]\n| near-s   = [[Town of Victoria Park|Victoria Park]]\n| near-se  = [[City of Belmont|Belmont]]\n}}\n\nThe '''City of Bayswater''' is a [[Local government areas of Western Australia|local government area]] in the [[Western Australia]]n capital city of [[Perth]], about {{convert|7|km|mi|0}} northeast of [[Perth central business district|Perth's central business district]]. The City covers an area of {{convert|34.6|km2|sqmi|1}} and has a population of 65,050 as at the [[2016 Australia Census|2016 Census]]. The City of Bayswater is a member of the [[Eastern Metropolitan Regional Council]].\n\n==History==\nThe Bayswater Road District was created on 5 March 1897. On 1 July 1961, it became a shire following the enactment of the ''Local Government Act 1960''. On 29 October 1983 it attained city status.<ref>WA Electoral Commission, ''Municipality Boundary Amendments Register'' (release 2.0), 31 May 2003.</ref><ref>{{Gazette WA|title=Local Government Act 1960\u20131982. City of Bayswater (City Status) Order 1983|date=3 June 1983|page=1983:1704}}</ref> In 1998 the suburb of Maylands was transferred into the City of Bayswater from the [[City of Stirling]]. The portion of the suburb of [[Noranda, Western Australia|Noranda]] north of Widgee Road was transferred to the City of Bayswater from the [[City of Swan]] on 1 July 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pascual Juanola|first1=Marta|title=Noranda joins Baysy|url=https://perthvoiceinteractive.com/2016/03/31/noranda-joins-baysy/|accessdate=9 April 2016|work=The Perth Voice|date=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Past Mayors===\n\n* [[John D'Orazio]] (1984-2001)\n* Terry Kenyon (2005-2007)\n* Lou Magro (2007-2009)\n* Terry Kenyon (2009-2013)\n* Sylvan Albert (2013-2015)\n* Barry McKenna (2015-2017)\n\n==Wards==\nThe City is divided into 4 wards. The Mayor and Deputy Mayor is each elected from among the councillors.\n\n* Central Ward (3 Councillors) Cr Barry McKenna (1991\u2013present), Cr Steven Ostaszewskyj (2019\u2013present), Cr Sally Palmer (2015\u2013present)\n\n* North Ward (3 Councillors) Cr Brent Fleeton (2015\u2013present), Cr Stephanie Gray (2017-present), Cr Filomena Piffaretti (2017-present)\n\n* South Ward (2 Councillors) Cr Catherine Ehrhardt (2015\u2013present), Cr Elli Petersen-Pik (2017-present)\n\n* West Ward (3 Councillors) Cr Dan Bull (2015-present), Cr Lorna Clarke (2017-present), Cr Giorgia Johnson (2017-present)\n\nCurrent Mayor: Cr Dan Bull (Oct 2017\u2013present). \nCurrent Deputy Mayor: Cr Filomena Piffaretti (Oct 2019\u2013present)\n\n==Suburbs==\n* [[Bayswater, Western Australia|Bayswater]]\n* [[Bedford, Western Australia|Bedford]]\n* [[Embleton, Western Australia|Embleton]]\n* [[Maylands, Western Australia|Maylands]]\n* [[Morley, Western Australia|Morley]]\n* [[Mount Lawley, Western Australia|Mount Lawley]] *\n* [[Noranda, Western Australia|Noranda]]\n*[[Dianella, Western Australia]]*\n\n<div class=small><nowiki>*</nowiki> indicates suburb partially located within City</div>\n\n==Population==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Population\n|- \n| 1911 || 1,790 \n|- \n| 1921 || 2,392 \n|- \n| 1933 || 4,138 \n|- \n| 1947 || 6,453 \n|- \n| 1954 || 14,555 \n|- \n| 1961 || 19,296 \n|- \n| 1966 || 26,112 \n|- \n| 1971 || 34,261 \n|- \n| 1976 || 38,302 \n|- \n| 1981 || 38,526 \n|- \n| 1986 || 41,331 \n|- \n| 1991 || 43,810 \n|-\n| 1996 || 43,573 \n|-\n| 2001 || 54,008 \n|-\n| 2006 || 55,801 \n|-\n| 2011 || 61,262 \n|-\n| 2016 || 64,677\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://lgam.wikidot.com/bayswater-city-council City of Bayswater Asset Management Information]\n\n{{Local Government Areas of Western Australia}}\n{{Cities of Western Australia}}\n{{coord|-31.887|115.907|type:adm2nd_region:AU-WA|format=dms|display=title}}<!-- coords of seat -->\n\n[[Category:Local government areas of the Perth region of Western Australia|Bayswater]]\n[[Category:City of Bayswater]\n", "name_user": "Calistemon", "label": "safe", "comment": "add missing ]", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/City_of_Bayswater"}
{"title_page": "Palo Cedro, California", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Palo Cedro\n|settlement_type          = [[census-designated place]]\n|image_skyline            = Windmill Palo Cedro.jpg\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = Windmill, Downtown Palo Cedro \n|image_seal               =\n|image_map                = Shasta_County_California_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Palo_Cedro_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Shasta County, California|Shasta County]] and the state of [[California]]\n|image_map1               =\n|mapsize1                 =\n|map_caption1             =\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|California}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in California|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Shasta County, California|Shasta]]\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =\n|leader_name              =\n|established_date         =\n<!-- Area------------------>\n|area_magnitude           =\n| unit_pref               =US\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>[https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt U.S. Census] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |date=2012-01-25 }}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi        = 3.754\n| area_land_sq_mi         = 3.679\n| area_water_sq_mi        = 0.075\n| area_total_km2          = 9.722\n| area_land_km2           = 9.528\n| area_water_km2          = 0.194\n| area_water_percent      = 2.00\n| area_note               =\n|elevation_ft             = 465\n|elevation_m              = 143\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_total         = 1269\n|population_metro         =\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n|utc_offset               = \u22128\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|33|4|N|122|14|3|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = \u22127\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 96073\n|area_code                = [[Area code 530|530]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 06-55296\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0230275\n|footnotes                =\n|website                  =\n}}\n'''Palo Cedro''' (''Cedarwood'') is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in [[Shasta County, California|Shasta County]], [[California]], United States. The population was 1,269 at the 2010 census, up from 1,247 at the 2000 census. It is 8 miles (13&nbsp;km) east of [[Redding, California]].  The communities of [[Bella Vista, California|Bella Vista]] (pop. 2,781), [[Millville, California|Millville]] (pop. 727), [[Shingletown, California|Shingletown]] (pop. 2,283), [[Oak Run, California|Oak Run]] (pop. 880),{{sfn|Berkshire Hathaway Home Services}} [[Whitmore, California|Whitmore]] (pop. 999),{{sfn|CLR Choice, Inc.}} and [[Round Mountain, California|Round Mountain]] (pop. 155) lie within a 15-mile (24&nbsp;km) radius.\n\nOriginally, indigenous Native Americans lived in Northern California, including what is now Shasta County, prior to European American settlement. European American exploration of inland California started in 1769 and continued on into the 19th Century. Cow Creek, a Sacramento River tributary, that runs south through Palo Cedro, was a conduit for entrance into the [[Sacramento Valley]] by Hudson Bay Fur Company trappers including [[Alexander Roderick McLeod|Alexander McLeod]] (1829) and [[John Work (fur trader)|John Work]] (1832). The town is named after cedarwood trees originally indigenous to the area in the 19th Century.\n\nAs of the 2010 census, Palo Cedro has a population density of 338.1 people per square mile (130.5/km<sup>2</sup>). Award winning country musician [[Merle Haggard]] lived in Palo Cedro for decades until his death on April 6, 2016.\n\n==History==\n===Indigenous peoples===\n{{main|Indigenous peoples of California}}\n\nPrior to white settlement, various Indian tribes settled and inhabited Northern California.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} These tribes included the [[Wintu]], [[Patwin]]s, Nozi, [[Pit River Tribe|Pit Rivers]], Hat Creeks, [[Shasta people|Shastas]], [[Northern Paiute|Paiute]]s, and [[Modoc people|Modoc]] Indian tribes.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} The Wintus established their main camp on Cottonwood Creek.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} [[Penutian languages|Penutian]] Indian tribes on the [[Pacific coast]] or valley included the [[Maidu]], [[Miwok]], [[Ohlone|Constanoan]], [[Yokuts]], Yanas, and other divisions. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} Historians said that, in the lower 48 continental United States, California has the most native tribes and subdivisions of tribes and more different Indian languages.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} The Wintus were the largest and most peaceful division that settled in Northern California and Oregon. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}}\n\n===18th and 19th centuries===\n{{see|History of California before 1900|Alta California|California grizzly bears}}\nDuring the 18th Century, the first recorded Spanish (or any European) land entry and exploration of the present-day state of California, was the [[Portol\u00e1 expedition]], in 1769\u20131770, that led to the founding of [[Alta California]], reaching as far north as [[San Francisco Bay]].\n\nThe 19th Century launched many explorations by whites into California and its northern interior. In March 1812, the Russian-American Fur Company under [[Ivan Kuskov]] established a colony at [[Fort Ross, California|Fort Ross]] on the coast of what is now Sonoma County.{{sfn|''Fort Ross'' Establishment of the California Settlement 1998}} As early as 1817, Father [[Narciso Dur\u00e1n]], on an expedition sighted a snow capped mountain (Mount Shasta), that he called ''Jesus Maria'', from what is now the Marysville plains. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=11-12}} Three years later, in 1827, an expedition to the Klammath Mountains from the Coastal Range, by explorer [[Luis Antonio Arg\u00fcello|Luis Arg\u00fcello]] and company, sighted two \"twin\" mountains, believed to be Mount Shasta and Mount Lassen.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=11-12}} In 1826, Mount Shasta was seen by Hudson Bay fur trader Peter Skene Odgen.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=14}} In 1828, Mt. Shasta was seen by United States fur trapper [[Jedediah Smith]], whom he named ''Mt. Simpson''.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=13-14}} On April 11, 1828 Smith and his party traveled north and entered what is now called Shasta County, and proceeded to what is now called [[Burnt Ranch, California|Burnt Ranch]] in Trinity County.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=13-14}}\n[[File:John Work, Hudson's Bay Company officer, before 1861.jpg|left|thumb|120px|<center>'''John Work'''</center>]]\nThe earliest [[European Americans|European American]] history of Palo Cedro comes from the exploration of [[Hudson's Bay Company]] trapper [[Alexander Roderick McLeod|Alexander McLeod]] (c. 1782&nbsp;\u2013 11 June 1840) who sometime between March 26, 1829 and April 6, 1829, along with guide [[John Turner (fur trapper)|John Turner]], and a brigade of trappers, traveling through Mexican [[California]], started from the Pit River following the [[Cow Creek (Sacramento River tributary)|Cow Creek]] trail, and reached the Sacramento River.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} [[Cow Creek (Sacramento River tributary)|Cow Creek]] is Sacramento River tributary that runs through Palo Cedro and serves as its south eastern borderline. McLeod had been sent out earlier in January 1829 from Fort Vancouver to find the origins of a mythical [[Buenaventura River (legend)|Buenaventura River]].{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} After crossing the Sacramento River, McLeod explored and trapped in the [[Sacramento Valley]] as far South as present day Stockton. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} Upon his return with an abundant supply of furs, he camped on the west bank of the Sacramento River by present day [[Anderson, California|Anderson]] in December 1829. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} While attempting to cross the Cascades in winter, McLeod was met by a snow storm at the headwaters of the river named after him, ''McLeod River'' ([[McCloud River]]), he lost all his horses, was forced to cache his furs, and by snowshoe trek back to Vancouver, arriving on February 10, 1830. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}}{{efn|According to historian Rosena A. Giles, the name of the McCloud river was a misspelling of McLeod's original name, and confused by the name of Ross McCloud, a pioneer of the 1850's. In 1878, an unsuccessful attempt was made by C.C. Bush to have the California state legislature change the name of the river from ''McCloud'' to ''McLeod''.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} Frank & Chapel called the river ''McLeod''. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} Reading called the river ''McLoud''.  {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}}}}\n[[File:74-LASSOING_A_GRIZZLEY.jpg|right|180px|thumb|'''Lassoing a Grizzley''' ''1873''<br>Canadian fur trapper John Work, in 1832, noted there were California grizzlies, in the area of what is now Palo Cedro. California grizzlies were hunted to extinction in the 1920s.]]\n\nIn 1832, another Hudson's Bay trapper [[John Work (fur trader)|John Work]] (c.1792-1861), searching for a route to connect the [[Columbia River]] to the [[Sacramento River]], reported in his journal traveling through Mexican California in with a group from the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] fur traders, staying east of the [[Siskiyou Mountains|Siskiyous]], bypassing [[Lassen Peak|Mt. Lassen]], along Cow Creek, through the areas now known as [[Millville, California|Millville]] and Palo Cedro, finding a way to the Sacramento Valley.{{sfnm|Owens|2002|1p=348|Giles|1949|2pp=15-16}}{{efn|Historian Rosena A. Giles said Work's party included 28 men, 22 women, and 44 children.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=15}}}} In the surrounding area, Work noted there were local Indians who lived in huts, in addition to various wildlife and numerous animals, including deer, elk, and grizzly bears.{{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=209-210}} Local Indian men gave Work and his men food. {{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=209-210}} Work called Cow Creek, ''Canoe River'', and his men chopped down pine trees to make canoes, camped near what is now called [[Anderson, California|Anderson]]. {{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=209-210, 216}}{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=15}} During their stay, while his men were making the canoes, Work said the Indians were weeping and lamenting and observed six fires were burning in the Indian camp. {{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=210-211}} Work later learned that the local Indian camp had been attacked and burned by another Indian raiding party, possibly the Shastas.{{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=210-211}} After trapping in the Sacramento Valley, work retraced his steps to the Pit River, and using the same route as McLeod had earlier used through Bartle's Gap, but without disaster, emerged from the mountains and was assisted back to Vancouver.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=15-16}}\n[[image:Carsonfremont.jpg|150px|thumb|left|John C. Fr\u00e9mont (seated right)<br>and his guide [[Kit Carson]].]]\nIn 1846, on his third expedition, [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] and his military party, followed the Cow Creek, Walla Walla Trail through what is now Shasta County, headed north to Klammath Lake area in Oregon.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=46}}{{efn|''Walla Walla'' or old ''Columbian'' are terms for the trail between Mount Shasta and Mount Lassen.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=12}}}} Fr\u00e9mont's guide for three federal expeditions was mountain man [[Kit Carson]].\n\nIn June 1850, U.S. Army Captain [[Nathaniel Lyon]], and his military party along with Colonel Freaner, left [[Pierson Barton Reading|Pierson Reading]]'s [[Rancho Buena Ventura]] following Fremont's route through the Cow Creek and Pit River.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=49}} Lyon had been sent from [[Benicia, California|Benicia]] by his government to avenge the death of Captain Warren. {{sfn|Giles|1949|p=49}}\n\nIn 1883, a United States post office was established for this area; at that time, the town was known as Albertson.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}} The name was changed to Roberts in 1885 and finally to Palo Cedro in 1893, meaning \"[[Cedrus|cedarwood]]\" in Spanish, after the cedar trees of the area.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}}\n\nIn 1891, T.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;H. Shannahan and Joe Enright bought {{convert|30|acre|ha}} of land from Lem Benton and had it divided into 12 lots.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}} The town never materialized or was developed, but the original cedar tree for which it was named was cut down.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}} School children since then planted cedar trees at the Junction School District yard.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}}\n\nIn 1897, or shortly before, the [[California, Shasta and Eastern Railway|Anderson and Bella Vista Railroad]] was constructed by the Terry Lumber Company from [[Anderson, California|Anderson]] to [[Bella Vista, California|Bella Vista]], passing through Palo Cedro.  Miners used this railroad, as did the Terry Lumber Company at Bella Vista.  The train delivered groceries and mail to the villages along its route. It also had a passenger car.\n\n===20th and 21st centuries===\n{{see|History of California 1900 to present|California}}\nIn the early 1900s, the stage route went from [[Redding, California|Redding]] through Palo Cedro, [[Millville, California|Millville]], [[Oak Run, California|Oak Run]], and on to [[Fall River Mills, California|Fall River Mills]].\n\nPalo Cedro's first school house was located near the corner of Hillside Drive and Deschutes Road on the south side of town. Later it was moved to a site near the Grange Hall, on the north side of town. The school was located there until the \"new\" Junction School was built in 1960 on the south side of town.\n\nIn 1907 or thereabouts, Frank and Mary Love owned the Palo Cedro general store. The store was on the west side of the tracks and their house on the east.  A two-story house on the northeast corner of Deschutes Road and Old Forty-Four Drive may, at one time, have been a stopping place for stage drivers and travelers. Sarah Addington later owned the Palo Cedro store.  She was also the postmaster and handed the position down to her daughter, Mary Jones. She moved the post office next door into her home.\n\nJohn Gebauer has since owned the store. In the 1960s John moved to his new building on the south east side of Palo Cedro; it had several one-story spaces for commercial businesses. The largest business was the Palo Cedro Market. Gebauer's son John now operates it. The post office moved into a part of Gebauer's building. Mary Jones' assistants were her sisters. The next postmaster was Sylvia Metz. As she found the post office needed more space, it moved to a two-story building on the north side of Palo Cedro.\n\nThe first Grange Hall and Feed Store were constructed in the early 1930s, just off Deschutes Road on Old Highway 44.  The building was two stories with the meeting and/or dance hall upstairs. The dining room was downstairs in back and the feed store in front. This building burned down in the early 1940s and was quickly replaced with a one-story building, which is still in use in the 21st century. The feed store was built on the north side of Old Forty-Four Drive and is still there today.\n\nAs Palo Cedro continued to grow more services were needed, and the first independently owned pharmacy opened in August 1975.  Its first space was a remodelled auto body shop. To accommodate its growing business, it moved to the current location on the south side of Highway 44 off Deschutes Road. Palo Cedro Pharmacy has an eclectic mix of pictures, memorabilia, and antiques collected over the last 40 years showing how the town and pharmacy has changed over the years. The unannounced and unknown to the Community and self proclaimed current Mayor of Palo Cedro is Carlos Zapata.\n\n==Geography==\nPalo Cedro is located at {{Coord|40|33|4|N|122|14|3|W|type:city}} (40.551091, \u2212122.234255)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> at an elevation of 465&nbsp;ft (143 m) above sea level.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|3.8|sqmi|km2}}, 98.00% of it land, and 2.00% of it water.\n\n===Climate===\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Palo Cedro has a [[Mediterranean climate#Warm-summer Mediterranean climate|warm-summer Mediterranean climate]], abbreviated \"Csa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=692740&cityname=Palo+Cedro%2C+California%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Palo Cedro, California]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n===2010===\nThe [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0655296|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140715032244/http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0655296|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 15, 2014|title=2010 Census Interactive Population Search: CA - Palo Cedro CDP|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|access-date=July 12, 2014}}</ref> reported that Palo Cedro had a population of 1,269. The [[population density]] was 338.1 people per square mile (130.5/km<sup>2</sup>). The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of Palo Cedro was 1,164 (91.7%) White, 7 (0.6%) African American, 24 (1.9%) Native American, 6 (0.5%) Asian, 1 (0.1%) Pacific Islander, 22 (1.7%) from other races, and 45 (3.5%) from two or more races.  Hispanic or Latino of any race were 74 persons (5.8%).\n\nThe Census reported that 1,260 people (99.3% of the population) lived in households, 4 (0.3%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 5 (0.4%) were institutionalized.\n\nThere were 474 households, out of which 153 (32.3%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 318 (67.1%) were [[marriage|opposite-sex married couples]] living together, 41 (8.6%) had a female householder with no husband present, 24 (5.1%) had a male householder with no wife present.  There were 18 (3.8%) [[POSSLQ|unmarried opposite-sex partnerships]], and 7 (1.5%) [[Domestic partnership|same-sex married couples or partnerships]]. 70 households (14.8%) were made up of individuals and 38 (8.0%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.66.  There were 383 [[Family (US Census)|families]] (80.8% of all households); the average family size was 2.89.\n\nThe population was spread out with 289 people (22.8%) under the age of 18, 74 people (5.8%) aged 18 to 24, 192 people (15.1%) aged 25 to 44, 429 people (33.8%) aged 45 to 64, and 285 people (22.5%) who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 48.3 years. For every 100 females, there were 96.4 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 95.6 males.\n\nThere were 504 housing units at an average density of 134.3 per square mile (51.8/km<sup>2</sup>), of which 411 (86.7%) were owner-occupied, and 63 (13.3%) were occupied by renters. The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.9%; the rental vacancy rate was 7.2%.  1,072 people (84.5% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 188 people (14.8%) lived in rental housing units.\n\n===2000===\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 1,247 people, 436 households, and 367 families residing in the CDP.  The [[population density]] was 330.1 people per square mile (127.4/km<sup>2</sup>).  There were 447 housing units at an average density of 118.3 per square mile (45.7/km<sup>2</sup>).  The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the CDP was 93.10% White, 0.56% African American, 1.12% Native American, 1.52% Asian, 0.88% from other races, and 2.81% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.57% of the population.\n\nThere were 436 households out of which 37.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 74.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 15.6% were non-families. 13.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.85 and the average family size was 3.12.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 27.7% under the age of 18, 6.7% from 18 to 24, 22.7% from 25 to 44, 28.7% from 45 to 64, and 14.2% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.8 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $51,471, and the median income for a family was $60,385. Males had a median income of $47,232 versus $33,125 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $23,419.  About 5.4% of families and 5.5% of the population were below the [[Poverty threshold|poverty line]], including 14.1% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Politics==\nIn the [[California State Legislature|state legislature]] Palo Cedro is located in {{Representative|casd|1|fmt=sdistrict}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://senate.ca.gov/senators |title=Senators |access-date=March 10, 2013  |publisher=State of California}}</ref> and {{Representative|caad|1|fmt=adistrict}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://assembly.ca.gov/assemblymembers |title=Members Assembly |access-date=March 2, 2013 |publisher=State of California}}</ref>\n\nFederally, Palo Cedro is in {{Representative|cacd|1|fmt=district}}.<ref>{{Cite GovTrack|CA|1|access-date=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\n[[file:MerleHaggardJun09.jpg|thumb|right|180px|<center>'''Merle Haggard''' ''June 2009''</center>]]\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Merle Haggard]], country musician, lived in Palo Cedro for decades until his death on his 79th birthday (April 6, 2016).\n\n==Education==\n;Elementary Schools:\n*North Cow Creek School\n*Junction Elementary School\n*Chrysalis Charter School\n*Redding Christian School\n\n;Middle Schools\n*Junction Intermediate School\n*Saint Francis Middle School\n*Chrysalis Charter School\n*North Cow Creek School\n*Redding Christian School\n\n;High Schools\n*[[Foothill High School (Palo Cedro, California)|Foothill High School]] has an  API score of 817, making it one of the best public schools in northern California.\n*[[Bishop Quinn High School]]\n*Redding Christian School\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Mount_Lassen_Sunrise1.jpg|View from Palo Cedro of Sunrise over Mount Lassen (September 2007)\nImage:Windmill Palo Cedro.jpg|Windmill landmark in Palo Cedro shopping center (November 2007)\nImage:Church and Mt Lassen Palo Cedro.jpg|Local Church with Mount Lassen in the Background (November 2007)\nImage:Palo Cedro Fire Dept.jpg|Palo Cedro Fire Department (November 2007)\nImage:Junction_Middle_School.jpg|Junction Middle School (Thanksgiving Holiday 2007)\nImage:Foothill HS 01.jpg|Foothill High School (November 2007)\nImage:Deschutes_Road_From_Junction.jpg|Deschutes Road Looking North, From Junction Elementary School (September 2007)\nImage:Church of Jesus Christ Latter Day Saints.jpg|Palo Cedro Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (November 2007)\nImage:Palo_Cedro_Inn.jpg|The Palo Cedro Inn\u2014A Palo Cedro Landmark (November 2007)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books and Journals===\n*{{cite book|title=''Fort Ross'' Establishment of the California Settlement|url=https://www.fortross.org/russian-american-company.htm|publisher=Fort Ross Interpretive Association (Fort Ross Conservancy)|date=1998|isbn=1-56540-355-X|ref={{sfnRef|''Fort Ross'' Establishment of the California Settlement 1998}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Giles|first=Rosena A.|title=Shasta County California A History|edition=California Centennial|publisher=Biobooks|location=[[Oakland, California|Oakland]]|date=1949|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Maloney|first1=Alice Bay|last2=Work|first2=John|title=Fur Brigade to the Bonaventura: John Work's California Expedition of 1832-33 for the Hudson's Bay Company|publisher=California Historical Society|journal=California Historical Society Quarterly|volume=22|number=3|date=September 1943|pages=193\u2013222|url=http://www.martinezbeavers.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Fur-Brigade-to-the-Bonaventura-John-Works-California-Expedition-of-1832-33-for-the-Hudsons-Bay-Company-Maloney-Work-Calif-Historical-Quarterly-Sept.-1943.pdf|format=PDF|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Owens|first=Kenneth N.|title=Riches for All: The California Gold Rush and the World|editor=Kenneth N. Owens|date=2002|chapter=Begun by Gold|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|location=[[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]]|isbn=0-8032-3570-4|ref=harv}}\n\n===Internet===\n* {{cite web|title=Oak Run 96069 Real Estate|url=https://www.berkshirehathawayhs.com/CA/Oak%20Run/96069|publisher=Berkshire Hathaway Home Services|date=2018|ref={{sfnRef|Berkshire Hathaway Home Services}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Whitmore, CA 96096 Population Growth and Population Statistics|url=https://www.clrsearch.com/Whitmore-Demographics/CA/96096/Population-Growth-and-Population-Statistics|publisher=CLR Choice, Inc.|date=2012|ref={{sfnRef|CLR Choice, Inc.}}}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://palocedrocommunitypark.org/ Palo Cedro Community Park Project]\n*[http://www.palocedrochamber.org/ Palo Cedro Chamber of Commerce]\n*[http://www.foothillcougars.com/ Foothill High School]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070707020131/http://www.shastalink.k12.ca.us/junction/index.htm Junction Elementary School District]\n*[http://www.topix.com/city/palo-cedro-ca Palo Cedro News]\n*[http://www.4palocedro.com Palo Cedro Real Estate and area information]\n*[http://www.inforedding.com/]\n{{Shasta County, California}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Shasta County, California]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Palo Cedro\n|settlement_type          = [[census-designated place]]\n|image_skyline            = Windmill Palo Cedro.jpg\n|imagesize                =\n|image_caption            = Windmill, Downtown Palo Cedro \n|image_seal               =\n|image_map                = Shasta_County_California_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Palo_Cedro_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location in [[Shasta County, California|Shasta County]] and the state of [[California]]\n|image_map1               =\n|mapsize1                 =\n|map_caption1             =\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|California}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in California|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Shasta County, California|Shasta]]\n|government_type          =\n|leader_title             =\n|leader_name              =\n|established_date         =\n<!-- Area------------------>\n|area_magnitude           =\n| unit_pref               =US\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>[https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt U.S. Census] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |date=2012-01-25 }}</ref>\n| area_total_sq_mi        = 3.754\n| area_land_sq_mi         = 3.679\n| area_water_sq_mi        = 0.075\n| area_total_km2          = 9.722\n| area_land_km2           = 9.528\n| area_water_km2          = 0.194\n| area_water_percent      = 2.00\n| area_note               =\n|elevation_ft             = 465\n|elevation_m              = 143\n|population_as_of         = 2010\n|population_footnotes     =\n|population_total         = 1269\n|population_metro         =\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[Pacific Time Zone|Pacific (PST)]]\n|utc_offset               = \u22128\n|coordinates              = {{coord|40|33|4|N|122|14|3|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST             = PDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = \u22127\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 96073\n|area_code                = [[Area code 530|530]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 06-55296\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0230275\n|footnotes                =\n|website                  =\n}}\n'''Palo Cedro''' (''Cedarwood'') is a [[census-designated place]] (CDP) in [[Shasta County, California|Shasta County]], [[California]], United States. The population was 1,269 at the 2010 census, up from 1,247 at the 2000 census. It is 8 miles (13&nbsp;km) east of [[Redding, California]].  The communities of [[Bella Vista, California|Bella Vista]] (pop. 2,781), [[Millville, California|Millville]] (pop. 727), [[Shingletown, California|Shingletown]] (pop. 2,283), [[Oak Run, California|Oak Run]] (pop. 880),{{sfn|Berkshire Hathaway Home Services}} [[Whitmore, California|Whitmore]] (pop. 999),{{sfn|CLR Choice, Inc.}} and [[Round Mountain, California|Round Mountain]] (pop. 155) lie within a 15-mile (24&nbsp;km) radius.\n\nOriginally, indigenous Native Americans lived in Northern California, including what is now Shasta County, prior to European American settlement. European American exploration of inland California started in 1769 and continued on into the 19th Century. Cow Creek, a Sacramento River tributary, that runs south through Palo Cedro, was a conduit for entrance into the [[Sacramento Valley]] by Hudson Bay Fur Company trappers including [[Alexander Roderick McLeod|Alexander McLeod]] (1829) and [[John Work (fur trader)|John Work]] (1832). The town is named after cedarwood trees originally indigenous to the area in the 19th Century.\n\nAs of the 2010 census, Palo Cedro has a population density of 338.1 people per square mile (130.5/km<sup>2</sup>). Award winning country musician [[Merle Haggard]] lived in Palo Cedro for decades until his death on April 6, 2016.\n\n==History==\n===Indigenous peoples===\n{{main|Indigenous peoples of California}}\n\nPrior to white settlement, various Indian tribes settled and inhabited Northern California.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} These tribes included the [[Wintu]], [[Patwin]]s, Nozi, [[Pit River Tribe|Pit Rivers]], Hat Creeks, [[Shasta people|Shastas]], [[Northern Paiute|Paiute]]s, and [[Modoc people|Modoc]] Indian tribes.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} The Wintus established their main camp on Cottonwood Creek.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} [[Penutian languages|Penutian]] Indian tribes on the [[Pacific coast]] or valley included the [[Maidu]], [[Miwok]], [[Ohlone|Constanoan]], [[Yokuts]], Yanas, and other divisions. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} Historians said that, in the lower 48 continental United States, California has the most native tribes and subdivisions of tribes and more different Indian languages.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}} The Wintus were the largest and most peaceful division that settled in Northern California and Oregon. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=6-9, 36}}\n\n===18th and 19th centuries===\n{{see|History of California before 1900|Alta California|California grizzly bears}}\nDuring the 18th Century, the first recorded Spanish (or any European) land entry and exploration of the present-day state of California, was the [[Portol\u00e1 expedition]], in 1769\u20131770, that led to the founding of [[Alta California]], reaching as far north as [[San Francisco Bay]].\n\nThe 19th Century launched many explorations by whites into California and its northern interior. In March 1812, the Russian-American Fur Company under [[Ivan Kuskov]] established a colony at [[Fort Ross, California|Fort Ross]] on the coast of what is now Sonoma County.{{sfn|''Fort Ross'' Establishment of the California Settlement 1998}} As early as 1817, Father [[Narciso Dur\u00e1n]], on an expedition sighted a snow capped mountain (Mount Shasta), that he called ''Jesus Maria'', from what is now the Marysville plains. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=11-12}} Three years later, in 1827, an expedition to the Klammath Mountains from the Coastal Range, by explorer [[Luis Antonio Arg\u00fcello|Luis Arg\u00fcello]] and company, sighted two \"twin\" mountains, believed to be Mount Shasta and Mount Lassen.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=11-12}} In 1826, Mount Shasta was seen by Hudson Bay fur trader Peter Skene Odgen.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=14}} In 1828, Mt. Shasta was seen by United States fur trapper [[Jedediah Smith]], whom he named ''Mt. Simpson''.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=13-14}} On April 11, 1828 Smith and his party traveled north and entered what is now called Shasta County, and proceeded to what is now called [[Burnt Ranch, California|Burnt Ranch]] in Trinity County.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=13-14}}\n[[File:John Work, Hudson's Bay Company officer, before 1861.jpg|left|thumb|120px|<center>'''John Work'''</center>]]\nThe earliest [[European Americans|European American]] history of Palo Cedro comes from the exploration of [[Hudson's Bay Company]] trapper [[Alexander Roderick McLeod|Alexander McLeod]] (c. 1782&nbsp;\u2013 11 June 1840) who sometime between March 26, 1829 and April 6, 1829, along with guide [[John Turner (fur trapper)|John Turner]], and a brigade of trappers, traveling through Mexican [[California]], started from the Pit River following the [[Cow Creek (Sacramento River tributary)|Cow Creek]] trail, and reached the Sacramento River.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} [[Cow Creek (Sacramento River tributary)|Cow Creek]] is Sacramento River tributary that runs through Palo Cedro and serves as its south eastern borderline. McLeod had been sent out earlier in January 1829 from Fort Vancouver to find the origins of a mythical [[Buenaventura River (legend)|Buenaventura River]].{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} After crossing the Sacramento River, McLeod explored and trapped in the [[Sacramento Valley]] as far South as present day Stockton. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} Upon his return with an abundant supply of furs, he camped on the west bank of the Sacramento River by present day [[Anderson, California|Anderson]] in December 1829. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} While attempting to cross the Cascades in winter, McLeod was met by a snow storm at the headwaters of the river named after him, ''McLeod River'' ([[McCloud River]]), he lost all his horses, was forced to cache his furs, and by snowshoe trek back to Vancouver, arriving on February 10, 1830. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}}{{efn|According to historian Rosena A. Giles, the name of the McCloud river was a misspelling of McLeod's original name, and confused by the name of Ross McCloud, a pioneer of the 1850's. In 1878, an unsuccessful attempt was made by C.C. Bush to have the California state legislature change the name of the river from ''McCloud'' to ''McLeod''.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} Frank & Chapel called the river ''McLeod''. {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}} Reading called the river ''McLoud''.  {{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=14-15}}}}\n[[File:74-LASSOING_A_GRIZZLEY.jpg|right|180px|thumb|'''Lassoing a Grizzley''' ''1873''<br>Canadian fur trapper John Work, in 1832, noted there were California grizzlies, in the area of what is now Palo Cedro. California grizzlies were hunted to extinction in the 1920s.]]\n\nIn 1832, another Hudson's Bay trapper [[John Work (fur trader)|John Work]] (c.1792-1861), searching for a route to connect the [[Columbia River]] to the [[Sacramento River]], reported in his journal traveling through Mexican California in with a group from the [[Hudson's Bay Company]] fur traders, staying east of the [[Siskiyou Mountains|Siskiyous]], bypassing [[Lassen Peak|Mt. Lassen]], along Cow Creek, through the areas now known as [[Millville, California|Millville]] and Palo Cedro, finding a way to the Sacramento Valley.{{sfnm|Owens|2002|1p=348|Giles|1949|2pp=15-16}}{{efn|Historian Rosena A. Giles said Work's party included 28 men, 22 women, and 44 children.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=15}}}} In the surrounding area, Work noted there were local Indians who lived in huts, in addition to various wildlife and numerous animals, including deer, elk, and grizzly bears.{{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=209-210}} Local Indian men gave Work and his men food. {{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=209-210}} Work called Cow Creek, ''Canoe River'', and his men chopped down pine trees to make canoes, camped near what is now called [[Anderson, California|Anderson]]. {{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=209-210, 216}}{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=15}} During their stay, while his men were making the canoes, Work said the Indians were weeping and lamenting and observed six fires were burning in the Indian camp. {{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=210-211}} Work later learned that the local Indian camp had been attacked and burned by another Indian raiding party, possibly the Shastas.{{sfn|Maloney|Work|1943|pp=210-211}} After trapping in the Sacramento Valley, work retraced his steps to the Pit River, and using the same route as McLeod had earlier used through Bartle's Gap, but without disaster, emerged from the mountains and was assisted back to Vancouver.{{sfn|Giles|1949|pp=15-16}}\n[[image:Carsonfremont.jpg|150px|thumb|left|John C. Fr\u00e9mont (seated right)<br>and his guide [[Kit Carson]].]]\nIn 1846, on his third expedition, [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] and his military party, followed the Cow Creek, Walla Walla Trail through what is now Shasta County, headed north to Klammath Lake area in Oregon.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=46}}{{efn|''Walla Walla'' or old ''Columbian'' are terms for the trail between Mount Shasta and Mount Lassen.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=12}}}} Fr\u00e9mont's guide for three federal expeditions was mountain man [[Kit Carson]].\n\nIn June 1850, U.S. Army Captain [[Nathaniel Lyon]], and his military party along with Colonel Freaner, left [[Pierson Barton Reading|Pierson Reading]]'s [[Rancho Buena Ventura]] following Fremont's route through the Cow Creek and Pit River.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=49}} Lyon had been sent from [[Benicia, California|Benicia]] by his government to avenge the death of Captain Warren. {{sfn|Giles|1949|p=49}}\n\nIn 1883, a United States post office was established for this area; at that time, the town was known as Albertson.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}} The name was changed to Roberts in 1885 and finally to Palo Cedro in 1893, meaning \"[[Cedrus|cedarwood]]\" in Spanish, after the cedar trees of the area.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}}\n\nIn 1891, T.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;H. Shannahan and Joe Enright bought {{convert|30|acre|ha}} of land from Lem Benton and had it divided into 12 lots.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}} The town never materialized or was developed, but the original cedar tree for which it was named was cut down.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}} School children since then planted cedar trees at the Junction School District yard.{{sfn|Giles|1949|p=194}}\n\nIn 1897, or shortly before, the [[California, Shasta and Eastern Railway|Anderson and Bella Vista Railroad]] was constructed by the Terry Lumber Company from [[Anderson, California|Anderson]] to [[Bella Vista, California|Bella Vista]], passing through Palo Cedro.  Miners used this railroad, as did the Terry Lumber Company at Bella Vista.  The train delivered groceries and mail to the villages along its route. It also had a passenger car.\n\n===20th and 21st centuries===\n{{see|History of California 1900 to present|California}}\nIn the early 1900s, the stage route went from [[Redding, California|Redding]] through Palo Cedro, [[Millville, California|Millville]], [[Oak Run, California|Oak Run]], and on to [[Fall River Mills, California|Fall River Mills]].\n\nPalo Cedro's first school house was located near the corner of Hillside Drive and Deschutes Road on the south side of town. Later it was moved to a site near the Grange Hall, on the north side of town. The school was located there until the \"new\" Junction School was built in 1960 on the south side of town.\n\nIn 1907 or thereabouts, Frank and Mary Love owned the Palo Cedro general store. The store was on the west side of the tracks and their house on the east.  A two-story house on the northeast corner of Deschutes Road and Old Forty-Four Drive may, at one time, have been a stopping place for stage drivers and travelers. Sarah Addington later owned the Palo Cedro store.  She was also the postmaster and handed the position down to her daughter, Mary Jones. She moved the post office next door into her home.\n\nJohn Gebauer has since owned the store. In the 1960s John moved to his new building on the south east side of Palo Cedro; it had several one-story spaces for commercial businesses. The largest business was the Palo Cedro Market. Gebauer's son John now operates it. The post office moved into a part of Gebauer's building. Mary Jones' assistants were her sisters. The next postmaster was Sylvia Metz. As she found the post office needed more space, it moved to a two-story building on the north side of Palo Cedro.\n\nThe first Grange Hall and Feed Store were constructed in the early 1930s, just off Deschutes Road on Old Highway 44.  The building was two stories with the meeting and/or dance hall upstairs. The dining room was downstairs in back and the feed store in front. This building burned down in the early 1940s and was quickly replaced with a one-story building, which is still in use in the 21st century. The feed store was built on the north side of Old Forty-Four Drive and is still there today.\n\nAs Palo Cedro continued to grow more services were needed, and the first independently owned pharmacy opened in August 1975.  Its first space was a remodelled auto body shop. To accommodate its growing business, it moved to the current location on the south side of Highway 44 off Deschutes Road. Palo Cedro Pharmacy has an eclectic mix of pictures, memorabilia, and antiques collected over the last 40 years showing how the town and pharmacy has changed over the years. The current Mayor of Palo Cedro is Carlos Zapata.\n\n==Geography==\nPalo Cedro is located at {{Coord|40|33|4|N|122|14|3|W|type:city}} (40.551091, \u2212122.234255)<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> at an elevation of 465&nbsp;ft (143 m) above sea level.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the CDP has a total area of {{convert|3.8|sqmi|km2}}, 98.00% of it land, and 2.00% of it water.\n\n===Climate===\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] system, Palo Cedro has a [[Mediterranean climate#Warm-summer Mediterranean climate|warm-summer Mediterranean climate]], abbreviated \"Csa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=692740&cityname=Palo+Cedro%2C+California%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Palo Cedro, California]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n===2010===\nThe [[2010 United States Census]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0655296|archive-url=https://archive.today/20140715032244/http://www.census.gov/2010census/popmap/ipmtext.php?fl=06:0655296|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 15, 2014|title=2010 Census Interactive Population Search: CA - Palo Cedro CDP|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|access-date=July 12, 2014}}</ref> reported that Palo Cedro had a population of 1,269. The [[population density]] was 338.1 people per square mile (130.5/km<sup>2</sup>). The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of Palo Cedro was 1,164 (91.7%) White, 7 (0.6%) African American, 24 (1.9%) Native American, 6 (0.5%) Asian, 1 (0.1%) Pacific Islander, 22 (1.7%) from other races, and 45 (3.5%) from two or more races.  Hispanic or Latino of any race were 74 persons (5.8%).\n\nThe Census reported that 1,260 people (99.3% of the population) lived in households, 4 (0.3%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 5 (0.4%) were institutionalized.\n\nThere were 474 households, out of which 153 (32.3%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 318 (67.1%) were [[marriage|opposite-sex married couples]] living together, 41 (8.6%) had a female householder with no husband present, 24 (5.1%) had a male householder with no wife present.  There were 18 (3.8%) [[POSSLQ|unmarried opposite-sex partnerships]], and 7 (1.5%) [[Domestic partnership|same-sex married couples or partnerships]]. 70 households (14.8%) were made up of individuals and 38 (8.0%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.66.  There were 383 [[Family (US Census)|families]] (80.8% of all households); the average family size was 2.89.\n\nThe population was spread out with 289 people (22.8%) under the age of 18, 74 people (5.8%) aged 18 to 24, 192 people (15.1%) aged 25 to 44, 429 people (33.8%) aged 45 to 64, and 285 people (22.5%) who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 48.3 years. For every 100 females, there were 96.4 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 95.6 males.\n\nThere were 504 housing units at an average density of 134.3 per square mile (51.8/km<sup>2</sup>), of which 411 (86.7%) were owner-occupied, and 63 (13.3%) were occupied by renters. The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.9%; the rental vacancy rate was 7.2%.  1,072 people (84.5% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 188 people (14.8%) lived in rental housing units.\n\n===2000===\nAs of the [[2000 United States Census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 1,247 people, 436 households, and 367 families residing in the CDP.  The [[population density]] was 330.1 people per square mile (127.4/km<sup>2</sup>).  There were 447 housing units at an average density of 118.3 per square mile (45.7/km<sup>2</sup>).  The [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census|racial makeup]] of the CDP was 93.10% White, 0.56% African American, 1.12% Native American, 1.52% Asian, 0.88% from other races, and 2.81% from two or more races. Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.57% of the population.\n\nThere were 436 households out of which 37.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 74.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.8% had a female householder with no husband present, and 15.6% were non-families. 13.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 5.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.85 and the average family size was 3.12.\n\nIn the CDP, the population was spread out with 27.7% under the age of 18, 6.7% from 18 to 24, 22.7% from 25 to 44, 28.7% from 45 to 64, and 14.2% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 41 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.8 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.8 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the CDP was $51,471, and the median income for a family was $60,385. Males had a median income of $47,232 versus $33,125 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the CDP was $23,419.  About 5.4% of families and 5.5% of the population were below the [[Poverty threshold|poverty line]], including 14.1% of those under age 18 and none of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Politics==\nIn the [[California State Legislature|state legislature]] Palo Cedro is located in {{Representative|casd|1|fmt=sdistrict}},<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://senate.ca.gov/senators |title=Senators |access-date=March 10, 2013  |publisher=State of California}}</ref> and {{Representative|caad|1|fmt=adistrict}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://assembly.ca.gov/assemblymembers |title=Members Assembly |access-date=March 2, 2013 |publisher=State of California}}</ref>\n\nFederally, Palo Cedro is in {{Representative|cacd|1|fmt=district}}.<ref>{{Cite GovTrack|CA|1|access-date=March 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n\n[[file:MerleHaggardJun09.jpg|thumb|right|180px|<center>'''Merle Haggard''' ''June 2009''</center>]]\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Merle Haggard]], country musician, lived in Palo Cedro for decades until his death on his 79th birthday (April 6, 2016).\n\n==Education==\n;Elementary Schools:\n*North Cow Creek School\n*Junction Elementary School\n*Chrysalis Charter School\n*Redding Christian School\n\n;Middle Schools\n*Junction Intermediate School\n*Saint Francis Middle School\n*Chrysalis Charter School\n*North Cow Creek School\n*Redding Christian School\n\n;High Schools\n*[[Foothill High School (Palo Cedro, California)|Foothill High School]] has an  API score of 817, making it one of the best public schools in northern California.\n*[[Bishop Quinn High School]]\n*Redding Christian School\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nImage:Mount_Lassen_Sunrise1.jpg|View from Palo Cedro of Sunrise over Mount Lassen (September 2007)\nImage:Windmill Palo Cedro.jpg|Windmill landmark in Palo Cedro shopping center (November 2007)\nImage:Church and Mt Lassen Palo Cedro.jpg|Local Church with Mount Lassen in the Background (November 2007)\nImage:Palo Cedro Fire Dept.jpg|Palo Cedro Fire Department (November 2007)\nImage:Junction_Middle_School.jpg|Junction Middle School (Thanksgiving Holiday 2007)\nImage:Foothill HS 01.jpg|Foothill High School (November 2007)\nImage:Deschutes_Road_From_Junction.jpg|Deschutes Road Looking North, From Junction Elementary School (September 2007)\nImage:Church of Jesus Christ Latter Day Saints.jpg|Palo Cedro Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (November 2007)\nImage:Palo_Cedro_Inn.jpg|The Palo Cedro Inn\u2014A Palo Cedro Landmark (November 2007)\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books and Journals===\n*{{cite book|title=''Fort Ross'' Establishment of the California Settlement|url=https://www.fortross.org/russian-american-company.htm|publisher=Fort Ross Interpretive Association (Fort Ross Conservancy)|date=1998|isbn=1-56540-355-X|ref={{sfnRef|''Fort Ross'' Establishment of the California Settlement 1998}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Giles|first=Rosena A.|title=Shasta County California A History|edition=California Centennial|publisher=Biobooks|location=[[Oakland, California|Oakland]]|date=1949|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Maloney|first1=Alice Bay|last2=Work|first2=John|title=Fur Brigade to the Bonaventura: John Work's California Expedition of 1832-33 for the Hudson's Bay Company|publisher=California Historical Society|journal=California Historical Society Quarterly|volume=22|number=3|date=September 1943|pages=193\u2013222|url=http://www.martinezbeavers.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Fur-Brigade-to-the-Bonaventura-John-Works-California-Expedition-of-1832-33-for-the-Hudsons-Bay-Company-Maloney-Work-Calif-Historical-Quarterly-Sept.-1943.pdf|format=PDF|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Owens|first=Kenneth N.|title=Riches for All: The California Gold Rush and the World|editor=Kenneth N. Owens|date=2002|chapter=Begun by Gold|publisher=University of Nebraska Press|location=[[Lincoln, Nebraska|Lincoln]]|isbn=0-8032-3570-4|ref=harv}}\n\n===Internet===\n* {{cite web|title=Oak Run 96069 Real Estate|url=https://www.berkshirehathawayhs.com/CA/Oak%20Run/96069|publisher=Berkshire Hathaway Home Services|date=2018|ref={{sfnRef|Berkshire Hathaway Home Services}}}}\n* {{cite web|title=Whitmore, CA 96096 Population Growth and Population Statistics|url=https://www.clrsearch.com/Whitmore-Demographics/CA/96096/Population-Growth-and-Population-Statistics|publisher=CLR Choice, Inc.|date=2012|ref={{sfnRef|CLR Choice, Inc.}}}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://palocedrocommunitypark.org/ Palo Cedro Community Park Project]\n*[http://www.palocedrochamber.org/ Palo Cedro Chamber of Commerce]\n*[http://www.foothillcougars.com/ Foothill High School]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070707020131/http://www.shastalink.k12.ca.us/junction/index.htm Junction Elementary School District]\n*[http://www.topix.com/city/palo-cedro-ca Palo Cedro News]\n*[http://www.4palocedro.com Palo Cedro Real Estate and area information]\n*[http://www.inforedding.com/]\n{{Shasta County, California}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Census-designated places in Shasta County, California]]\n[[Category:Census-designated places in California]]\n", "name_user": "Nonameknowitall", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Public knowledge)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palo_Cedro,_California"}
{"title_page": "Evo Morales", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Former Bolivian President and politician}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{spanish name|Morales|Ayma}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Evo Morales\n| image = File:Presidentes del Per\u00fa y Bolivia inauguran Encuentro Presidencial y III Gabinete Binacional Per\u00fa-Bolivia (36962597345) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Morales in 2017\n| order = 65th \n| office = President of Bolivia\n| alt = Morales looking to the side\n| vicepresident = [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]]\n| term_start = 22 January, 2006\n| term_end = 10 November, 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/20/el-mas-reconoce-la-sucesion-por-renuncia-abandono-de-funciones-de-evo-alvaro-238006.html|title=El MAS reconoce la sucesi\u00f3n por renuncia y abandono de funciones de Evo y \u00c1lvaro|website=Pagina Siete|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]]\n| successor = [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] <small>(''interim'')</small>\n| office1 = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_label1 = In role\n| term_start1 = January 14, 2019\n| term_end1 = November 10, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Salvador S\u00e1nchez Cer\u00e9n]]\n| successor1 = [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]]\n| office2 = [[President pro tempore of the Union of South American Nations|President pro tempore of UNASUR]]\n| term_label2 = In role\n| term_start2 = April 17, 2018\n| term_end2 = April 16, 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Mauricio Macri]]\n| successor2 = ''Vacant''{{Disputed inline|date=December 2019}}\n| office3 = Leader of the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]]\n| term_start3 = January 1, 1998\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = ''party established''\n| successor3 = \n| office4 = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly#Chamber of Deputies|Member of the Chamber of Deputies]]<br />for [[Cochabamba Department|Cochabamba]]\n| term_start4 = August 6, 1997\n| term_end4 = January 24, 2002\n| birth_name = Juan Evo Morales Ayma\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|10|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Isallavi]], Bolivia\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]]\n| children = 2\n| parents = Dionisio Morales Choque<br />Mar\u00eda Ayma Mamani\n| residence = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n| signature = Evo Morales signature.svg\n<!--Military service-->| nickname = \n| allegiance = {{flagicon|Bolivia}} Bolivia\n| branch = [[Image:Logo del Ej\u00e9rcito de Bolivia..jpg|22px]] [[Bolivian Army]]\n| serviceyears = 1977\u20131978\n| rank = \n| unit = [[Fourth Ingavi Cavalry Regiment]]\n| commands = \n| battles = \n| mawards = \n}}\n'''Juan Evo Morales Ayma'''  ({{IPA-es|\u02c8e\u03b2o mo\u02c8\u027eales}}; born October 26, 1959) is a [[Bolivia|Bolivian]] politician and former \n[[cocalero]] activist who served as the [[President of Bolivia]] from 2006 to 2019. Widely regarded as the country's first president to come from its [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] population,{{efn|Morales is described as the first indigenous president of Bolivia in academic studies of his presidency, such as those of Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian,{{sfn|Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|2008|p=180}} Webber,{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=1}} Philip and Panizza,{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=57}} and Farthing and Kohl,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=1}} as well as in press reports, such as those of [[BBC News]],<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> However, there have been challenges to this claim by critics who have asserted that Morales probably has some European ancestry, and thus on genetic grounds is technically ''[[mestizo]]'' rather than solely indigenous.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} Further, former president [[Enrique Pe\u00f1aranda]] was of substantially indigenous origin. Harten asserted that this argument was \"misguided[,] wrong[... and] above all irrelevant\" because regardless of his genetic makeup, the majority of Bolivians perceive Morales as being the first indigenous president.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} In Bolivian society, indigeneity is a fluid concept rooted in cultural identity;{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} for instance, many indigenous individuals that have settled in urban areas and abandoned their traditional rural customs have come to identify as ''mestizo''.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=22}} }} his administration focused on the implementation of [[leftist]] policies, poverty reduction, and combating the influence of the [[United States]] and multinational corporations in Bolivia. A [[socialist]], he is the head of the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] (MAS) party.\n\n<!--Early life and political activism-->\nBorn to an [[Aymara people|Aymara]] family of [[subsistence farmers]] in Isallawi, [[Orinoca Canton]], Morales undertook a basic education before mandatory military service, in 1978 moving to [[Chapare Province]]. Growing [[coca]] and becoming a trade unionist, he rose to prominence in the ''[[Unique Confederation of Rural Laborers of Bolivia|campesino]]'' (\"rural laborers\") union. In that capacity, he campaigned against U.S. and Bolivian attempts to [[coca eradication|eradicate coca]] as part of the [[War on Drugs]], denouncing these as an [[imperialist]] violation of indigenous Andean culture. His involvement in anti-government [[direct action]] protests resulted in multiple arrests. Morales entered electoral politics in 1995, became the leader of the MAS, and was elected to [[Bolivian National Congress, 1997\u20132002|Congress]] in 1997. Coupled with [[populist]] rhetoric, his campaign focused on issues affecting indigenous and poor communities, advocating land reform and the more equal redistribution of gas wealth. He gained increased visibility through the [[Cochabamba Water War]] and [[Bolivian gas conflict|gas conflict]]. In 2002, he was expelled from Congress for encouraging anti-government protesters, although he came second in [[2002 Bolivian general election|that year's presidential election]].\n\n<!--Presidency-->\n[[2005 Bolivian general election|Once elected in 2005]], Morales increased taxation on the hydrocarbon industry to bolster social spending and emphasized projects to combat illiteracy, poverty, racism, and sexism. Vocally criticizing [[neoliberalism]], Morales' government moved Bolivia towards a [[mixed economy]], reduced its dependence on the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]], and oversaw strong economic growth. Scaling back U.S. influence in the country, he built relationships with leftist governments in the Latin American [[pink tide]]\u2014especially [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]]'s Venezuela and [[Fidel Castro]]'s Cuba\u2014and signed Bolivia into the [[Bolivarian Alliance for the Americas]]. His administration opposed the right-wing autonomist demands of [[media luna|Bolivia's eastern provinces]], won [[2008 Bolivian vote of confidence referendum|a 2008 recall referendum]], and instituted a [[Constitution of Bolivia|new constitution]] that established Bolivia as a [[plurinationalism|plurinational state]]. [[2009 Bolivian general election|Re-elected in 2009]] and [[2014 Bolivian general election|2014]], he oversaw Bolivia's admission to the [[Bank of the South]] and [[Community of Latin American and Caribbean States]] although his popularity was dented by attempts to abolish presidential [[term limits]]. Following the disputed [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 general election]] and [[2019 Bolivian protests|the ensuing unrest]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|Morales agreed to military calls for his resignation]], after which he was granted [[Right of asylum|political asylum]], first in Mexico, then in Argentina. \n\n<!--Reception, legacy, and influence-->\nMorales was decorated with various international awards and received praise both for overseeing economic growth and for significantly reducing poverty and illiteracy in Bolivia. His supporters lauded him as a champion of [[indigenous rights]], [[anti-imperialism]], and [[environmentalism]]. He faced accusations that his defence of coca contributed to illegal [[cocaine]] production and that his calls for domestic protest represented [[sedition]] and [[terrorism]].\n\n==Early life and activism==\n===Childhood, education, and military service: 1959\u201378===\n\nMorales was born in the small rural village of Isallawi in [[Orinoca Canton]], part of western Bolivia's [[Oruro Department]], on October 26, 1959 to a family from the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] [[Aymara people]].<ref name=oct17bbc />{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=35|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=62}} One of seven children born to Dionisio Morales Choque and his wife Mar\u00eda Ayma Mamani,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/amp/entrega-modulo-educativo-maria-ayma-dice-nunca-influyo-nombramiento-obras-137307.html | title=Evo entrega modulo educativo \"Maria Ayma\" y dice que nunca influy\u00f3 en nombramiento de obras - Diario Pagina Siete | access-date=January 26, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904084711/https://www.paginasiete.bo/amp/entrega-modulo-educativo-maria-ayma-dice-nunca-influyo-nombramiento-obras-137307.html | archive-date=September 4, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> only he and two siblings, Esther and Hugo, survived past childhood.{{sfnm|1a1=Gutsch|1y=2006|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=32|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=35}} His mother almost died from a [[Postpartum hemorrhage|postpartum haemorrhage]] following his birth.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=35}} In keeping with Aymara custom, his father buried the [[placenta]] produced after his birth in a place specially chosen for the occasion.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=35}} His childhood home was a traditional [[adobe]] house,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=33}} and he grew up speaking the [[Aymara language]], although later commentators would remark that by the time he had become president he was no longer an entirely fluent speaker.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=33|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=7|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=63}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = Aymara ceremony copacabana 4.jpg\n| width1 = 200\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Fishing boat Lake Poopo.jpg\n| width2 = 198\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Aymara in traditional dress (left); [[Poop\u00f3 Lake]] was the dominant geographical feature around Morales's home village of Isallawi (right).{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=35}}\n}}\n\nMorales's family were farmers; from an early age, he helped them to plant and harvest crops and guard their herd of llamas and sheep, taking a homemade soccer ball to amuse himself.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=32|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=35}} As a toddler, he briefly attended Orinoca's preparatory school, and at five began schooling at the single-room primary school in Isallawi.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=33\u201334|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=36}} Aged 6, he spent six months in northern Argentina with his sister and father. There, Dionisio harvested sugar cane while Evo sold ice cream and briefly attended a Spanish-language school.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=34|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=36|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3pp=62\u201363}} As a child, he regularly traveled on foot to [[Arani province]] in [[Cochabamba]] with his father and their llamas, a journey lasting up to two weeks, in order to exchange salt and potatoes for maize and coca. {{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=33|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=36\u201337}} A big fan of soccer, at age 13 he organized a community soccer team with himself as team captain. Within two years, he was elected training coach for the whole region, and thus gained early experience in leadership.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=34|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=40}}\n\nAfter finishing primary education, Morales attended the Agrarian Humanistic Technical Institute of Orinoca (ITAHO), completing all but the final year.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=37}} His parents then sent him to study for a degree in [[Oruro, Bolivia|Oruro]]; although he did poorly academically, he finished all of his courses and exams by 1977, earning money on the side as a brick-maker, day laborer, baker and a trumpet player for the Royal Imperial Band. The latter position allowed him to travel across Bolivia.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=34\u201335|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=37|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=63}} At the end of his higher education he failed to collect his degree certificate.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=37}} Although interested in studying journalism, he did not pursue it as a profession.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=35|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=37}}\nMorales served his mandatory [[conscription|military service]] in the Bolivian army from 1977 to 1978. Initially signed up at the Centre for Instruction of Special Troops (CITE) in Cochabamba, he was sent into the Fourth Ingavi Cavalry Regiment and stationed at the army headquarters in the Bolivian capital [[La Paz]].{{sfnm|1a1=Blackwell|1y=2002|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=35|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=37}} These two years were one of Bolivia's politically most unstable periods, with five presidents and two military coups, led by General [[Juan Pereda]] and General [[David Padilla]] respectively; under the latter's regime, Morales was stationed as a guard at the ''[[Palacio Quemado]]'' (Presidential Palace).{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=37\u201338}}\n\n===Early ''cocalero'' activism: 1978\u201383===\nFollowing his military service, Morales returned to his family, who had escaped the agricultural devastation of 1980's ''[[El Ni\u00f1o-Southern Oscillation|El Ni\u00f1o]]'' storm cycle by relocating to the Tropics of [[Cochabamba]] in the eastern lowlands.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=35}} Setting up home in the town of Villa 14 de Septiembre, [[Chapare Province|El Chapare]], using a loan from Morales's maternal uncle, the family cleared a plot of land in the forest to grow rice, oranges, grapefruit, papaya, bananas and later on [[coca]].{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=36|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=39}} It was here that Morales learned to speak [[Quechua languages|Quechua]], the indigenous local language.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=63}} The arrival of the Morales family was a part of a much wider migration to the region; in 1981 El Chapare's population was 40,000 but by 1988 it had risen to 215,000. Many Bolivians hoped to set up farms where they could earn a living growing coca, which was experiencing a steady rise in price and which could be cultivated up to four times a year; a traditional medicinal and ritual substance in Andean culture, it was also sold abroad as the key ingredient in [[cocaine]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=39}} Morales joined the local soccer team, before founding his own team, New Horizon, which proved victorious at the August 2 Central Tournament.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=39}} The El Chapare region remained special to Morales for many years to come; during his presidency he often talked of it in speeches and regularly visited.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=39}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Folha de coca.jpg\n| width1 = 200\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Mate de coca Peru.jpg\n| width2 = 198\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer =  Morales policy was \"Coca Yes, Cocaine No\". A Bolivian man holding a coca leaf, (left); [[Coca tea]], a traditional Andean [[infusion]] (right).\n}}\nIn El Chapare, Morales joined a trade union of ''[[cocalero]]s'' (coca growers), being appointed local Secretary of Sports. Organizing soccer tournaments, among union members he earned the nickname of \"the young ball player\" because of his tendency to organize matches during meeting recesses.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=39}} Influenced in joining the union by wider events, in 1980 the far-right General [[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza]] had seized power in a military coup, banning other political parties and declaring himself president; for Morales, a \"foundational event in his relationship with politics\" occurred in 1981, when a ''campesino'' (coca grower) was accused of cocaine trafficking by soldiers, beaten up, and burned to death.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=40\u201341}} In 1982 the leftist [[Hern\u00e1n Siles Zuazo]] and the [[Democratic and Popular Union]] (''Unidad Democr\u00e1tica y Popular'' \u2013 UDP) took power in [[representative democracy|representative democratic]] elections, before implementing [[neoliberalism|neoliberal capitalist]] reforms and privatizing much of the state sector with US support; hyperinflation came under control, but unemployment rose to 25%.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=40\u201341|2a1=Philip|2a2=Panizza|2y=2011|2pp=76&ndash;77}} Becoming increasingly active in the union, from 1982 to 1983, Morales served as the General Secretary of his local San Francisco syndicate.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}} However, in 1983, Morales's father Dionisio died, and although he missed the funeral he temporarily retreated from his union work to organize his father's affairs.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=40\u201341, 57\u201358}}\n\nFighting their [[War on Drugs]], the U.S. government hoped to stem the cocaine trade by preventing the production of coca; they pressured the Bolivian government to eradicate it, sending troops to Bolivia to aid the operation.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=41}} Bolivian troops would burn coca crops and in many cases beat up coca growers who challenged them.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=109}} Angered by this, Morales returned to ''cocalero'' campaigning; like many of his comrades, he refused the US$2,500 compensation offered by the government for each acre of coca he eradicated. Deeply embedded in Bolivian culture, the ''campesinos'' had an ancestral relationship with coca and did not want to lose their most profitable means of subsistence. For them, it was an issue of national sovereignty, with the U.S. viewed as [[imperialism|imperalists]]; activists regularly proclaimed \"Long live coca! Death to the Yankees!\" (\"''Causachun coca! Wa\u00f1uchun yanquis!''\").{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}}\n\n===General Secretary of the ''Cocalero'' Union: 1984\u201394===\n\nFrom 1984 to 1985 Morales served as Secretary of Records for the movement,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}} and in 1985 he became General Secretary of the August Second Headquarters.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}}\nFrom 1984 to 1991 the ''sindicatos'' embarked on a series of protests against the forced eradication of coca by occupying local government offices, setting up roadblocks, going on hunger strike, and organizing mass marches and demonstrations.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=42|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=109}} Morales was personally involved in this direct activism and in 1984 was present at a roadblock where 3 ''campesinos'' were killed.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=43}} In 1988, Morales was elected to the position of Executive Secretary of the Federation of the Tropics.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}} In 1989 he spoke at a one-year commemoratory event of the [[Villa Tunari massacre]] in which 11 coca farmers had been killed by agents of the [[UMOPAR|Rural Area Mobile Patrol Unit]] (''Unidad M\u00f3vil Policial para \u00c1reas Rurales'' \u2013 UMOPAR).{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=43}} The following day, UMOPAR agents beat Morales up, leaving him in the mountains to die, but he was rescued by other union members.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=43, 65}} To combat this violence, Morales concluded that an armed ''cocalero'' militia could launch a [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla war]] against the government, but he was soon persuaded on an electoral path to change instead.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=43\u201344, 49}} In 1992, he made various international trips to champion the ''cocalero'' cause, speaking at a conference in Cuba,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=52}} and also traveling to Canada, during which he learned of his mother's death.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=58}}\n\n[[File:Banner of the Qulla Suyu.svg|147px|left|thumb|The [[Wiphala]], flag of the Aymara.]]\n\nIn his speeches, Morales presented the coca leaf as a symbol of Andean culture that was under threat from the imperialist oppression of the U.S. In his view, the U.S. should deal with their domestic cocaine abuse problems without interfering in Bolivia, arguing that they had no right trying to eliminate coca, a legitimate product with many uses which played a rich role in Andean culture.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=74\u201377}} In a speech on this issue, Morales told reporters \"I am not a drug trafficker. I am a coca grower. I cultivate coca leaf, which is a natural product. I do not refine (it into) cocaine, and neither cocaine nor drugs have ever been part of the Andean culture.\"<ref name=\"BBC bio\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Bolivia's President Evo Morales |date=October 13, 2014 |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12166905 |access-date=June 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012080954/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12166905 |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On another, he asserted that \"We produce our coca, we bring it to the main markets, we sell it and that's where our responsibility ends.\"{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=44}}\n\nMorales presented the coca growers as victims of a wealthy, urban social elite who had bowed to U.S. pressure by implementing neoliberal economic reforms.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=74\u201377}} He argued that these reforms were to the detriment of Bolivia's majority, and thus the country's representative democratic system of governance failed to reflect the true democratic will of the majority.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=74\u201377}} This situation was exacerbated following [[1993 Bolivian general election|the 1993 general election]] when the centrist [[Revolutionary Nationalist Movement]] (''Movimiento Nacionalista Revolucionario'' \u2013 MNR) won the election and [[Gonzalo S\u00e1nchez de Lozada]] became President. He adopted a policy of \"[[Shock therapy (economics)|shock therapy]]\", implementing economic liberalization and widescale privatization of state-owned assets.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=97\u201399}} S\u00e1nchez also agreed with the U.S. DEA to relaunch its offensive against the Bolivian coca growers, committing Bolivia to eradicating {{convert|12500|acre|ha}} of coca by March 1994 in exchange for $20 million worth of US aid, something Morales claimed would be opposed by the cocalero movement.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=44\u201345}}\n\nIn August 1994 Morales was arrested; reporters present at the scene witnessed him being beaten and accosted with racial slurs by civil agents. Accused of sedition, in jail he began a dry hunger strike to protest his arrest.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=45}} The following day, 3000 ''campesinos'' began a {{convert|360|mi|km|adj=on}} march from [[Villa Tunari]] to La Paz. Morales would be freed on September 7, and soon joined the march, which arrived at its destination on September 19, where they covered the city with political graffiti.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=45\u201347}} He was again arrested in April 1995 during a sting operation that rounded up those at a meeting of the Andean Council of Coca Producers that he was chairing on the shores of Lake Titicaca. Accusing the group of plotting a coup with the aid of Colombia's [[FARC]] and Peru's [[Shining Path]], a number of his comrades were tortured, although no evidence of a coup was brought forth and he was freed within a week.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=47}} He proceeded to Argentina to attend a seminar on liberation struggles.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=47\u201349}}\n\n==Political rise==\n===The ASP, IPSP, and MAS: 1995\u201399===\nMembers of the ''sindicato'' social movement first suggested a move into the political arena in 1986. This was controversial, with many fearing that politicians would co-opt the movement for personal gain.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=83}} Morales began supporting the formation of a political wing in 1989, although a consensus in favor of its formation only emerged in 1993.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} On March 27, 1995, at the 7th Congress of the [[Unique Confederation of Rural Laborers of Bolivia]] (''Confederaci\u00f3n Sindical \u00danica de Trabajadores Campesinos de Bolivia'' \u2013 CSUTCB), a \"political instrument\" (a term employed over \"political party\") was formed, named the [[Assembly for the Sovereignty of the Peoples]] (''Asamblea por la Sobern\u00eda de los Pueblos'' \u2013 ASP).{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=84|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}} At the ASP's 1st Congress, the CSUTCB participated alongside three other Bolivian unions, representing miners, peasants and indigenous peoples.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} In 1996, Morales was appointed chairman of the Committee of the Six Federations of the Tropics of Cochabamba, a position that he retained until 2006.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=79}}\n\nBolivia's [[National Electoral Court of Bolivia|National Electoral Court]] (''Corte Nacional Electoral'' \u2013 CNE) refused to recognize the ASP, citing minor procedural infringements.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} The coca activists circumvented this problem by running under the banner of the [[United Left (Bolivia)|United Left]] (IU), a coalition of leftist parties headed by the [[Communist Party of Bolivia]] (''Partido Comunista Boliviano'' \u2013 PCB).{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=24|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=79|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=84|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=60}} They won landslide victories in those areas which were local strongholds of the movement, producing 11 mayors and 49 municipal councilors.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} Morales was elected to the Chamber of Deputies in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|National Congress]] as a representative for El Chapare, having secured 70.1% of the local vote.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=79}} In the [[1997 Bolivian legislative election|national elections of 1997]], the IU/ASP gained four seats in Congress, obtaining 3.7% of the national vote, with this rising to 17.5% in the department of Cochabamba.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=85}} The election resulted in the establishment of a coalition government led by the right-wing [[Nationalist Democratic Action]] (''Acci\u00f3n Democr\u00e1tica Nacionalista'' \u2013 ADN), with [[Hugo Banzer]] as President; Morales lambasted him as \"the worst politician in Bolivian history\".{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=79\u201380}}\n\n[[File:MAS XVI Anniversary Celebration.jpg|thumb|MAS-IPSP partisans celebrate the 16th anniversary of the IPSP party's founding in [[Sacaba]], [[Cochabamba Department|Cochabamba]].]]\nRising electoral success was accompanied by factional in-fighting, with a leadership contest emerging in the ASP between the incumbent [[Alejo V\u00e9liz]] and Morales, who had the electoral backing of the social movement's bases.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=85}} The conflict led to a schism, with Morales and his supporters splitting to form their own party, the Political Instrument for the Sovereignty of the Peoples (''Instrumento Pol\u00edtico por la Soberan\u00eda de los Pueblos'' \u2013 IPSP).{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=85|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}} The movement's bases defected ''en masse'' to the IPSP, leaving the ASP to crumble and V\u00e9liz to join the center-right [[New Republican Force]] (''Nueva Fuerza Republicana'' \u2013 NFR), for which Morales denounced him as a traitor to the ''cocalero'' cause.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=86}} Continuing his activism, in 1998 Morales led another ''cocalero'' march from El Chapare to la Paz,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=81}} and came under increasing criticism from the government, who repeatedly accused him of being involved in the cocaine trade and mocked him for how he spoke and his lack of education.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=81\u201382}}\n\nMorales came to an agreement with [[David A\u00f1ez Pedraza]], the leader of a defunct yet still registered party named the Movement for Socialism (MAS); under this agreement, Morales and the Six Federaci\u00f3nes could take over the party name, with Pendraza stipulating the condition that they must maintain its own acronym, name and colors. Thus the defunct right wing MAS became the flourishing left wing vehicle for the coca activist movement known as the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism \u2013 Political Instrument for the Sovereignty of the Peoples]].{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=86|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}} The MAS would come to be described as \"an indigenous-based political party that calls for the nationalization of industry, legalization of the coca leaf ... and fairer distribution of national resources.\"<ref name=\"In these times\">{{cite news | date=December 18, 2005 | title=Evo Morales Has Plans for Bolivia | author=America Vera-Zavala | work=In These Times | url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/site/main/article/2438/ |accessdate=February 7, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303110107/http://inthesetimes.com/article/2438 |archivedate=March 3, 2015 }}</ref> The party lacked the finance available to the mainstream parties, and so relied largely on the work of volunteers in order to operate.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=89\u201390|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=87}} It was not structured like other political parties, instead operating as the political wing of the social movement, with all tiers in the movement involved in decision making; this form of organisation would continue until 2004.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=89\u201390}}\nIn the [[1999 Bolivian municipal elections|December 1999 municipal elections]], the MAS secured 79 municipal council seats and 10 mayoral positions, gaining 3.27% of the national vote, although 70% of the vote in Cochabamba.{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=86|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}}\n\n===Cochabamba protests: 2000\u201302===\nIn 2000, the Tunari Waters corporation doubled the price at which they sold water to Bolivian consumers, resulting in a backlash from leftist activist groups, including the ''cocaleros''. Activists clashed with police and armed forces, in what was dubbed \"[[2000 Cochabamba protests|the Water War]]\", resulting in 6 dead and 175 wounded. Responding to the violence, the government removed the contract from Tunari and placed the utility under cooperative control.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=82\u201383|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=112\u2013118|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=11}} In ensuing years further violent protests broke out over a range of issues, resulting in more deaths both among activists and law enforcement. Much of this unrest was connected with the widespread opposition to economic liberalization across Bolivian society, with a common perception that it only benefited a small minority.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=107, 117}}\n\nIn the Andean High Plateau, a ''cocalero'' group launched a guerrilla uprising under the leadership of [[Felipe Quispe]]; an ethnic separatist, he and Morales disliked each other, with Quispe considering Morales to be a traitor and an opportunist for his willingness to cooperate with [[White Bolivians]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=83\u201384}}\nMorales had not taken a leading role in these protests, but did use them to get across his message that the MAS was not a single-issue party, and that rather than simply fighting for the rights of the ''cocalero'' it was arguing for structural change to the political system and a redefinition of citizenship in Bolivia.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=126}}\n[[File:Evomorales.jpg|left|thumb|Evo Morales (right) with French labor union leader [[Jos\u00e9 Bov\u00e9]] in 2002]]\nIn August 2001, Banzer resigned due to terminal illness, and [[Jorge Quiroga]] took over as President.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=84}} Under U.S. pressure, Quiroga sought to have Morales expelled from Congress. To do so, he claimed that Morales's inflammatory language had caused the deaths of two police officers in [[Sacaba]] near Cochabamba, however was unable to provide any evidence of Morales's culpability. 140 deputies voted for Morales's expulsion, which came about in 2002. Morales asserted that it \"was a trial against Aymara and Quechas\", {{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=84\u201385}} while MAS activists interpreted it as evidence of the pseudo-democratic credentials of the political class.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=117}}\n\nThe MAS gained increasing popularity as a [[protest party]], relying largely on widespread dissatisfaction with the existing mainstream political parties among Bolivians living in rural and poor urban areas.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=95\u201396}} Morales recognized this, and much of his discourse focused on differentiating the MAS from the traditional political class.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=102}} Their campaign was successful, and in the [[2002 Bolivian presidential election|2002 presidential election]] the MAS gained 20.94% of the national vote, becoming Bolivia's second largest party, being only 1.5% behind the victorious MNR, whose candidate, [[Gonzalo S\u00e1nchez de Lozada]], became President.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=149|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=90|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=87|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=63|5a1=Farthing|5a2=Kohl|5y=2014|5pp=11\u201312}} They won 8 seats in the Senate and 27 in the Chamber of Deputies.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=87}} Now the leader of the [[Opposition (parliamentary)|political opposition]], Morales focused on criticising government policies rather than outlining alternatives. He had several unconstructive meetings with Lozada, but met with Venezuela's [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] for the first time.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=94-96}}\n\nBolivia's U.S. embassy had become publicly highly critical of Morales; just prior to the election, the U.S. ambassador to Bolivia [[Manuel Rocha]] issued a statement declaring that U.S. aid to Bolivia would be cut if MAS won the election. However, [[exit poll]]s revealed that Rocha's comments had served to increase support for Morales.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=86\u201387|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=158|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=87}} Following the election, the U.S. embassy maintained this critical stance, characterising Morales as a criminal and encouraging Bolivia's traditional parties to sign a broad agreement to oppose the MAS; Morales himself began alleging that the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] was plotting to assassinate him.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=95, 98|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=159}}\n\n===Rise to prominence: 2003\u201305===\n[[File:Evo Morales y Garcia Linera en El Potosi.jpg|thumb|right|Morales with his Vice Presidential running mate, \u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera, in 2005]]\n\nIn 2003, the [[Bolivian gas conflict]] broke out as activists \u2013 including coca growers \u2013 protested against the privatization of the country's natural gas supply and its sale to U.S. companies below the market value. Activists blocked off the road into La Paz, resulting in clashes with police. 80 were killed and 411 injured, among them officers, activists, and civilians, including children.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1pp=164\u2013167|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=99\u2013103|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3pp=118\u2013124}} Morales did not take an active role in the conflict, instead traveling to Libya and Switzerland, there describing the uprising as a \"peaceful revolution in progress\".{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=100}} The government accused Morales and the MAS of using the protests to overthrow Bolivia's parliamentary democracy with the aid of organized crime, [[FARC]], and the [[Far-left politics|far-left]] governments of Venezuela, Cuba, and Libya.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=122\u2013123}}\n\nMorales led calls for President S\u00e1nchez de Lozada to step down over the death toll, gaining widespread support from the MAS, other activist groups, and the middle classes; with pressure building, S\u00e1nchez resigned and fled to [[Miami]], [[Florida]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=167|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=101\u2013103|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3pp=122\u2013124}} He was replaced by [[Carlos Mesa]], who tried to strike a balance between U.S. and cocalero demands, but whom Morales mistrusted.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=167|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=137\u2013139|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=80}} In November, Morales spent 24 hours with Cuban President [[Fidel Castro]] in [[Havana]],{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=103\u2013104}} and then met Argentinian President [[Nestor Kirchner]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=138}} In the 2004 municipal election, the MAS became the country's largest national party, with 28.6% of all councilors in Bolivia. However, they had failed to win the mayoralty in any big cities, reflecting their inability to gain widespread support among the urban middle-classes.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=142|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=88}} In Bolivia's wealthy [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz]] region, a strong movement for autonomy had developed under the leadership of the Pro Santa Cruz Committee (''Comite Pro Santa Cruz''). Favorable to neoliberal economics and strongly critical of the cocaleros, they considered armed insurrection to secede from Bolivia should MAS take power.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=141\u2013142}}\n\nIn March 2005, Mesa resigned, citing the pressure of Morales and the cocalero road blocks and riots.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=175|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=142\u2013145|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=14}} Amid fears of civil war,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=146}} [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] became President of a [[transitional government]], preparing Bolivia for a [[2005 Bolivian presidential election|general election in December 2005]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=175|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=147}} Hiring the Peruvian Walter Ch\u00e1vez as its campaign manager, the MAS electoral campaign was based on [[Salvador Allende]]'s successful campaign in the [[1970 Chilean presidential election]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=148\u2013149}} Measures were implemented to institutionalize the party structure, giving it greater independence from the social movement; this was done to allow Morales and other MAS leaders to respond quickly to new developments without the lengthy process of consulting the bases, and to present a more moderate image away from the bases' radicalism.{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1pp=140, 151|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=68}} Although he had initially hoped for a female running mate, Morales eventually chose Marxist intellectual [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] as his Vice Presidential candidate,{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1pp=179\u2013180|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=150\u2013151|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=88|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=64}} with some Bolivian press speculating as to a romantic relationship between the two.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=139}} MAS' primary opponent was [[Jorge Quiroga]] and his center-right [[Social and Democratic Power]], whose campaign was centered in Santa Cruz and which advocated continued neo-liberal reform; Quiroga accused Morales of promoting the legalization of cocaine and being a [[puppet state|puppet]] for Venezuela.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=177|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=152}}\n\nWith a turnout of 84.5%, the election saw Morales gain 53.7% of the vote, while Quiroga came second with 28.6%; Morales's was the first victory with an [[absolute majority]] in Bolivia for 40 years.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=178|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=155\u2013158|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=88|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=50}} Given that he was the sixth self-described leftist president to be elected in Latin America since 1998, his victory was identified as part of the broader regional [[pink tide]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=1|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=2|3a1=Pearce|3y=2011|3p=xv}} Becoming [[president elect]], Morales was widely described as Bolivia's first indigenous leader, at a time when around 62% of the population identified as indigenous; political analysts therefore drew comparisons with the election of [[Nelson Mandela]] to the [[1994 South African general election|South African Presidency in 1994]].{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1pp=88\u201389|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=1, 70}} This resulted in widespread excitement among the approximately 40 million indigenous people in the Americas, particularly those of Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=1\u20132}} However, his election caused concern among the country's wealthy and landowning classes, who feared state expropriation and nationalisation of their property, as well as far-right groups, who claimed it would spark a [[race war]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=1\u20132}} He traveled to Cuba to spend time with Castro, before going to Venezuela, and then on tour to Europe, China, and South Africa; significantly, he avoided the U.S.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=156\u2013157|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=1}} In January 2006, Morales attended an indigenous spiritual ceremony at [[Tiwanaku]] where he was crowned [[Apu Mallku]] (''Supreme Leader'') of the Aymara, receiving gifts from indigenous peoples across Latin America. He thanked the goddess [[Pachamama]] for his victory and proclaimed that \"With the unity of the people, we're going to end the colonial state and the neo-liberal model.\"{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=117\u2013118|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=159|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=35}}\n\n==Presidency==\n{{main|Presidency of Evo Morales}}\n\n===First presidential term: 2006\u201309===\n\n{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=In the world there are large and small countries, rich countries and poor countries, but we are equal in one thing, which is our right to dignity and sovereignty.|source=\u2014 Evo Morales, Inaugural Speech, 22 January 2006.{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1p=133|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=161}} }}\n\nMorales's inauguration took place on January 22 in La Paz. It was attended by various heads of state, including Argentina's Kirchner, Venezuela's Ch\u00e1vez, Brazil's [[Lula da Silva]], and Chile's [[Ricardo Lagos]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=160}} Morales wore an Andeanized suit designed by fashion designer [[Beatriz Canedo Pati\u00f1o]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gutsch|1y=2006|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=158}} and gave a speech that included a minute silence in memory of cocaleros and indigenous activists killed in the struggle.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=160}} He condemned Bolivia's former \"colonial\" regimes, likening them to [[South Africa under apartheid]] and stating that the MAS' election would lead to a \"refoundation\" of the country, a term that the MAS consistently used over \"revolution\".{{sfn|Dunkerley|2007|p=146}} Morales repeated these views in his convocation of the Constituent Assembly.{{sfn|Dunkerley|2007|pp=146\u2013147}}\n\nIn taking office, Morales emphasized nationalism, anti-imperialism, and anti-neoliberalism, although did not initially refer to his administration as socialist.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=214\u2013215}} He immediately reduced both his own presidential wage and that of his ministers by 57% to $1,875 a month, also urging members of Congress to do the same.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=195|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=179|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3pp=35\u201336}}{{sfn|Gutsch|2006}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivian president slashes salary for public schools |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-01-28-morales-salary_x.htm |date=January 28, 2006 |website=USA Today |accessdate=January 5, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228201501/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-01-28-morales-salary_x.htm |archivedate=December 28, 2013 }}</ref> Morales gathered together a largely inexperienced [[Cabinet of Bolivia|cabinet]] made up of indigenous activists and leftist intellectuals,{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1p=134|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=195|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3pp=179\u2013180}} although over the first three years of government there was a rapid turnover in the cabinet as Morales replaced many of the indigenous members with trained middle-class leftist politicians.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=58}} By 2012 only 3 of the 20 cabinet members identified as indigenous.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=65}}\n\n====Economic program====\nAt Morales's election, Bolivia was South America's poorest nation.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=99}} Morales's government did not initiate fundamental change to Bolivia's economic structure,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=79}} and in their National Development Plan (PDN) for 2006\u201310, adhered largely to the country's previous liberal economic model.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=192}} Bolivia's economy was based largely on the extraction of [[natural resources]], with the nation having South America's second largest reserves of natural gas.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1pp=77\u201378|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=81}} As per his election pledge, Morales took increasing state control of this [[hydrocarbon]] industry with Supreme Decree 2870; previously, corporations paid 18% of their profits to the state, but Morales symbolically reversed this, so that 82% of profits went to the state and 18% to the companies. The oil companies threatened to take the case to the international courts or cease operating in Bolivia, but ultimately relented. Thus, where Bolivia had received $173 million from hydrocarbon extraction in 2002, by 2006 they received $1.3 billion.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=199\u2013203|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=180\u2013181|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3pp=80\u201381}} Although not technically a form of nationalization, Morales and his government referred to it as such, resulting in criticism from sectors of the Bolivian left.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=39}} In June 2006, Morales announced his desire to nationalize mining, electricity, telephones, and railroads, and in February 2007 nationalized the [[Vinto]] metallurgy plant, refusing to compensate [[Glencore]], which the government asserted had obtained the contract illegally.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=203\u2013204|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=74\u201375}} Although the FSTMB miners' federation called for the government to nationalize the mines, the government did not do so, instead stating that any transnational corporations operating in Bolivia legally would not be expropriated.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=107}}\n\n[[File:Morales 20060113 02.jpg|thumb|left|Evo Morales in 2006]]\n\nUnder Morales, Bolivia experienced unprecedented economic strength, resulting in the increase in value of its currency, the [[boliviano]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=85}} His first year in office ended with no [[fiscal deficit]]; the first time this had happened in Bolivia for 30 years,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=107}} while during the global [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]] it maintained some of the world's highest levels of economic growth.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=87}} Such economic strength led to a nationwide boom in construction,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=85}} and allowed the state to build up strong financial reserves.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=85}} Although the levels of social spending were increased, they remained relatively conservative, with a major priority being placed on constructing paved roads, as well as community spaces such as soccer fields and union buildings.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=198|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=85, 87}} In particular, the government focused on rural infrastructure improvement, to bring roads, running water, and electricity to areas that lacked them.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=98}}\n\nThe government's stated intention was to reduce Bolivia's most acute poverty levels from 35% to 27% of the population, and moderate poverty levels from 58.9% to 49% over five years.{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1pp=133\u2013134|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=205\u2013206}}\nThe welfare state was expanded, as characterized by the introduction of non-contributory old-age pensions and payments to mothers provided their babies are taken for health checks and that their children attend school. Hundreds of free tractors were also handed out. The prices of gas and many foodstuffs were controlled, and local food producers were made to sell in the local market rather than export. A new state-owned body was also set up to distribute food at subsidized prices. All these measures helped to curb inflation, while the economy grew (partly because of rising public spending), accompanied by stronger public finances which brought economic stability.<ref name=\"The explosive apex of Evo's power\">{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/node/15065929 |website=The Economist |title=The explosive apex of Evo's power |date=December 10, 2009 |accessdate=January 5, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406092712/http://www.economist.com/node/15065929 |archivedate=April 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring Morales's first term, Bolivia broke free of the domination of the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) which had characterized previous regimes by refusing their financial aid and connected regulations.{{clarify|date=June 2017}}{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2011|1p=145|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=73}} In May 2007, it became the world's first country to withdraw from the [[International Center for the Settlement of Investment Disputes]], with Morales asserting that the institution had consistently favored multinational corporations in its judgments; Bolivia's lead was followed by other Latin American nations.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=73}} Despite being encouraged to do so by the U.S., Bolivia refused to join the [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]], deeming it a form of U.S. imperialism.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=162}}\n\nA major dilemma faced by Morales's administration was between the desire to expand extractive industries in order to fund social programs and provide employment, and to protect the country's environment from the pollution caused by those industries.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=91}} Although his government professed an environmentalist ethos, expanding environmental monitoring and becoming a leader in the voluntary [[Forest Stewardship Council]], Bolivia continued to witness rapid deforestation for agriculture and illegal logging.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=91\u201392}}\nEconomists on both the left and right expressed concern over the government's lack of economic diversification.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=87}}\nMany Bolivians opined that Morales's government had failed to bring about sufficient job creation.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=79}}\n\n====ALBA and international appearances====\n[[File:F\u00f3rum Social Mundial 2008 - AL.jpg|thumb|Morales with regional allies, at the F\u00f3rum Social Mundial for Latin America: President of Paraguay [[Fernando Lugo|Lugo]], President of Brasil [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula]], President of Equador [[Rafael Correa|Correa]] and President of Venezuela [[Hugo Chavez|Chavez]].]]\n\nMorales's administration sought strong links with the far-left governments of Cuba and Venezuela.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2011|1p=63|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=40|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=75}} In April 2005 Morales traveled to [[Havana]] for knee surgery, there meeting with the two nations' presidents, Castro and Ch\u00e1vez.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=70}} In April 2006, Bolivia agreed to join Cuba and Venezuela in founding the [[Bolivarian Alliance for the Americas|Bolivarian Alternative for the Americas]] (ALBA), with Morales attending ALBA's conference in May, at which they initiated with a Peoples' Trade Agreement (PTA).{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=70|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=41|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=75}} Meanwhile, his administration became \"the least US-friendly government in Bolivian history\".{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=160}} In September Morales visited the U.S. for the first time to attend the [[UN General Assembly]], where he gave a speech condemning U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] as a terrorist for launching the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq War]], and called for the [[United Nations Headquarters|UN Headquarters]] to be moved out of the country. In the U.S., he met with former presidents [[Bill Clinton]] and [[Jimmy Carter]] and with [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Native American groups]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=180\u2013181, 187\u2013189}} Relations were further strained between the two nations when in December Morales issued a Supreme Decree requiring all U.S. citizens visiting Bolivia to have a visa.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=165}} His government also refused to grant legal immunity to U.S. soldiers in Bolivia; hence the U.S. cut back their military support to the country by 96%.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=162}}\n\nIn December 2006, he attended the first [[South\u2013South cooperation|South-South conference]] in [[Abuja]], Nigeria, there meeting Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]], whose government had recently awarded Morales the [[Al-Gaddafi International Prize for Human Rights]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=58\u201361}} Morales proceeded straight to Havana for a conference celebrating Castro's life, where he gave a speech arguing for stronger links between Latin America and the Middle East to combat U.S. imperialism.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=68\u201369}} Under his administration, diplomatic relations were established with Iran, with Morales praising [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] as a revolutionary comrade.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=167}} In April 2007 he attended the first [[South American Energy Summit]] in Venezuela, arguing with many allies over the issue of [[biofuel]], which he opposed.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=114\u2013115}} He had a particularly fierce argument with Brazilian President Lula over Morales's desire to bring Bolivia's refineries \u2013 which were largely owned by Brazil's [[Petrobr\u00e1s]] \u2013 under state control. In May, Bolivia purchased the refineries and transferred them to the [[YPFB|Bolivian State Petroleum Company]] (YPFB).{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=114\u2013115, 124\u2013125|2a1=Philip|2a2=Panizza|2y=2011|2pp=143&ndash;145}}\n\n====Social reform====\n[[File:Moraleslula 20060113 02.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Morales with Brazilian President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula]]]]\nMorales's government sought to encourage a model of development based upon the premise of ''vivir bien'', or \"to live well\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=99}} This entailed seeking social harmony, consensus, the elimination of discrimination, and wealth redistribution; in doing so, it was rooted in communal rather than individual values and owed more to indigenous Andean forms of social organization than Western ones.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=99}}\n\nUpon Morales's election, Bolivia's illiteracy rate was at 16%, the highest in South America.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=124\u2013125|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=104\u2013105}} Attempting to rectify this with the aid of far left allies, Bolivia launched a literacy campaign with Cuban assistance, while Venezuela invited 5000 Bolivian high school graduates to study in Venezuela for free.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=124\u201325|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=104\u201305}} By 2009, [[UNESCO]] declared Bolivia free from illiteracy,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=227}} although the World Bank claimed that it had only declined by 5%.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=105}} Cuba also aided Bolivia in the development of its medical care, opening ophthalmological centers in the country to treat 100,000 Bolivians for free per year, and offering 5000 free scholarships for Bolivian students to study medicine in Cuba.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=41|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=110}} The government sought to expand state medical facilities, opening twenty hospitals by 2014, and increasing basic medical coverage up to the age of 25.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=109\u2013110}} Their approach sought to utilize and harmonize both mainstream Western medicine and Bolivia's [[traditional medicine]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=109}}\n\nThe 2006 Bono Juancito Pinto program provided US$29 per month to poor families for every young child that they had,{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=198|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=102}} while 2008's Renta Dignidad initiative provided around $344 per month to low-income citizens over 60.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=200|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=101\u2013102}} 2009's Bono Juana Azurduy program offered cash transfers to uninsured mothers to improve their likelihood of seeking medical care.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=200}} Conservative critics of Morales's government claimed that these measures were simply designed to buy off the poor and ensure continued support for the government.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=112}}\n\nMorales announced that one of the top priorities of his government was to eliminate racism against the country's indigenous population.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=123}} To do this, he announced that all civil servants were required to learn one of Bolivia's three indigenous languages, Quechua, Aymara, or Guaran\u00ed, within two years.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1p=123|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=103}} His government encouraged the development of indigenous cultural projects,{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|pp=123\u2013124}} and sought to encourage more indigenous people to attend university; by 2008, it was estimated that half of the students enrolled in Bolivia's 11 public universities were indigenous,{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=124}} while three indigenous-specific universities had been established, offering subsidized education.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=107\u2013108}} In 2009, a Vice Ministry for Decolonization was established, which proceeded to pass the 2010 Law against Racism and Discrimination banning the espousal of racist views in private or public institutions.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=58, 65}}\nVarious commentators noted that there was a renewed sense of pride among the country's indigenous population following Morales's election.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=126}} Conversely, the opposition accused Morales's administration of aggravating racial tensions between indigenous, white, and mestizo populations,{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=123, 127}} with some non-indigenous Bolivians feeling that they were now experiencing racism.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=115\u201316, 121|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=92}}\n\n[[File:Evo shoeshine.jpg|thumb|left|Morales and vice-president [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] in 2006 [[Shoeshiner|shining the shoes]] of shoeshine boys.]]\n\nOn [[International Workers' Day]] 2006, Morales issued a presidential decree undoing aspects of the informalization of labor which had been implemented by previous neoliberal governments; this was seen as a highly symbolic act for [[labor rights]] in Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=68}} In 2009 his government put forward suggested reforms to the 1939 labor laws, although lengthy discussions with trade unions hampered the reforms' progress.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=69}} Morales's government increased the legal minimum wage by 50%,{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1p=165|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=69}} and reduced the pension age from 65 to 60, and then in 2010 reduced it again to 58.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=102}}\n\nWhile policies were brought in to improve the living conditions of the working classes, conversely many middle-class Bolivians felt that they had seen their social standing decline,{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=121}} with Morales personally mistrusting the middle-classes, deeming them fickle.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=217}} A 2006 law reallocated state-owned lands,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=121}} with this agrarian reform entailing distributing land to traditional communities rather than individuals.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=165}} In 2010, a law was introduced permitting the formation of recognized indigenous territories, although the implementation of this was hampered by bureaucracy and contesting claims over ownership.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=124\u201325}} Morales's government also sought to improve women's rights in Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=66}} In 2010, it founded a Unit of Depatriarchalization to oversee this process.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=58}} Further seeking to provide legal recognition and support to [[LGBT rights]], it declared June 28 to be Sexual Minority Rights Day in the country,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=71}} and encouraged the establishment of a gay-themed television show on the state channel.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=155}}\n\nAdopting a policy known as \"Coca Yes, Cocaine No\",{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=128}} Morales's administration ensured the legality of coca growing, but also introduced measures to regulate the production and trade of the crop.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|pp=119\u2013200}} In 2007, they announced that they would permit the growing of 50,000 acres of coca in the country, primarily for the purposes of domestic consumption,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=133}} with each family being restricted to the growing of one ''cato'' (1600 meters squared) of coca.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=164}}\n\nA social control program was implemented whereby local unions took on responsibility for ensuring that this quota was not exceeded; in doing so, they hoped to remove the need for military and police intervention, and thus stem the violence of previous decades.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=135\u2013136}} Measures were implemented to ensure the industrialization of coca production, with Morales inaugurating the first coca industrialization plant in [[Chulumani]], which produced and packaged coca and trimate tea; the project was primarily funded through a $125,000 donation from Venezuela under the PTA scheme.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|pp=119\u2013200}}\n\nThese industrialization measures proved largely unsuccessful given that coca remained illegal in most nations outside Bolivia, thus depriving the growers of an international market.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=137}} Campaigning against this, in 2012 Bolivia withdrew from the UN 1961 Convention which had called for global criminalisation of coca, and in 2013 successfully convinced the [[UN Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs]] to declassify coca as a narcotic.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=133\u201334}} The U.S. State Department criticized Bolivia, asserting that it was regressing in its counter-narcotics efforts, and dramatically reduced aid to Bolivia to $34 million to fight the narcotics trade in 2007.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1p=120|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=181\u201382}} Nevertheless, the number of cocaine seizures in Bolivia increased under Morales's government,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=141}} as they sought to encourage coca growers to report and oppose cocaine producers and traffickers.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=140}} However, high levels of police corruption surrounding the illicit trade in cocaine remained a continuing problem for Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=142}}\n\nMorales's government also introduced measures to tackle Bolivia's endemic corruption; in 2007, he used a presidential decree to create the Ministry of Institutional Transparency and Fight Against Corruption.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=43}} However, critics highlighted that MAS members were rarely prosecuted for the crime, the main exception being YPFB head [[Santos Ram\u00edrez]], who was sentenced to twelve years imprisonment for corruption in 2008. Conversely, a 2009 law that permitted the retroactive prosecution for corruption led to legal cases being brought against a number of opposition politicians for alleged corruption in the pre-Morales period; many fled abroad to avoid standing trial.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=44}}\n\n====Domestic unrest and the new constitution====\nDuring his presidential campaign, Morales had supported calls for regional autonomy for Bolivia's departments. As president, he changed his position, viewing the calls for autonomy \u2013 which came from [[Media Luna|Bolivia's four eastern departments]] of Santa Cruz, [[Beni Department|Beni]], [[Pando Department|Pando]], and [[Tarija]] \u2013 as an attempt by the wealthy bourgeoisie living in these regions to preserve their economic position.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=210}} He nevertheless agreed to a [[2006 Bolivian regional autonomy referendum|referendum on regional autonomy]], held in July 2006; the four eastern departments voted in favor of autonomy, but Bolivia as a whole voted against it by 57.6%.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=210|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=87|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=47}} In September, autonomy activists launched strikes and blockades across eastern Bolivia, resulting in violent clashes with MAS activists.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=212|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=96}} In January 2007, clashes in Cochabamba between activist groups led to fatalities, with Morales's government sending in troops to maintain the peace. The left-indigenous activists formed a Revolutionary Departmental Government, but Morales denounced it as illegal and continued to recognize the legitimacy of right-wing departmental head [[Manfred Reyes Villa]].{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=111\u2013124}}\n\nIn July 2006, an [[2006 Bolivian Constitutional Assembly election|election to form a Constitutional Assembly]] was held, which saw the highest ever electoral turnout in the nation's history. MAS won 137 of its 255 seats, after which the Assembly was inaugurated in August.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1pp=182\u2013183|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=210, 212|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=181|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4pp=39\u201340}} The Assembly was the first elected parliamentary body in Bolivia which features strong campesino and indigenous representation.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|pp=23\u201324}} In November, the Assembly approved [[Constitution of Bolivia|a new constitution]], which converted the Republic of Bolivia into the Plurinational State of Bolivia, describing it as a \"plurinational communal and social unified state\". The constitution emphasized Bolivian sovereignty of natural resources, separated church and state, forbade foreign military bases in the country, implemented [[term limit|a two-term limit]] for the presidency, and permitted limited regional autonomy. It also enshrined every Bolivians' right to water, food, free health care, education, and housing.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=213, 219|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=182, 218\u2013219|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3pp=41\u201342}} In enshrining the concept of plurinationalism, one commentator noted that it suggested \"a profound reconfiguration of the state itself\" by recognising the rights to self-determination of various nations within a single state.{{sfn|Assies|2011|p=93}}\n\n[[File:Evo morales 2 year bolivia Joel Alvarez.jpg|left|thumb|Morales in 2008]]\nIn May 2008, the eastern departments pushed for greater autonomy, but Morales's government rejected the legitimacy of their position.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=219\u2013220}} They called for a [[2008 Bolivian vote of confidence referendum|referendum on recalling Morales]], which saw an 83% turnout and in which Morales was ratified with 67.4% of the vote.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=220\u2013221|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=125|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=48}} Unified as the National Council for Democracy (CONALDE), these groups \u2013 financed by the wealthy agro-industrialist, petroleum, and financial elite \u2013 embarked on a series of destabilisation campaigns to unseat Morales's government.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=132\u2013133}}\n[[2008 unrest in Bolivia|Unrest then broke out across eastern Bolivia]], as radicalized autonomist activists established blockades, occupied airports, clashing with pro-government demonstrations, police, and armed forces. Some formed paramilitaries, bombing state companies, indigenous NGOs, and human rights organisations, also launching armed racist attacks on indigenous communities, culminating in the [[Porvenir Massacre|Pando Massacre]] of MAS activists.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=221\u2013222|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=182\u2013183|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3pp=133\u2013140|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4pp=47\u201349}} The autonomists gained support from some high-ranking politicians; Santa Cruz Governor [[Rub\u00e9n Costas]] lambasted Morales and his supporters with racist epithets, accusing the president of being an Aymara fundamentalist and a [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]] dictator responsible for [[state terrorism]].{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=221|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2pp=127\u2013128}} Amid the unrest, foreign commentators began speculating on the possibility of civil war.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=222|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=169|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=96}}\n\nAfter it was revealed that [[USAID]]'s [[Office of Transition Initiatives]] had supplied $4.5 million to the pro-autonomist departmental governments of the eastern provinces, in September 2008 Morales accused the U.S. ambassador to Bolivia, [[Philip Goldberg]], of \"conspiring against democracy\" and encouraging the civil unrest, ordering him to leave the country.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=222|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=132|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=49}}{{sfn|BBC News|2008a}}. The U.S. government responded by expelling Bolivian ambassador to the U.S., [[Gustavo Guzman]].{{sfn|BBC News|2008b}}. Bolivia subsequently expelled the U.S. [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) from the country, while the U.S. responded by withdrawing their [[Peace Corps]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=72}} Ch\u00e1vez stood in solidarity with Bolivia by ordering the U.S. ambassador [[Patrick Duddy]] out of his country and withdrawing the Venezuelan ambassador to the U.S.{{sfnm|1a1=BBC News|1y=2008b|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=169|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=139|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4p=49}} The [[Union of South American Nations]] (UNASUR) convened a special meeting to discuss the Bolivian situation, expressing full support for Morales's government.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=222|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=169|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=141}}\n\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev 16 February 2009-1.jpg|thumb|right|Morales meeting with Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] in 2009]]\nAlthough unable to quell the autonomist violence, Morales's government refused to declare a [[state of emergency]], believing that the autonomists were attempting to provoke them into doing so.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=134, 139}}\nInstead, they decided to compromise, entering into talks with the parliamentary opposition. As a result, 100 of the 411 elements of the Constitution were changed, with both sides compromising on certain issues.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=223|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=183|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=41}} Nevertheless, the governors of the eastern provinces rejected the changes, believing it gave them insufficient autonomy, while various Indianist and leftist members of MAS felt that the amendments conceded too much to the political right.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=223}} The constitution was put to a [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|referendum in January 2009]], in which it was approved by 61.4% of voters.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=223|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=183|3a1=Assies|3y=2011|3p=112|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=153|5a1=Farthing|5a2=Kohl|5y=2014|5p=41}}\n\nFollowing the approval of the new Constitution, the [[2009 Bolivian general election|2009 general election]] was called. The opposition sought to delay the election by demanding a new [[biometric registry]] system, hoping that it would give them time to form a united front against MAS.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=184}} Many MAS activists reacted violently against the demands, and attempting to prevent this. Morales went on a five-day hunger strike in April 2009 to push the opposition to rescind their demands. He also agreed to allow for the introduction of a new voter registry, but insisted that it was rushed through so as not to delay the election.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=184\u2013185}} Morales and the MAS won with a landslide majority, polling 64.2%, while voter participation had reached an all-time high of 90%.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=226|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=185|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=153|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4pp=50\u201351}} His primary opponent, Reyes Villa, gained 27% of the vote. The MAS won a two-thirds majority in both the [[National Congress of Bolivia|Chamber of Deputies]] and the [[National Congress of Bolivia|Senate]].{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=226|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=153|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3pp=50\u201351}} Morales notably increased his support in the east of the country, with MAS gaining a majority in Tarija.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=226|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=185|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=153}}\nIn response to his victory, Morales proclaimed that he was \"obligated to accelerate the pace of change and deepen socialism\" in Bolivia, seeing his re-election as a mandate to further his reforms.{{sfnm|1a1=Friedman-Rudovsky|1y=2009|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=155}}\n\n===Second presidential term: 2009\u20132014===\nDuring his second term, Morales began to speak openly of \"communitarian socialism\" as the ideology that he desired for Bolivia's future.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=155}} He assembled a new cabinet which was 50% female, a first for Bolivia,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=228}} although by 2012, that had dropped to a third.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=66}} One of the main tasks that faced his government during this term was the aim of introducing legislation that would cement the extension of rights featured in the new constitution.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=25}} In April 2010, the departmental elections saw further gains for MAS.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=154}} In 2013, the government passed a law to combat domestic violence against women.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=51}}\n\n[[File:Evo Morales in 2012.jpg|left|thumb|Morales at an international conference in 2012]]\n\nIn December 2009, Morales attended the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] in Copenhagen, Denmark, where he blamed climate change on capitalism and called for a [[financial transactions tax]] to fund climate change mitigation. Ultimately deeming the conference to have been a failure, he oversaw the World's People Conference on Climate Change and the Rights of Mother Earth outside of Cochabamba in April 2010.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=156|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=75\u201376}}\n\nFollowing the victories of [[Barack Obama]] and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 U.S. presidential election]], relations between Bolivia and the U.S. improved slightly, and in November 2009 the countries entered negotiations to restore diplomatic relations.{{sfnm|1a1=Friedman-Rudovsky|1y=2009|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=73}} After the U.S. backed the [[2011 military intervention in Libya]] by [[NATO]] forces, Morales condemned Obama, calling for his [[Nobel Peace Prize]] to be revoked.{{sfn|Lovell|2011}} The two nations restored diplomatic relations in November 2011,{{sfn|BBC News|2011a}} although Morales refused to allow the DEA back into the country.{{sfn|BBC News|2011b}}\n\nIn October 2012, the government passed a Law of Mother Earth that banned [[genetically modified organisms]] (GMOs) being grown in Bolivia; although praised by environmentalists, it was criticized by the nation's [[soya bean|soya]] growers, who claimed that it would make them less competitive on the global market.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=93}}\n\nOn July 2, 2013, Bolivia's foreign minister said that [[Evo Morales grounding incident|the diversion of Morales's presidential plane]] (FAB-001, a [[Dassault Falcon 900]]EX), when Portuguese, French, Spanish and Italian authorities denied access to their airspace due to suspicions that [[Edward Snowden]] was on board the aircraft, had put the president's life at risk.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivia: Presidential plane forced to land after false rumors of Snowden onboard|date=July 3, 2013|author=Catherine E. Shoichet|website=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/02/world/americas/bolivia-presidential-plane|accessdate=January 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324023608/http://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/02/world/americas/bolivia-presidential-plane|archivedate=March 24, 2015}}</ref> Latin American leaders describe the incident as a \"stunning violation of national sovereignty and disrespect for the region\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Evo Morales, Bolivia President, Leaves Europe After Flight Delayed Over Snowden Suspicions|author1=Michael Weissenstein|author2=Angels Charlton|date=July 3, 2013|website=Huffington Post|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/03/bolivia-snowden_n_3539179.html|access-date=December 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210021721/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/03/bolivia-snowden_n_3539179.html|archive-date=February 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Morales himself described the incident as a \"hostage\" situation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivia's Morales says plane held 'hostage' because of Snowden rumors|date=July 3, 2013|agency=United Press International|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2013/07/03/Bolivias-Morales-says-plane-held-hostage-because-of-Snowden-rumors/14561372850204|access-date=December 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101065353/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2013/07/03/Bolivias-Morales-says-plane-held-hostage-because-of-Snowden-rumors/14561372850204/|archive-date=January 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> France apologized for the incident the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=France apologises to Bolivia over jet row|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=Al Jazeera|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2013/07/2013747914179924.html|access-date=July 4, 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6O7fPZHdM?url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2013/07/2013747914179924.html|archive-date=March 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The presidents of Argentina, Ecuador, Suriname, Uruguay and Venezuela, Morales's political allies in the region, gathered to demand an explanation of the incident.<ref>{{cite web|website=Bloomberg Business|date=July 5, 2013|author=Nathan Gill|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-05/bolivia-threatens-u-s-embassy-closure-after-search-for-snowden.html|title=Bolivia Threatens U.S. Embassy Closing After Snowden Search|access-date=March 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022153516/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-05/bolivia-threatens-u-s-embassy-closure-after-search-for-snowden.html|archive-date=October 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Morales became the oldest active professional soccer player in the world after signing a contract for $200 a month with [[Sport Boys Warnes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivian President Evo Morales signed by football club|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-27463520|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=May 24, 2014|date=May 19, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524104439/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-27463520|archive-date=May 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2014, Morales condemned the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict]] and declared Israel a \"terrorist state\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/07/30/bolivia-israel-terrorist-state/13384989|title=Bolivia declares Israel a 'terrorist state'|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=August 1, 2014|access-date=August 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012063209/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/07/30/bolivia-israel-terrorist-state/13384989/|archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Domestic protests====\n[[File:Bolivia evo-morales government Joel Alvarez.jpg|thumb|right|Morales addressing Bolivia's Parliament]]\nMorales's second term was heavily affected by infighting and dissent from within his support base, as indigenous and leftist activists rejected several government reforms.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=55}} In May 2010, his government announced a 5% rise in the minimum wage. The Bolivian Workers' Central (COB) felt this insufficient given the rising cost of living, calling a [[general strike]], while protesters clashed with police. The government refused to increase the rise, accusing protesters of being pawns of the right.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=216\u201325}} In August 2010, violent protests broke out in southern [[Potos\u00ed]] over widespread unemployment and a lack of infrastructure investment.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=51}} In December 2010, the government cut subsidies for gasoline and diesel fuels, which raised fuel prices and transport costs. Protests led Morales to nullify the decree, responding that he \"ruled by obeying\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=51\u201352}} In June 2012, [[Law enforcement in Bolivia|Bolivia's police]] launched protests against anti-corruption reforms to the police service; they burned disciplinary case records and demanded salary increases. Morales's government relented, canceling many of the proposed reforms and agreeing to the wage rise.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=54\u201355}}\n\nIn 2011, the government announced it had signed a contract with a Brazilian company to construct a highway connecting Beni to Cochabamba, which would pass through the [[Isiboro S\u00e9cure National Park and Indigenous Territory]] (TIPNIS). This would better integrate the Beni and Pando departments with the rest of Bolivia and facilitate hydrocarbons exploration. The plan brought condemnation from environmentalists and indigenous communities living in the TIPNIS, who claimed that it would encourage deforestation and illegal settlement and that it violated the constitution and United Nations [[Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples]].{{sfnm|1a1=Farthing|1a2=Kohl|1y=2014|1pp=52\u201354|2a1=Crabtree|2a2=Chaplin|2y=2013|2p=17}} The issue became an international cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre and cast doubt on the government's environmentalist and indigenous rights credentials.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=18}} In August, 800 protesters embarked on [[2011 Bolivian indigenous protests|a protest march]] from [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]] to La Paz; many were injured in clashes with police and supporters of the road.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=52\u201354}} Two government ministers and other high-ranking officials resigned in protest and Morales's government relented, announcing suspension of the road.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=52\u201354}} In October 2011, he passed Law 180, prohibiting further road construction, although the government proceeded with a consultation, eventually gaining the consent of 55 of the 65 communities in TIPNIS to allow the highway to be built, albeit with a variety of concessions; construction was scheduled to take place after the 2014 general election.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=52\u201354}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Indigenous Bolivians march against Amazon road|date=August 15, 2011|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-14536163|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813013212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-14536163|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivia's Long March Against Evo Morales: An Indigenous Protest|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2097142,00.html|work=Time|date=October 17, 2011|access-date=December 13, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213032428/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2097142,00.html|archive-date=December 13, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2013, the government announced that it would permit hydrocarbon exploration in Bolivia's 22 national parks, to widespread condemnation from environmentalists.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=93}}\n\n===Third presidential term: 2014\u20132019===\n[[File:Third GECF summit in Tehran 11.jpg|thumb|Morales with Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] during the [[Third GECF summit]].]]\nIn 2008, Morales had vowed that he would not stand for re-election in the 2014 general election.{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=119}}\nHowever, he successfully did so and after proclaiming victory in the election, Morales declared it \"a triumph of the anti-colonialists and anti-imperialists\" and dedicated his win to both Castro and Ch\u00e1vez.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolivia elects Evo Morales as president for third term|newspaper=The Guardian|date=October 13, 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|access-date=December 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218142814/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|archive-date=December 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Evo Morales Dedicates Electoral Victory to Fidel Castro and Hugo Chavez|publisher=CubaNews|date=October 13, 2014|url=http://www.cubanews.ain.cu/world/1657-evo-morales-dedicates-electoral-victory-to-fidel-castro-and-hugo-chavez|access-date=October 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026041916/http://www.cubanews.ain.cu/world/1657-evo-morales-dedicates-electoral-victory-to-fidel-castro-and-hugo-chavez|archive-date=October 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Morales wins third term in Bolivian presidential election|date=October 13, 2014|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=http://www.dw.de/morales-wins-third-term-in-bolivian-presidential-election/a-17989872|access-date=October 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013120101/http://www.dw.de/morales-wins-third-term-in-bolivian-presidential-election/a-17989872|archive-date=October 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the basis of this victory, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' remarked that Morales was \"one of the world's most popular leaders\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Andres Schipani|title=Bolivia's Evo Morales secures redistributionist mandate|newspaper=Financial Times|date=October 13, 2014|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/077a25b4-528f-11e4-b55e-00144feab7de.html|access-date=October 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021053122/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/077a25b4-528f-11e4-b55e-00144feab7de.html|archive-date=October 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 17, 2015, Morales surpassed [[Andr\u00e9s de Santa Cruz]]'s nine years, eight months, and twenty-four days in office and became Bolivia's longest serving president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.paginasiete.bo/ideas/2015/10/11/andres-santa-cruz-morales-72985.html|title=Andr\u00e9s de Santa Cruz y Evo Morales|last=Quiroga T.|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=October 11, 2015|work=P\u00e1gina Siete|accessdate=June 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822150438/http://www.paginasiete.bo/ideas/2015/10/11/andres-santa-cruz-morales-72985.html|archive-date=August 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bolivia elects Evo Morales as president for third term|website=The Guardian|date=October 13, 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|access-date=December 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218142814/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|archive-date=December 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Writing in ''The Guardian'', [[Ellie Mae O'Hagan]] attributes his enduring popularity not to anti-imperialist rhetoric but his \"extraordinary socio-economic reforms,\" which resulted in poverty and extreme poverty declining by 25% and 43% respectively.<ref>[[Ellie Mae O'Hagan]] (October 14, 2014). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/oct/14/evo-morales-reelected-socialism-doesnt-damage-economies-bolivia Evo Morales has proved that socialism doesn't damage economies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218142813/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/oct/14/evo-morales-reelected-socialism-doesnt-damage-economies-bolivia |date=December 18, 2016 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''; retrieved October 18, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn early February 2016 there were rumors that Morales had had a child with a young woman, Gabriela Zapata Monta\u00f1o, and had granted favors to the Chinese company that she worked for.<ref name=\"Guardian-Monta\u00f1o\">{{cite news |last1=Collyns |first1=Dan |publisher=The Guardian |title=Sex, lies and paternity claims: Bolivia's president reels amid tumultuous scandal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jun/24/bolivia-evo-morales-press-freedom-gabriela-zapata-child |date=June 24, 2016}}</ref> Morales admitted that they had had a son (who he says died in infancy), but denied granting any favors and said he had not been in contact with Zapata Monta\u00f1o since 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gabriela Zapata Monta\u00f1o, la exnovia que puso en aprietos al presidente de Bolivia Evo Morales|url=http://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias/2016/02/160205_exnovia_evo_morales_bolivia_vs|agency=BBC|date=February 6, 2016|access-date=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209020810/http://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias/2016/02/160205_exnovia_evo_morales_bolivia_vs|archive-date=February 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The commission that investigated the issue concluded that Morales was not at fault. Zapata Monta\u00f1o was later sentenced to ten years in prison for illegal financial behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Comision-legislativa-influencias-contratos-CAMC_0_2484951532.html|title=Comisi\u00f3n legislativa concluye que no hubo tr\u00e1fico de influencias en contratos del Estado con CAMC - La Raz\u00f3n|access-date=December 22, 2017|website=www.la-razon.com|language=es}}</ref>\n\nMorales attended the swearing-in ceremony of Venezuela's president [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] for his second term on January 10, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Venezuelan President Maduro sworn in for second term amid international boycott |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/10/venezuelan-president-maduro-sworn-second-term-amid-international/ |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=April 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402153411/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/10/venezuelan-president-maduro-sworn-second-term-amid-international/ |archive-date=April 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2019, Morales condemned the arrest by the [[United Kingdom]] of WikiLeaks founder [[Julian Assange]].<ref name=\"assangereactions\">{{cite news |title=Julian Assange's arrest draws fierce international reaction |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/wikileaks-julian-assange-arrest-international-reaction |publisher=Fox News |date=April 11, 2019 |access-date=April 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413222042/https://www.foxnews.com/world/wikileaks-julian-assange-arrest-international-reaction |archive-date=April 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Term limit====\n{{See also|2016 Bolivian constitutional referendum}}\nThe [[Constitution of Bolivia|2009 Bolivian constitution]] prohibits more than two consecutive presidential terms.<ref name=\"2009-constitution\">{{Cite web |title=Bolivia (Plurinational State of)'s Constitution of 2009 |url=https://www.constituteproject.org/constitution/Bolivia_2009.pdf |publisher=Constitute Project}}</ref> Morales had been allowed to serve three consecutive terms as President due to a 2013 ruling by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]] that Morales' first term did not count towards the term limit because it had taken place prior to the ratification of the 2009 constitution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia: New law backs President Evo Morales third term |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-22605030 |publisher=BBC |date=May 21, 2013}}</ref> Despite Morales' claim in 2014 that he would not attempt to alter the constitution so that he could serve a fourth term,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Evo Morales rules out fourth term |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-29613434 |publisher=BBC |date=October 14, 2014}}</ref> in February 2016 a [[2016 Bolivian constitutional referendum|referendum]] was held on a constitutional amendment to allow presidents to serve three consecutive terms, which would have allowed Morales to run for a fourth term (third under the new constitution).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dube |first1=Ryan |title=Bolivia\u2019s Evo Morales Faces Tough Vote on Referendum |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bolivias-evo-morales-faces-tough-vote-on-referendum-1455902404 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=February 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Valdez |first1=Carlos |title=AP Explains: Why is Evo Morales facing protests in Bolivia? |url=https://apnews.com/4fcd6a5f055b44299178d6573734eea0 |publisher=Associated Press |date=November 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia passes law to allow Morales to run for fourth term |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-presidency/bolivia-passes-law-to-allow-morales-to-run-for-fourth-term-idUSKCN0RQ0SL20150926 |publisher=Reuters |date=September 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Bolivia-Sets-Date-For-Referendum-On-Evo-Morales-Re-election-20151015-0021.html Bolivia Sets Date For Referendum On Evo Morales Re-election] Telesurv, October 15, 2015</ref> The amendment narrowly lost.<ref name=\"BBC-2016referendum\">{{Cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093| title=Bolivian leader 'loses' fourth term bid| work=BBC News| date=February 22, 2016| access-date=June 21, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510094756/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093| archive-date=May 10, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMorales blamed the referendum loss on [[American imperialism]] and a \"dirty war\" by the right-wing opposition.<ref name=\"Blair\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/03/evo-morales-bolivia-president-election-limits|title=Evo for ever? Bolivia scraps term limits as critics blast 'coup' to keep Morales in power|last1=Blair|first1=Laurence|date=December 3, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 1, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101135426/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/03/evo-morales-bolivia-president-election-limits|archive-date=January 1, 2018|quote=This week, the country\u2019s highest court overruled the constitution, scrapping term limits altogether for every office. Morales can now run for a fourth term in 2019 \u2013 and for every election thereafter. ... the referendum results \u2013 which the government claims were invalid due to an opposition smear campaign directed by Washington ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Collyns |first1=Dan |last2=Watts |first2=Jonathan |title=Bolivia: tensions rise as Evo Morales's bid to extend presidency hangs in balance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/22/bolivia-tensions-rise-as-evo-moraless-bid-to-extend-presidency-hangs-in-balance |publisher=The Guardian |date=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Daniel |last2=Machicao |first2=Monica |title=Bolivia's Morales accepts defeat in term limit referendum |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-referendum/bolivias-morales-accepts-defeat-in-term-limit-referendum-idUSKCN0VX09E |publisher=Reuters |date=February 23, 2016}}</ref> Morales' had maintained high approval ratings throughout his presidency, which saw extreme poverty reduced, but shortly before the referendum his popularity was damaged by allegations that his former girlfriend, Gabriela Zapata Monta\u00f1o, had helped secure US$500 million in government contracts for the Chinese engineering firm that employed her, as well as by claims that the government intimidated journalists who investigated the scandal.<ref name=\"Guardian-Monta\u00f1o\"/><ref name=\"BBC-2016referendum\"/> Further adding to the scandal, Zapata alleged that the child Morales had with her that he claimed had died in infancy was, in fact, alive.<ref name=\"Monta\u00f1o scandal NYT\">{{cite news |title=The Worst Boyfriend in Bolivia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/26/opinion/the-worst-boyfriend-in-bolivia.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=May 25, 2016}}</ref> She later changed her story, and said that the baby had died in 2009.<ref name =\"trt230517\" /> In June 2016 Bolivia's attorney general, Ramiro Guerrero, told reporters that Zapata had paid $5,000 to the parents of an unrelated child in return for the child pretending to be Morales' son. Five people were arrested in relation to the charade<ref name=\"Guardian-Monta\u00f1o\"/><ref name =\"trt230517\" /> and in May 2017 Bolivian courts concluded that the child was not alive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/05/17/the-saga-of-fidel-the-president-of-bolivias-illusory-secret-son/|title=The Saga of Fidel, the Bolivian President\u2019s Illusory Secret Son|last1=Soloway|first1=Benjamin|date=May 17, 2016|publisher=Foreign Policy}}</ref> Morales denied the allegations relating to the government contracts and ordered an inquiry into how the contracts were awarded.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivian President Evo Morales 'loses' fourth term bid|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093|agency=BBC|date=February 22, 2016|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510094756/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093|archive-date=May 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The inquiry concluded that Morales was not at fault, while Zapata was arrested and ultimately sentenced to ten years in prison for influence peddling and laundering \"illicit earnings\".<ref name=\"Monta\u00f1o scandal NYT\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2017/05/23/condenan-a-10-anos-de-carcel-a-gabriela-zapata-expareja-de-evo-morales/|title=Condenan a 10 a\u00f1os de c\u00e1rcel a Gabriela Zapata, expareja de Evo Morales|last1=Carrasco|first1=Gloria|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\"trt230517\">{{cite news|url=https://www.trtworld.com/americas/bolivian-president-s-ex-girlfriend-gets-10-year-jail-term-7235|title=Bolivian president's ex-girlfriend gets 10 year jail term|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=TRT World}}</ref> However, there was controversy over the fact that Zapata's defense lawyer and an aunt who had corroborated her claim that Morales' son was alive were both jailed.<ref name=\"Monta\u00f1o scandal NYT\" /> \n\nDespite the referendum loss and Morales' earlier claim that he would not seek a fourth term if he lost the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales loses referendum for fourth term |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/02/bolivia-morales-loses-referendum-term-160224035410165.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> in December 2016 MAS nominated Morales as their candidate for the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 presidential election]], stating that they would seek various avenues to ensure the legality of Morales' candidacy.<ref>{{cite article |title=Bolivia's President Evo Morales to Run Again Despite Referendum Ruling it Out |date=December 18, 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |access-date=December 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219073457/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2017, MAS asked the Plurinational Constitutional Court to rescind legal limits barring elected authorities from seeking re-election indefinitely.<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/> In its ruling one month later, the Court struck down term limits for all elected public offices, including the Presidency, stating that term limits are [[human rights]] violations under the [[American Convention on Human Rights]], a multilateral treaty signed by many countries in the Americas,<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\">{{cite news |title=Bolivian court clears way for Morales to run for fourth term |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivian-court-clears-way-for-morales-to-run-for-fourth-term-idUSKBN1DS2ZX |publisher=Reuters |date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> enabling Morales to run for a fourth term.<ref name=\"Blair\" /> In response to the decision, the Secretary General of the [[Organization of American States]], [[Luis Almagro]], stated that the clause in the [[American Convention on Human Rights]] cited by the Court \u201cdoes not mean the right to perpetual power\u201d;<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/> however, in 2019 he publicly supported Morales' participation in the 2019 election, arguing that \"presidents [in other countries]...have taken part in electoral processes on the grounds of a court ruling\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election/bolivias-morales-defies-term-limits-launches-bid-for-fourth-term-idUSKCN1SO0R3|title=Bolivia's Morales defies term limits, launches bid for fourth term|last1=Ramos|first1=Daniel|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021034143/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election/bolivias-morales-defies-term-limits-launches-bid-for-fourth-term-idUSKCN1SO0R3|archive-date=October 21, 2019|publisher=Reuters|agency=Reuters}}</ref> Opposition leader [[Samuel Doria Medina]] called the decision \"a blow to the constitution\".<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/>\n\n==== New presidential residence ====\n[[File:Plaza Murillo .jpg|thumb|The new [[Casa Grande del Pueblo]] presidential residence built by Morales in 2018]]\nControversy arose when a new $34 million presidential skyscraper residence, the [[Casa Grande del Pueblo]], was constructed in the historical [[Plaza Murillo]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/16/bolivian-president-evo-morales-new-residence-is-as-imposing-as-it-is-divisive-la-paz|title=Bolivian president\u2019s new residence is as imposing as it is divisive|last=Collyns|first=Dan|date=August 16, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=December 7, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20180620-impoverished-bolivia-presidents-new-palace-eyesore|title=In impoverished Bolivia, president's new palace an eyesore for some|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2018|website=[[France 24]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> The proposal was initially declined due to municipal height restrictions in the historical district, though Morales' parliamentary majority in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] overrode the ban, permitting the tower's construction.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The Casa Grande del Pueblo was inaugurated by Morales on August 9, 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-45229290|title=C\u00f3mo es la imponente y pol\u00e9mica \"Casa Grande del Pueblo\", la nueva sede del gobierno de Bolivia construida por Evo Morales|last=|first=|date=August 18, 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=December 7, 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe 29-story tower standing at {{Convert|120|m|ft|abbr=}} was the tallest building in the capital city of La Paz when completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expreso.com.pe/mundo/bolivia-conozca-el-suite-presidencial-que-ocupo-evo-morales-en-la-casa-grande-del-pueblo/|title=Bolivia: conozca la suite presidencial que ocup\u00f3 Evo Morales en la Casa Grande del Pueblo|date=November 15, 2019|website=Expreso|language=es|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/11/15/las-fotos-de-la-suite-de-evo-morales-en-la-casa-del-pueblo-parece-una-habitacion-de-un-jeque-arabe/|title=Las fotos de la suite de Evo Morales en La Casa del Pueblo: \u201cParece una habitaci\u00f3n de un jeque \u00e1rabe\"|last=|first=|date=November 15, 2019|website=[[Infobae]]|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> It was designed by Bolivian architects and decorated with indigenous motifs representing traditional Bolivian culture.<ref name=\":1\"/> The skyscraper was built to replace the former presidential palace, which Morales planned to turn into a museum.<ref name=\"bbc021114\">{{cite web |last1=BBC News |title=Bolivian palace: President Evo Morales signs contract |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-29868704 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> The building features a helipad and the top two floors were reserved for the president, featuring a gym, spa, Jacuzzi and private elevator.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The presidential suite in total was {{Convert|1,068|m2|ft2|abbr=}}, with the bathroom and dressing room measuring at {{Convert|47|m2|ft2|abbr=}} while the bedroom was {{Convert|61|m2|ft2|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/gente/2018/5/20/la-suite-de-evo-tiene-1068-m2-incluye-sauna-jacuzzi-sala-de-masajes-180564.html|title=La suite de Evo tiene 1.068 m2 e incluye sauna, jacuzzi y sala de masajes|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2018|website=Diario Pagina Siete|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> According to ''Diario Pagina Siete'', Morales' bedroom was the same size as the average home provided by his government housing project.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMany analysts and critics of Morales denounced the spending due to the large levels of poverty in Bolivia.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[NPR]] described the new residence as \"a luxurious new skyscraper\" and that critics contend that \"Morales is acting more like an emperor than a president\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/14/767967304/how-bolivias-evo-morales-could-win-a-4th-term-as-president|title=How Bolivia's Evo Morales Could Win A 4th Term As President|last=|first=|date=October 14, 2019|website=[[NPR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> while [[Reuters]] wrote that Morales \"alienated those who once backed him, especially by building the ostentatious presidential palace\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-palace-idUKKBN1XO2Y4|title=Andean textiles and bank bills: Inside Morales' home at Bolivia's Big House of the People|last=|first=|date=November 14, 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=December 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref> Bolivian [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Toribio Ticona Porco]] dubbed the tower \"Evo Palace\" and criticized the opulence invested into it.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAfter signing the contract for the new building, Morales stated that it was \"not a luxury\" since it would also house cabinet meeting rooms, a center for indigenous ceremonies and a 1,000-seat auditorium as well as rooms for exclusive presidential use.<ref name = \"bbc021114\"/> He also stated that the project would reduce government spending by $20 million per year as five other ministries would move into the building.<ref name=\":1\" /> He said the Casa Grande del Pueblo was a break with the past and described the previous residence, the [[Palacio Quemado]] or \"Burnt Palace\", as a vestige of colonialism and a symbol of neoliberal governments that stripped the State of its wealth, its heritage and its memory.<ref name=\":3\" />  Morales' communication minister [[G\u00edsela L\u00f3pez]] responded to criticism, stating that the tower was \"a necessity for the people\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== 2019 election controversy and resignation ===\n{{Main article|2019 Bolivian political crisis}}\n====Background====\nArticle 168 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia|2009 Bolivian constitution]] allows the President and Vice President to put themselves forward for re-election only once, limiting the number of terms to two.<ref name=\"2009-constitution\"/> As Evo Morales was approaching the end of his second consecutive term since the ratification of the 2009 constitution (his third consecutive term since first being elected\u2014in 2013 Bolivia's highest court ruled that Morales' first term did not count towards the term limit because it had taken place prior to the ratification of the 2009 constitution<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia: New law backs President Evo Morales third term |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-22605030 |publisher=BBC |date=May 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LaRazon6Nov15\">[http://la-razon.com/nacional/Referendum_constitucional-consulta-habilitar-Evo-marcha-MAS-juega_0_2376362395.html Consulta para habilitar a Evo est\u00e1 en marcha;  El MAS \u2018se juega la vida\u2019] La Raz\u00f3n, 6 November 2015</ref>), the governing party, the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] (MAS), sponsored an effort to amend this article. The referendum was authorized by a combined session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] on 26 September 2015, by a vote of 112 to 41.<ref name=\"ALP26Sep15\">[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/La-ALP-sanciono-la-Ley-de-Reforma-parcial-de-la-CPE La ALP sancion\u00f3 la Ley de Reforma parcial de la CPE] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226052237/http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/La-ALP-sanciono-la-Ley-de-Reforma-parcial-de-la-CPE |date=2015-12-26 }} Vice President of Bolivia</ref><ref name=\"R\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/26/us-bolivia-presidency-idUSKCN0RQ0SL20150926 Bolivia passes law to allow Morales to run for fourth term] Reuters, 25 September 2015</ref> A successful 'yes' vote would have allowed President Evo Morales and Vice President [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] to run for a fourth term in office in 2019.\n\nThe referendum was held on Sunday, 21 February 2016. The proposed constitutional amendment was voted down by a 51% majority.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Nicholas |title=Bolivian President Concedes Defeat in Term-Limit Referendum |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/25/world/americas/bolivian-president-evo-morales-concedes-defeat-in-term-limit-referendum.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=24 February 2016}}</ref> \n\nDespite the referendum loss and Morales' earlier claim that he would not seek a fourth term if he lost the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales loses referendum for fourth term |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/02/bolivia-morales-loses-referendum-term-160224035410165.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> in December 2016 MAS nominated Morales as their candidate for the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 presidential election]], stating that they would seek various avenues to ensure the legality of Morales' candidacy.<ref>{{cite article |title=Bolivia's President Evo Morales to Run Again Despite Referendum Ruling it Out |date=December 18, 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |access-date=December 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219073457/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2017, MAS applied to the Plurinational Constitutional Court, which critics claim had been stacked with Morales allies after its creation under Morales by the [[Constitution of Bolivia|2009 constitution]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armario |first1=Christine |title=AP Explains: Did a coup force Bolivia\u2019s Evo Morales out? |url=https://apnews.com/6b2c94306089451d9761878c9f7ce2f1 |publisher=Associated Press |date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=France-Presse |first1=Agence |title=Bolivia's Evo Morales faces second round run-off in bid for controversial fourth term |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/21/bolivias-evo-morales-faces-second-round-run-off-bid-controversial/ |publisher=The Telegraph |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> to abolish term limits. In November, the court ruled in favor of their abolition, stating that [[term limit]]s are [[human right]]s violations under the [[American Convention on Human Rights]].<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/> The ruling enabled Morales to run for re-election in the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 elections]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blair |first1=Laurence |title=Evo for ever? Bolivia scraps term limits as critics blast 'coup' to keep Morales in power |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/03/evo-morales-bolivia-president-election-limits |publisher=The Guardian |date=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2019 election====\n{{See also|2019 Bolivian general election}}\n\n<!-- Summary of election results -->\nFollowing the court ruling eliminating term limits, on October 20, 2019 Morales won 47.1% of the vote in the first round of the [[2019 Bolivian general election]]. His closest rival was Carlos Mesa, with 35.5% of the vote. As the gap between Morales and Mesa was over 10%, Bolivian election law dictated that a second-round run-off between them would not be required.<ref name=\"aj291019\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia, OAS close to deal on election audit as protests continue |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/bolivia-oas-close-deal-election-audit-protests-continue-191028143828285.html |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116145048/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/bolivia-oas-close-deal-election-audit-protests-continue-191028143828285.html |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<!-- Disputation of elecation and immediate aftermath -->\nThe results were immediately disputed as there was an unexplained break in transmission of the results, leading to widespread [[2019 Bolivian protests|protests across the country]]. Responding to the concerns and violent protests, Morales asked the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS) to conduct an audit of the vote count.<ref name=\"reuters231019\">{{cite news |title=Bolivian government seeks election audit, vows to respect result |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-foreign-minister/bolivian-government-seeks-election-audit-vows-to-respect-result-idUSKBN1X12FJ |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=October 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116145050/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-foreign-minister/bolivian-government-seeks-election-audit-vows-to-respect-result-idUSKBN1X12FJ |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morales said he would call for a second-round runoff vote with Mesa if the OAS' audit found evidence of fraud.<ref name=\"aj291019\"/> Morales asked the protesters to observe a truce while the OAS conducted the audit, while Mesa asked his supporters to maintain their strikes and street protests all over the country.<ref name=\"msm311019\">{{cite news |title=Morales calls for Bolivia violence 'truce' as OAS begins election audit |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/oas-begins-audit-of-disputed-bolivia-election-results/ar-AAJEH73 |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |agency=AFP |publisher=msm |date=October 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116145050/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/oas-begins-audit-of-disputed-bolivia-election-results/ar-AAJEH73 |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 8, 2019, police in a number of cities, including La Paz, Santa Cruz, Sucre and Cochabamba, joined in demonstrations against the government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/09/bolivian-police-in-la-paz-join-mutiny-against-evo-morales|title=Bolivian police in La Paz join 'mutiny' against Evo Morales|last=Collyns|first=Dan|date=November 9, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110003802/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/09/bolivian-police-in-la-paz-join-mutiny-against-evo-morales|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/animal_electoral/bolivia-motin-policial-policias-rebelion-evo_0_3254074610.html|title=El mot\u00edn policial se extiende a cuatro capitales - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> \n\n<!-- Independent reports released prior to OAS preliminary report -->\nPrior to the release of the OAS audit preliminary report, a number of independent audits were conducted. On 5 November 2019, Professor [[Walter Mebane|Walter R. Mebane]] at the University of Michigan used his own \"eforensics\" model to detect and predict the level of fraud that occurred during the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressenza.com/2019/11/studies-refute-oas-claims-of-irregularities-in-bolivian-elections/|title=Studies refute OAS claims of irregularities in Bolivian elections|last1=Swinden|first1=Silvia|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=16 November 2019|publisher=Pressenza - International Press Agency}}</ref><ref name=Mebane>{{Cite web|url=http://www-personal.umich.edu/~wmebane/Bolivia2019.pdf|title=Evidence Against Fraudulent Votes Being Decisive in the Bolivia 2019 Election\u2217|last=Mebane|first=Walter R.|date=13 November 2019|website=University of Michigan personal homepage server|url-status=live|access-date=2 January 2020|page=1}}</ref> He estimated that there were around 22500 fraudulent votes and initially determined that, although fraud existed, it would not have been enough to change the results of the elections. On 13 November, however, Mebane said that feedback from colleagues led him to believe that \"best formula\" for the model led to a new reallocation which indicated that Morales would have had a lead of 9.9% over Mesa, requiring a runoff election.<ref name=Mebane/> On 8 November 2019, Ethical Hacking, the tech security company hired by the TSE (under Morales) to audit the elections, stated that there were multiple irregularities and violations of procedure and that \"our function as an auditor security company is to declare everything that was found, and much of what was found supports the conclusion that the electoral process be declared null and void\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/8/ethical-hacking-las-elecciones-en-bolivia-estan-viciadas-de-nulidad-236759.html|title=Ethical Hacking: The elections in Bolivia are null and void|language=es}}</ref> In their official report, one source for the OAS, they stated \u2033We ''cannot'' attest to the integrity of the electoral results because the entire process is null and void due to the number of alterations to the TREP source code, the number of accesses and manual modifications with the maximum privileges to the databases being created during the electoral process and the inconsistencies of the software that arose in the TREP and Computo.\u2033 <ref>cite web | url=https://www.scribd.com/document/434031751/EHC-REP-Consolidado-Resumen|title=Ethical Hacking consolidated report|language=es</ref>\n\n<!-- OAS preliminary report and immediate political effects -->\nOn November 10, 2019, OAS published its preliminary report concluding that there were \"clear manipulations\" in the election.<ref>{{cite web |title=An\u00e1lisis de Integridad Electoral Elecciones Generales en el Estado Plurinacional de Bolivia 20 de octubre de 2019 |url=http://www.oas.org/documents/spa/press/Informe-Auditoria-Bolivia-2019.pdf |publisher=Organization of American States |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales to call fresh election after OAS audit |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50365340 |publisher=BBC |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Keith |title=Why Is Evo Morales Suddenly No Longer President of Bolivia? |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/11/evo-morales-resigns-president-bolivia/ |publisher=Foreign Policy |date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Krygier |first1=Rachelle |last2=Faiola |first2=Anthony |title=Bolivia\u2019s Morales resigns amid scathing election report, rising protests |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/bolivia-to-hold-new-elections-after-protests-and-international-criticism/2019/11/10/4778e842-03b2-11ea-ac12-3325d49eacaa_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref>  Within an hour of the release of the preliminary report, Morales announced that fresh elections would be held,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/animal_electoral/bolivia-elecciones-nuevas-convocatoria-evo-comicios_0_3255274455.html|title=Evo anuncia nuevas elecciones con nuevas autoridades electorales y nuevos actores pol\u00edticos - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> but this offer was rejected by the opposition party and civic leaders who demanded his resignation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales to call fresh election after OAS audit |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50365340 |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |date=November 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110130244/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50365340 |archive-date=November 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"reuters101119\">{{cite web |title=Bolivia's Morales agrees to new elections after damning OAS audit |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-oas/oas-finds-irregularities-in-disputed-bolivia-vote-calls-for-new-elections-idUSKBN1XK07T |website=Reuters |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110152642/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-oas/oas-finds-irregularities-in-disputed-bolivia-vote-calls-for-new-elections-idUSKBN1XK07T |archive-date=November 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Executive Secretary of the Bolivian Workers' Center Juan Carlos Huarachi, the chief of police Commander Yuri Calder\u00f3n, and prominent right-wing activist [[Luis Fernando Camacho]] called for Morales' resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/evo-morales-cob-renuncia-reflexionar-pacificar-pais-bolivia_0_3255274472.html|title=COB : 'Si es por el bien del pa\u00eds, que renuncie nuestro Presidente' - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/animal_electoral/FFAA-sugieren-presidente-Morales-renunciar-bolivia_0_3255274480.html|title=Las FFAA y la Polic\u00eda le sugieren al presidente Morales renunciar - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, General [[Williams Kaliman]], a loyal supporter of Morales and commander-in-chief of Bolivia's army,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/seguridad/2019/12/1/fiel-evo-hasta-el-final-kaliman-saco-las-tropas-amenazado-por-su-estado-mayor-239081.html|title=Fiel a Evo hasta el final, Kaliman sac\u00f3 a las tropas amenazado por su Estado Mayor - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> and other military chiefs suggested Morales step down to restore \"peace and stability and for the good of our Bolivia\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50369591|title=Bolivian army chief urges Morales to step down|date=November 10, 2019|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111084941/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50369591|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html|title=Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down|last=Londo\u00f1o|first=Ernesto|date=November 10, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110211008/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Morales announced his resignation. Other key figures in Morales' government also resigned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/seguridad/2019/12/4/kaliman-evo-como-puede-ser-golpe-de-estado-no-me-quede-de-presidente-239427.html|title=Kaliman a Evo: C\u00f3mo puede ser golpe de Estado, no me qued\u00e9 de Presidente - Diario Pagina Siete|last=|first=|date=|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> On 12 November, Morales flew to Mexico where he was granted [[Right of asylum|political asylum]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia crisis: Evo Morales accepts political asylum in Mexico |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50383608 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=November 12, 2019 |work=BBC News |date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112091524/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50383608 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morales, along with the governments of [[Mexico]], [[Cuba]], [[Uruguay]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Argentina]], maintain that his removal was a [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]].<ref name=\"BC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50370013|title=Bolivian President Evo Morales resigns|publisher=BBC News|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=November 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110213149/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50370013|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian101119\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/10/bolivian-president-evo-morales-resigns-after-election-result-dispute|title=Bolivian president Evo Morales resigns after election result dispute|date=November 10, 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|access-date=November 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111055233/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/10/bolivian-president-evo-morales-resigns-after-election-result-dispute|archive-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"reutersmexico\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nicaragua-bolivia-idUSKBN1XL06O|title=Nicaraguan government denounces \"coup\" in Bolivia: statement|date=November 11, 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111222822/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nicaragua-bolivia-idUSKBN1XL06O|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mexico says Bolivia suffered coup due to military pressure on Morales |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=November 11, 2019 |access-date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112013317/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/12/world/americas/bolivia-evo-morales-coup.html|title=Bolivia Crisis Shows the Blurry Line Between Coup and Uprising|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=November 12, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mexico says Bolivia suffered coup due to military pressure on Morales |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=November 11, 2019 |access-date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112013317/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bolivian opposition leaders and the governments of [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], the [[United Kingdom]], the [[United States]], and [[Canada]] recognized opposition senator [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] as the de facto interim president.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dyer |first1=Evan |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |publisher=CBC |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=de Haldevang |first1=Max |title=The world\u2019s as divided about Bolivia\u2019s alleged coup as Bolivians themselves |url=https://qz.com/1748281/experts-are-divided-on-evo-morales-and-bolivias-alleged-coup/ |publisher=Quartz |date=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/12/world/americas/bolivia-evo-morales-coup.html|title=Bolivia Crisis Shows the Blurry Line Between Coup and Uprising|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=November 12, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Final OAS report and corroborating reports -->\nOn 5 December 2019, the OAS released its final 96-page report on the integrity of the election. It found \"overwhelming evidence\" of vote-rigging in favor of Morales, including physical records with alterations, forged signatures, a \u201cparallel technological scheme\u201d of hidden servers, and evidence of wide-scale data manipulation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Final Report of the Audit of the Elections in Bolivia: Intentional Manipulation and Serious Irregularities Made it Impossible to Validate the Results |url=https://www.oas.org/en/media_center/press_release.asp?sCodigo=E-109/19 |publisher=Organization of American States |date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia election rigging in favor of Morales was 'overwhelming': OAS final report |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-oas/bolivia-election-rigging-in-favor-of-morales-was-overwhelming-oas-final-report-idUSKBN1Y9063 |publisher=Reuters |date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kurmanaev |first1=Anatoly |title=Election Fraud Aided Evo Morales, International Panel Concludes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/world/americas/evo-morales-election.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Evo Morales: Overwhelming evidence of election fraud in Bolivia, monitors say |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50685335 |publisher=BBC |date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia: 'overwhelming evidence' of vote-rigging in favor of Morales, OAS says |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/05/bolivia-election-evo-morales-vote-rigging-report-oas |publisher=The Guardian |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> The report was corroborated by a number of other independent analyses. For instance, the Technical Mission of Electoral Experts, sent by the European Union, published a 67-page report on 21 December that made similar observations and conclusions as the OAS's report. They noted that \"there were minutes with an unusually high number of null votes, blank votes and a hundred percent participation of voters in a series of polling stations\" and highlighted the general failure of the TSE to declare these irregularities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.voanoticias.com/a/union-europea-detecto-errores-irregularidades-elecciones-bolivia/5215093.html|title=Informe de la UE detect\u00f3 \u201cnumerosos errores\u201d en elecciones de Bolivia|date=21 December 2019|work=Voice of America|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uetrabajandojuntos.org/documentos/|title=Informe Final de la Misi\u00f3n T\u00e9cnica de Expertos Electorales sobre las Elecciones Generales en Bolivia del 20 de octubre de 2019|last=|first=|date=21 December 2019|website=Trabajando Juntos|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Analyses contradicting OAS report -->\nResponding to the OAS final report, a 27 February 2020 study published by independent contractors \u2014 commissioned by the [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and left-leaning <ref>{{cite web | url=https://fair.org/extra/the-incredible-shrinking-think-tank/ | title=The Incredible Shrinking Think Tank | last=Dolny | first=Michael | date=March 2008 | website=Fair | accessdate=17 April 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"The Perils Of Petrocracy\">{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Tina|title=The Perils Of Petrocracy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/magazine/04oil-t.html?pagewanted=7|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=4 November 2007|quote= \u2026 Mark Weisbrot, co-director of the Center for Economic and Policy Research, a left-leaning Washington policy group.}}</ref> think tank [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]] (CEPR) \u2014concluded that it was \"very likely\" that Morales' victory was legitimate.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Study Finds No Evidence of OAS Fraud Claims, \u201cVery Likely\u201d Evo Morales Won Bolivia\u2019s October Elections in the First Round |url=https://cepr.net/press-release/new-study-finds-no-evidence-of-oas-fraud-claims-very-likely-evo-morales-won-bolivias-october-elections-in-the-first-round/ |publisher=Center for Economic and Policy Research |date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=US centre: No evidence of fraud in Bolivia's October polls |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/centre-evidence-fraud-bolivia-october-polls-200228052717538.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=28 February 2020}}</ref> \"The media has largely reported the allegations of fraud as fact... However, as specialists in election integrity, we find that the statistical evidence does not support the claim of fraud in Bolivia's October election,\" the authors wrote in an article that was published by ''The Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Curiel |first1=John |last2=Williams |first2=Jack R. |title=Bolivia dismissed its October elections as fraudulent. Our research found no reason to suspect fraud. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/02/26/bolivia-dismissed-its-october-elections-fraudulent-our-research-found-no-reason-suspect-fraud/ |work=The Washington Post |date=27 February 2020}}</ref>  As a rebuttal to this criticism of his work for the OAS, [[Georgetown University]] political scientist Irfan Nooruddin wrote a similar article in the Washington Post to back up his conclusions that there were unexplained massive swings to Morales that were \"unpredicted and unanticipated by any previous part of the election trends\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nooruddin|first=Irfan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/10/yes-bolivias-2019-election-was-problematic-heres-why/|title=Yes, Bolivia's 2019 election was problematic. Here's why.|date=10 March 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He also pointed to another study made by Diego Escobari, Associate Professor at University of Texas Rio Grande Valley, and Gary A. Hoover, Head of Economics at the University of Oklahoma, which \"concluded even more forcefully that the election was fraudulent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3492928|title=Evo Morales and Electoral Fraud in Bolivia: A Natural Experiment Estimate|last1=Escobari|first1=Diego|last2=Hoover|first2=Gary A.|date=12 December 2019|website=SSRN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Escobari |first1=Diego |last2=Valdivia |first2=Walter D. |title=Bolivia\u2019s Electoral Fraud Reckoning |url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/evo-morales-bolivia-presidential-election-fraud-by-walter-d-valdivia-and-diego-escobari-2020-03 |publisher=Project Syndicate |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The 27 February report has received criticism from the OAS, who said it contained \"multiple falsehoods, inaccuracies and omissions\"; the interim Bolivian government, who called it \"lacking in scientific and academic value\"; and Bolivian newspaper, [[P\u00e1gina Siete]], who noted that one of the authors of the report, Jack Williams, had previously signed a letter to the US Congress to oppose the \"military coup\" in Bolivia and which supported a previous CEPR study claiming victory for Morales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/3/3/autor-de-analisis-del-cepr-firmo-peticion-favorable-evo-en-2019-248400.html|title=Author of CEPR analysis signed petition favoring Evo in 2019|last=Escobar|first=Luis|date=3 March 2020|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/director-oea-analisis-expertos-mit_0_3323667654.html|title=OAS director observes 11 points in the MIT expert analysis|last=|first=|date=3 March 2020|website=La Raz\u00f3n|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/3/6/ven-que-analisis-del-cepr-quedo-desvirtuado-tras-la-carta-del-mit-248773.html|title=You can see that CEPR analysis was distorted after the MIT letter|last=Esc\u00f3bar|first=Luis|date=6 March 2020|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Morales' later activity -->\nIn December 2019, Morales moved from Mexico to Argentina, where he was also granted political asylum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/evo-morales-granted-refugee-status-argentina-191212145522052.html|title=Evo Morales granted refugee status in Argentina|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> Later that month, an arrest warrant was issued for Morales by Bolivian prosecutors for alleged [[sedition]] and [[terrorism]]. The interim government alleged that Morales promoted violent clashes in the country before and after he left office.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/bolivia-prosecutors-order-arrest-president-evo-morales-191218181946003.html|title=Bolivia prosecutors order arrest of ex-President Evo Morales|date=18 December 2019|work=Al Jazeera|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/18/warrant-for-arrest-of-evo-morales-issued-in-bolivia|title=Warrant for arrest of Evo Morales issued in Bolivia|date=18 December 2019|work=The Guradian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2020, Morales announced that he would run for a seat in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] in the [[2020 Bolivian general election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/world/americas/bolivia-evo-morales-senate.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 4, 2020 |title=Evo Morales, Now in Exile, to Run for Bolivia\u2019s Senate |first=Julie |last=Turkewitz |quote=Evo Morales, the former Bolivian president who fled his country in November amid violent protests over his bid to stay in power, will attempt to run for the Senate in the country\u2019s upcoming elections.}}</ref> On 20 February, however, the national electoral tribunal ruled that Morales was ineligible to run for Senate.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Reuters]] |title=Bolivia electoral body blocks Morales senate run |date=February 20, 2020 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/bolivia-politics-morales/bolivia-electoral-body-blocks-morales-senate-run-idUSL1N2AL014 |first=Daniel |last=Ramos |first2=Adam |last2=Jourdan |editor-first=Sanda |editor-last=Maler |quote=Salvador Romero, the head of the country\u2019s electoral tribunal, told reporters that Morales did not meet the requirements to be a Senate candidate for his Movement for Socialism (MAS) party, which is currently leading in the polls.}}</ref>\n\n==Political ideology==\n{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=The worst enemy of humanity is capitalism. That is what provokes uprisings like our own, a rebellion against a system, against a neo-liberal model, which is the representation of a savage capitalism. If the entire world doesn't acknowledge this reality, that the national states are not providing even minimally for health, education and nourishment, then each day the most fundamental human rights are being violated.|source=\u2013 Evo Morales{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=12}} }}\n\nFigures in the Morales government have described the President's approach to politics as \"Evoism\" ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]: ''Evismo'').{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=210|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=65}} From 2009, Morales has advocated \"[[communitarianism|communitarian]] socialism\",{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=155}} while political scientist Sven Harten characterized Morales's ideology as \"eclectic\", drawing ideas from \"various ideological currents\".{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=40}} Harten noted that whilst Morales uses fierce anti-imperialist and leftist rhetoric, he is neither \"a hardcore [[anti-globalisation|anti-globalist]] nor a [[Marxism|Marxist]],\" not having argued for the violent and absolute overthrow of capitalism or U.S. involvement in Latin America.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=5}}\n\nEconomically, Morales's policies have sometimes been termed \"Evonomics\" and have focused on creating a [[mixed economy]].{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=222, 232}} Morales's presidential discourse has revolved around distinguishing between \"the people\", of whom he sees himself as a representative, and the oppressive socio-economic elite and the old political class, whom he believes have mistreated \"the people\" for centuries.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=154\u2013165}} Morales sought to make Bolivia's [[representative democracy]] more [[direct democracy|direct]] and [[communitarian]], through the introduction of referendums and a citizen-led legislative initiative.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=217}} George Philip and Francisco Panizza claimed that like his allies Correa and Ch\u00e1vez, Morales should be categorized as a populist,{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=68}} because he appealed \"directly to the people against their countries' political and economic order, divided the social field into antagonistic camps and promised redistribution and recognition in a newly founded political order.\"{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=73}}\n\nVarious far left commentators have argued against categorizing the Morales administration as socialist. Bolivia's Marxist Vice President [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] asserts that Bolivia lacks the sufficiently large industrialized working class, or [[proletariat]], to enable it to convert into [[Socialism (Marxism)|a socialist society]] in the Marxist understanding of the word. Instead, he terms the government's approach \"Andean and Amazonian capitalism\".{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1pp=159\u2013161|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=64|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=87}} Marxist American sociologist [[James Petras]] has argued that Morales's government is neither socialist nor anti-imperialist, instead describing Morales as a \"[[paternalistic conservatism|radical conservative]]\" for utilizing socialist rhetoric while continuing to support foreign investment and the economic status of Bolivia's capitalist class,{{sfnm|1a1=Petras|1y=2007<!--|2a1=Petras|2y=2013 blacklisted source -->}} while British Trotskyist academic Jeffery R. Webber asserted that Morales was no socialist but that his government was \"reconstituting neoliberalism\", thereby rejecting \"neoliberal orthdoxy\" but retaining a \"core faith in the capitalist market as the principal engine of growth and industrialization.\"{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=232}} Similarly, Aymara activist Felipe Quispe characterized Morales's government as \"neoliberalism with an Indian [i.e. indigenous] face\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=148}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Esther Morales, hermana del presidente de Bolivia Evo Morales se reuni\u00f3 con el Canciller Ricardo Pati\u00f1o (8001318681).jpg|200px|thumb|right|First Lady Morales with the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Ecuador [[Ricardo Pati\u00f1o]].]]\nMorales is ethnically [[Aymara people|Aymara]], and has been widely described as Bolivia's first democratically-elected President from the indigenous majority.<ref name=\"oct17bbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-12166905|title=Evo Morales: Bolivian leader wants five more years in power|publisher=BBC News|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014115936/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-12166905|archive-date=October 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> Although Morales has sometimes been described as the first indigenous president to be democratically elected in Latin America, [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], a Mexican of the [[Zapotec peoples|Zapotec]] ethnic group, was elected President of Mexico in 1858.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} Biographer Mart\u00edn Sivak described Morales as \"incorruptible, charismatic, and combative\",{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=95}} also noting that he had a \"friendly style\" and could develop a good rapport with journalists and photographers, in part because he could \"articulate his opinions with simplicity\".{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=45}} He places a great emphasis on trust,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=216}} and relies on his intuition, sometimes acting on what he considers omens in his dreams.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=215|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=167}} Harten said that Morales \"can be a forceful leader, one who instills great respect and, sometimes, a reluctance in others to contradict him, but he has also learnt to listen and learn from other people.\"{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=147}} Farthing and Kohl characterized Morales as a \"[[charisma]]tic [[populist]]\" of a kind common in Latin American history, who prioritized \"a direct relationship\" between the population and the leader.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=16}}\n\nMorales is not married and upon becoming president selected his older sister, [[Esther Morales Ayma]], to adopt the role of [[First Lady]]. He has two children from different mothers. They are his daughter Eva Liz Morales Alvarado and son \u00c1lvaro Morales Paredes.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=Hermana de Evo Morales sera primera dama |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/internacionales/505699.html |date=February 5, 2007 |work=[[Es M\u00e1s]] |language=es |access-date=July 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927015220/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/internacionales/505699.html |archive-date=September 27, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Oposici\u00f3n pide investigar denuncia de periodista Valverde| work = Los Tiempos| location = Cochabamba| accessdate = February 6, 2016| date = February 4, 2016| url = http://www.lostiempos.com/diario/actualidad/nacional/20160204/oposicion-pide-investigar-denuncia-de-periodista-valverde_332040_737980.html| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160206084816/http://www.lostiempos.com/diario/actualidad/nacional/20160204/oposicion-pide-investigar-denuncia-de-periodista-valverde_332040_737980.html| archive-date = February 6, 2016| url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Layme| first = Beatriz| title = Evo afirma que tuvo un hijo con Zapata y que muri\u00f3 en 2007| work = La Raz\u00f3n| location = La Paz, Bolivia| accessdate = February 6, 2016| date = February 6, 2016| url = http://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2016/2/6/afirma-tuvo-hijo-zapata-murio-2007-85925.html| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160207055212/http://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2016/2/6/afirma-tuvo-hijo-zapata-murio-2007-85925.html| archive-date = February 7, 2016| url-status = live}}</ref> Politician [[Juan del Granado]] is Eva Liz's godfather.<ref name=\":0\"/> His children left Bolivia and traveled to [[Buenos Aires]] in late November 2019 .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/argentina/evo-morales-children-arrive-in-buenos-aires.phtml|title=Buenos Aires Times {{!}} Evo Morales' children arrive in Buenos Aires|website=www.batimes.com.ar|access-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMorales has commented that he is only a [[Roman Catholic]] in order \"to go to weddings\", and when asked if he believed in [[God]], responded that \"I believe in the land. In my father and my mother. And in ''[[wikt:cuchi cuchi|cuchi-cuchi]]'' (sexual activity).\"{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=66}} According to some, Evo lives an [[ascetic]] life, with little interest in material possessions.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=218|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=179}} Morales is  an [[association football]] enthusiast and plays the game frequently, often with local teams.<ref>{{cite news | title=Footballing president breaks nose | date=July 31, 2006 | accessdate=July 31, 2006 | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5230572.stm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060816011715/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5230572.stm | archive-date=August 16, 2006 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=La fiesta de gala de los 15 a\u00f1os de Eva Liz Morales |work=El D\u00eda |accessdate=September 25, 2010 |date=November 27, 2009 |url=http://eldia.com.bo/?cat=181&pla=3&id_articulo=20491 |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150427/http://eldia.com.bo/?cat=181&pla=3&id_articulo=20491 |archive-date=July 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMorales's unorthodox behavior contrasts with the usual manners of dignitaries and other political leaders in Latin America. During speeches he made use of personal stories and anecdotes,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=111}} and used [[coca]] as a political symbol, wearing a coca leaf garland around his neck and a hat with coca leaves in it when speaking to crowds of supporters.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=119}} Following his election, he wore striped jumpers rather than the [[men's suit|suits]] typically worn by politicians. It became a symbol of Morales, with copies of it selling widely in Bolivia.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=169}}<ref>{{cite news | date=January 20, 2006 | title='Evo Fashion' arrives in Bolivia | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4630370.stm |website=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315182825/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4630370.stm |archivedate=March 15, 2008 }} Retrieved on February 1, 2007.</ref> \n\nOn July 4, 2018, Morales underwent emergency surgery at a private clinic in La Paz in order to remove a [[tumor]].<ref name=\"reutershealth\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivian-president-morales-has-emergency-surgery-for-tumor-idUSKBN1JV051 |publisher=Reuters |title=Bolivian President Morales has emergency surgery for tumor |first=Aislinn |last=Laing |first2=Daniel |last2=Ramos |editor-first=Leslie |editor-last=Adler |access-date=July 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708225416/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivian-president-morales-has-emergency-surgery-for-tumor-idUSKBN1JV051 |archive-date=July 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Influence and legacy==\n[[File:Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto, Justin Trudeau, and Evo Morales - Lima, Peru - 2018 (40563707215).jpg|thumb|right|Morales with [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] and [[Justin Trudeau]], Lima, Peru, 2018]]\n\nMorales has been described as \"the most famous Bolivian ever\",{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=1}} whose personality has become \"fixed in the global imagination\".{{sfn|Pearce|2011|p=xv}} Morales's government has been seen as part of the [[pink tide]] of left-leaning Latin American governments, becoming particularly associated with the hard left current of Venezuela and Cuba.{{sfnm|1a1=Pearce|1y=2011|1p=xv|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=1}} It has been praised for its pro-socialist stance among the international left,{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=154}} who have taken an interest in Bolivia under his leadership as a \"political laboratory\"{{sfn|Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|2008|p=1}} or \"a living workshop\" for the development of an alternative to capitalism.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=5}} Domestically, Morales's support base has been among Bolivia's poor and indigenous communities.<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> For these communities, who had felt marginalized in Bolivian politics for decades, Morales \"invokes a sense of dignity and destiny\" in a way that no other contemporary politician has done.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=227}} He has received the support of many [[democratic socialism|democratic socialists]] and [[social democracy|social democrats]], as well as sectors of Bolivia's liberal movement, who have been critical of Morales but favored him over the right-wing opposition.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=157\u201358}}\n\nBased on interviews conducted among Bolivians in 2012, John Crabtree and Ann Chaplin described the previous years of Morales's rule with the observation that: \"for many\u2014perhaps most\u2014Bolivians, this was a period when ordinary people felt the benefits of policy in ways that had not been the case for decades, if ever.\"{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} Crabtree and Chaplin added that Morales's administration had made \"important changes... that will probably be difficult to reverse\", including poverty reduction, the removal of some regional inequalities, and side-lining of some previously dominant political actors in favor of others who had been encouraged and enabled by his government.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}}\n\nCritics, particularly in the U.S. government, have varyingly termed him \"a left-wing radical, a partner of narco-traffickers and a terrorist\".{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=173}} Opposition to Morales's governance has centered in the wealthy eastern lowland province of Santa Cruz.<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> His policies often antagonized middle-class Bolivians, who deemed them too radical and argued that they threatened private property.<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> His most vociferous critics have been from Bolivia's conservative movement, although he has also received criticism from the country's far left, who believe his reformist policies have been insufficiently radical or socialist.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=157\u201358}} Many of these leftist critics were unhappy that Morales's government did not make a total break with global capitalism.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} His government has also faced many of the same complaints directed at previous Bolivian administrations, revolving around such issues as \"concentration of power, corruption, incompetent bureaucracies, and disrespect for civil liberties\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=144}}\n\nCrabtree and Chaplin's study led them to conclude that while Morales's initial election had brought \"huge expectations\" from many Bolivians, especially in the social movements, there had been \"inevitable frustrations\" at his administration's inability to deliver on everything that they had hoped.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=vii}} They thought that the \"heady optimism\" that had characterized Morales's first term in office had given way to \"a climate of questioning and growing criticism of the government and its policies\".{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} Although the Bolivian economy had grown, the material benefits had not been as high as many Bolivians had hoped.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} Crabtree and Chaplin argued that the experiences of his administration had \"drawn attention to the difficulties involved in bringing change in the patterns of development in one of Latin America's poorest and most unequal nations\".{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=vi}} Similarly, Harten thought that Morales's discourse of \"the people\" against the socio-economic elites has brought a spotlight on the deep social polarization in Bolivia.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=229}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Domestic policy of Evo Morales]]\n* [[Foreign policy of Evo Morales]]\n* [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite contribution |contribution=Bolivia's New Constitution and its Implications |title=Evo Morales and the Movimiento Al Socialismo in Bolivia: The First Term in Context, 2005\u20132009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6xIYgEACAAJ&dq=The+Rise+of+Evo+Morales+and+the+MAS&hl=en&ei=3B4aTuHLDYrB8QOy5KgH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAw |last=Assies|first=William|others=Adrian J. Pearce (ed.)|year=2011|publisher=Institute for the Study of the Americas|location=London, UK|isbn=978-1-900039-99-4|pages=93\u2013116|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite web|url=https://zcomm.org/znetarticle/from-coca-to-congress-by-evo-morales|title=From Coca To Congress|last=Blackwell|first=Benjamin|website=The Ecologist|date=November 11, 2002|accessdate=January 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105223036/https://zcomm.org/znetarticle/from-coca-to-congress-by-evo-morales|archivedate=January 5, 2016|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Evo Morales wins landslide victory in Bolivian presidential elections|last=Carroll|first=Rory|authorlink=Rory Carroll|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/dec/07/morales-presidential-victory|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK|date=December 7, 2009<!-- |ref=harv -->}}\n\n: {{cite book |last1=Crabtree |first1=John |last2=Chaplin |first2=Ann |title=Bolivia: Processes of Change |year=2013 |location=London and New York |publisher=Zed Books |isbn=978-1-78032-377-0 |ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite journal|last=Dunkerley|first=James|year=2007|title=Evo Morales, the 'Two Bolivias' and the Third Bolivian Revolution|journal=[[Journal of Latin American Studies]]|volume=39|pages=133\u201366|ref=harv|doi=10.1017/s0022216x06002069}}\n: {{cite book|title=Evo's Bolivia: Continuity and Change|url=|last1=Farthing|first1=Linda C.|last2=Kohl|first2=Benjamin H.|year=2014|publisher=University of Texas Press|location=Austin|isbn=978-0292758681|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Morales' Big Win: Voters Ratify His Remaking of Bolivia|last=Friedman-Rudovsky|first=Jean|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1945989,00.html|newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|location=New York City|date=December 7, 2009|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Indian, Coca Farmer, Bolivian President|last=Gutsch|first=Jochen-Martin|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/0,1518,414036,00.html|newspaper=[[Der Spiegel]]|publisher=SPIEGEL-Verlag|location=Germany|date=February 5, 2006|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|title=The Rise of Evo Morales and the MAS|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2XjvRwAACAAJ&dq=The+Rise+of+Evo+Morales+and+the+MAS|last=Harten|first=Sven|year=2011|publisher=Zed Books|location=London and New York|isbn=978-1-84813-523-9|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|title=Revolution!: South America and the Rise of the New Left|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3cU5ELUxXAEC&dq=Revolution!:+South+America+and+the+Rise+of+the+New+Left|last=Kozloff|first=Nicholas|year=2008|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|isbn=978-0-230-61754-4|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite journal|last=Lerager|first=James|year=2006|title=Report on Bolivia's Elections|journal=[[Latin American Perspectives]]|volume=33|issue=2|pages=141\u201344<!--|ref=harv-->|doi=10.1177/0094582X06286848}}\n\n: {{cite news |title=Nobel Committee asked to strip Obama of Peace Prize|last=Lovell |first=Joseph E.|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/304909 |newspaper=Digital Journal|publisher=Digital Journal, Inc.|date=March 21, 2011|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|first=Betilde|title=Electoral Rules and the Transformation of Bolivian Politics: The Rise of Evo Morales |year=2008 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York|isbn=978-0-230-60819-1|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite contribution |contribution=Introduction|title=Evo Morales and the Movimiento Al Socialismo in Bolivia: The First Term in Context, 2005\u20132009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6xIYgEACAAJ&dq=The+Rise+of+Evo+Morales+and+the+MAS&hl=en&ei=3B4aTuHLDYrB8QOy5KgH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAw|last=Pearce|first=Adrian J.|others=Adrian J. Pearce (ed.)|year=2011|publisher=Institute for the Study of the Americas|location=London, UK|isbn=978-1-900039-99-4|pages=xv\u2013xxv|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite journal|title=Evo Morales' Pursuit of 'Normal Capitalism'|last=Petras|first=James|journal=[[Economic and Political Weekly]]|volume=42|issue=23|date=June 9\u201315, 2007|pages=2155\u201358|ref=harv}}<!--\n-->\n\n: {{cite book|title=The Triumph of Politics: The Return of the Left in Venezuela, Bolivia and Ecuador|last1=Philip|first1=George|last2=Panizza|first2=Francisco|year=2011|publisher=Polity Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0745647494|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/triumphofpolitic0000phil}}\n\n: {{cite journal|last=Rochlin|first=James|year=2007|title=Latin America's Left Turn and the New Strategic Landscape: The Case of Bolivia |journal=[[Third World Quarterly]]|volume=28|issue=7|pages=1327\u201342<!--|ref=harv-->|doi=10.1080/01436590701591838}}\n\n: {{cite book|title=Evo Morales: The Extraordinary Rise of the First Indigenous President of Bolivia|url=https://books.google.com/?id=t5ZFs6vTlKwC&dq=Evo+Morales:+The+Extraordinary+Rise+of+the+First+Indigenous+President+of+Bolivia|last=Sivak|first=Mart\u00edn|authorlink=Mart\u00edn Sivak|year=2010|publisher=Palgrave MacMillan|location= New York|isbn=978-0-230-62305-7|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite contribution|contribution=The Bolivianisation of Washington-La Paz Relations: Evo Morales' Foreign Policy Agenda in Historical Context|title=Evo Morales and the Movimiento Al Socialismo in Bolivia: The First Term in Context, 2005\u20132009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6xIYgEACAAJ&dq=The+Rise+of+Evo+Morales+and+the+MAS&hl=en&ei=3B4aTuHLDYrB8QOy5KgH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAw|last=Sivak|first=Mart\u00edn|others=Adrian J. Pearce (ed.)|year=2011|publisher=Institute for the Study of the Americas|location=London, UK|isbn=978-1-900039-99-4|pages=143\u201374|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite book|title=From Rebellion to Reform in Bolivia: Class Struggle, Indigenous Liberation, and the Politics of Evo Morales|url=|last=Webber|first=Jeffrey R.|year=2011|publisher=Haymarket Books|isbn=978-1608461066|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=The explosive apex of Evo's power|url=http://www.economist.com/node/15065929|work=The Economist|date=December 10, 2009|ref=harv}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Bolivia tells US envoy to leave|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7609487.stm|publisher=BBC News|location=London, UK|date=September 11, 2008|ref={{sfnref|BBC News|2008a}}}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Chavez acts over US-Bolivia row|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7611705.stm|publisher=BBC News|location=London, UK|date=September 12, 2008|ref={{sfnref|BBC News|2008b}}}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Bolivia and US 'to restore diplomatic relations'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-15632484|publisher=BBC News|location=London, UK|date=November 8, 2011|ref={{sfnref|BBC News|2011a}}}}\n\n: {{cite news|title=Bolivia's Morales insists no return for US drug agency|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-15649399|publisher=BBC News|location=London, UK|date=November 9, 2011|ref={{sfnref|BBC News|2011b}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |commons=Category:Evo Morales|q=Evo Morales|d=Q42410|b=no|n=no|s=no|v=no|wikt=no}}\n{{Library resources box}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130410181559/http://www.presidencia.gob.bo/ Ministry of the Presidency] {{in lang|es}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12166905 Evo Morales] profile at ''[[BBC News]]''\n* [http://www.cidob.org/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_sur/bolivia/evo_morales_ayma Extended biography and tenure by CIDOB]\n* {{NYT topic|people/m/evo_morales}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]|years=2006\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] <br> Interim}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Portal bar|Bolivia|Argentina|Socialism}}\n\n{{Evo Morales|state=expanded}}\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{2005 presidential election candidates, Bolivia}}\n{{Social democracy}} \n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morales, Evo}}\n\n[[Category:Evo Morales| ]]\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Bolivian people of Aymara descent]]\n[[Category:Bolivian socialists]]\n[[Category:Democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:Indigenous leaders of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Movement for Socialism (Bolivia) politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Oruro Department]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Sun of Peru]]\n[[Category:Presidents pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States]]\n[[Category:Presidents pro tempore of the Union of South American Nations]]\n[[Category:Socialist rulers]]\n[[Category:United Left (Bolivia) politicians]]\n[[Category:South American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:Anti-imperialism in South America]]\n[[Category:Bolivian exiles]]\n[[Category:People expelled from public office]]\n[[Category:Politics of Bolivia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Former Bolivian President and politician}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{spanish name|Morales|Ayma}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Evo Morales\n| image = File:Presidentes del Per\u00fa y Bolivia inauguran Encuentro Presidencial y III Gabinete Binacional Per\u00fa-Bolivia (36962597345) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Morales in 2017\n| order = 65th \n| office = President of Bolivia\n| alt = Morales looking to the side\n| vicepresident = [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]]\n| term_start = 22 January, 2006\n| term_end = 10 November, 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/20/el-mas-reconoce-la-sucesion-por-renuncia-abandono-de-funciones-de-evo-alvaro-238006.html|title=El MAS reconoce la sucesi\u00f3n por renuncia y abandono de funciones de Evo y \u00c1lvaro|website=Pagina Siete|date=November 20, 2019|accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| predecessor = [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]]\n| successor = [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] <small>(''interim'')</small>\n| office1 = [[President pro tempore of the Community of Latin American and Caribbean States|President pro tempore of CELAC]]\n| term_label1 = In role\n| term_start1 = January 14, 2019\n| term_end1 = November 10, 2019\n| predecessor1 = [[Salvador S\u00e1nchez Cer\u00e9n]]\n| successor1 = [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]]\n| office2 = [[President pro tempore of the Union of South American Nations|President pro tempore of UNASUR]]\n| term_label2 = In role\n| term_start2 = April 17, 2018\n| term_end2 = April 16, 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Mauricio Macri]]\n| successor2 = ''Vacant''{{Disputed inline|date=December 2019}}\n| office3 = Leader of the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]]\n| term_start3 = January 1, 1998\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = ''party established''\n| successor3 = \n| office4 = [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly#Chamber of Deputies|Member of the Chamber of Deputies]]<br />for [[Cochabamba Department|Cochabamba]]\n| term_start4 = August 6, 1997\n| term_end4 = January 24, 2002\n| birth_name = Juan Evo Morales Ayma\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1959|10|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Isallavi]], Bolivia\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]]\n| children = 2\n| parents = Dionisio Morales Choque<br />Mar\u00eda Ayma Mamani\n| residence = [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]\n| signature = Evo Morales signature.svg\n<!--Military service-->| nickname = \n| allegiance = {{flagicon|Bolivia}} Bolivia\n| branch = [[Image:Logo del Ej\u00e9rcito de Bolivia..jpg|22px]] [[Bolivian Army]]\n| serviceyears = 1977\u20131978\n| rank = \n| unit = [[Fourth Ingavi Cavalry Regiment]]\n| commands = \n| battles = \n| mawards = \n}}\n'''Juan Evo Morales Ayma'''  ({{IPA-es|\u02c8e\u03b2o mo\u02c8\u027eales}}; born October 26, 1959) is a [[Bolivia|Bolivian]] politician and former \n[[cocalero]] activist who served as the [[President of Bolivia]] from 2006 to 2019. Widely regarded as the country's first president to come from its [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] population,{{efn|Morales is described as the first indigenous president of Bolivia in academic studies of his presidency, such as those of Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian,{{sfn|Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|2008|p=180}} Webber,{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=1}} Philip and Panizza,{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=57}} and Farthing and Kohl,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=1}} as well as in press reports, such as those of [[BBC News]],<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> However, there have been challenges to this claim by critics who have asserted that Morales probably has some European ancestry, and thus on genetic grounds is technically ''[[mestizo]]'' rather than solely indigenous.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} Further, former president [[Enrique Pe\u00f1aranda]] was of substantially indigenous origin. Harten asserted that this argument was \"misguided[,] wrong[... and] above all irrelevant\" because regardless of his genetic makeup, the majority of Bolivians perceive Morales as being the first indigenous president.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} In Bolivian society, indigeneity is a fluid concept rooted in cultural identity;{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} for instance, many indigenous individuals that have settled in urban areas and abandoned their traditional rural customs have come to identify as ''mestizo''.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=22}} }} his administration focused on the implementation of [[leftist]] policies, poverty reduction, and combating the influence of the [[United States]] and multinational corporations in Bolivia. A [[socialist]], he is the head of the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] (MAS) party.\n\n<!--Early life and political activism-->\nBorn to an [[Aymara people|Aymara]] family of [[subsistence farmers]] in Isallawi, [[Orinoca Canton]], Morales undertook a basic education before mandatory military service, in 1978 moving to [[Chapare Province]]. Growing [[coca]] and becoming a trade unionist, he rose to prominence in the ''[[Unique Confederation of Rural Laborers of Bolivia|campesino]]'' (\"rural laborers\") union. In that capacity, he campaigned against U.S. and Bolivian attempts to [[coca eradication|eradicate coca]] as part of the [[War on Drugs]], denouncing these as an [[imperialist]] violation of indigenous Andean culture. His involvement in anti-government [[direct action]] protests resulted in multiple arrests. Morales entered electoral politics in 1995, became the leader of the MAS, and was elected to [[Bolivian National Congress, 1997\u20132002|Congress]] in 1997. Coupled with [[populist]] rhetoric, his campaign focused on issues affecting indigenous and poor communities, advocating land reform and the more equal redistribution of gas wealth. He gained increased visibility through the [[Cochabamba Water War]] and [[Bolivian gas conflict|gas conflict]]. In 2002, he was expelled from Congress for encouraging anti-government protesters, although he came second in [[2002 Bolivian general election|that year's presidential election]].\n\n<!--Presidency-->\n[[2005 Bolivian general election|Once elected in 2005]], Morales increased taxation on the hydrocarbon industry to bolster social spending and emphasized projects to combat illiteracy, poverty, racism, and sexism. Vocally criticizing [[neoliberalism]], Morales' government moved Bolivia towards a [[mixed economy]], reduced its dependence on the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]], and oversaw strong economic growth. Scaling back U.S. influence in the country, he built relationships with leftist governments in the Latin American [[pink tide]]\u2014especially [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]]'s Venezuela and [[Fidel Castro]]'s Cuba\u2014and signed Bolivia into the [[Bolivarian Alliance for the Americas]]. His administration opposed the right-wing autonomist demands of [[media luna|Bolivia's eastern provinces]], won [[2008 Bolivian vote of confidence referendum|a 2008 recall referendum]], and instituted a [[Constitution of Bolivia|new constitution]] that established Bolivia as a [[plurinationalism|plurinational state]]. [[2009 Bolivian general election|Re-elected in 2009]] and [[2014 Bolivian general election|2014]], he oversaw Bolivia's admission to the [[Bank of the South]] and [[Community of Latin American and Caribbean States]] although his popularity was dented by attempts to abolish presidential [[term limits]]. Following the disputed [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 general election]] and [[2019 Bolivian protests|the ensuing unrest]], [[Evo Morales government resignation|Morales agreed to military calls for his resignation]], after which he was granted [[Right of asylum|political asylum]], first in Mexico, then in Argentina. \n\n<!--Reception, legacy, and influence-->\nMorales was decorated with various international awards and received praise both for overseeing economic growth and for significantly reducing poverty and illiteracy in Bolivia. His supporters lauded him as a champion of [[indigenous rights]], [[anti-imperialism]], and [[environmentalism]]. He faced accusations that his defence of coca contributed to illegal [[cocaine]] production and that his calls for domestic protest represented [[sedition]] and [[terrorism]].\n\n==Early life and activism==\n===Childhood, education, and military service: 1959\u201378===\n\nMorales was born in the small rural village of Isallawi in [[Orinoca Canton]], part of western Bolivia's [[Oruro Department]], on October 26, 1959 to a family from the [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|indigenous]] [[Aymara people]].<ref name=oct17bbc />{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=35|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=62}} One of seven children born to Dionisio Morales Choque and his wife Mar\u00eda Ayma Mamani,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/amp/entrega-modulo-educativo-maria-ayma-dice-nunca-influyo-nombramiento-obras-137307.html | title=Evo entrega modulo educativo \"Maria Ayma\" y dice que nunca influy\u00f3 en nombramiento de obras - Diario Pagina Siete | access-date=January 26, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904084711/https://www.paginasiete.bo/amp/entrega-modulo-educativo-maria-ayma-dice-nunca-influyo-nombramiento-obras-137307.html | archive-date=September 4, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> only he and two siblings, Esther and Hugo, survived past childhood.{{sfnm|1a1=Gutsch|1y=2006|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=32|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=35}} His mother almost died from a [[Postpartum hemorrhage|postpartum haemorrhage]] following his birth.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=35}} In keeping with Aymara custom, his father buried the [[placenta]] produced after his birth in a place specially chosen for the occasion.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=35}} His childhood home was a traditional [[adobe]] house,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=33}} and he grew up speaking the [[Aymara language]], although later commentators would remark that by the time he had become president he was no longer an entirely fluent speaker.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=33|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=7|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=63}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| image1 = Aymara ceremony copacabana 4.jpg\n| width1 = 200\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Fishing boat Lake Poopo.jpg\n| width2 = 198\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer = Aymara in traditional dress (left); [[Poop\u00f3 Lake]] was the dominant geographical feature around Morales's home village of Isallawi (right).{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=35}}\n}}\n\nMorales's family were farmers; from an early age, he helped them to plant and harvest crops and guard their herd of llamas and sheep, taking a homemade soccer ball to amuse himself.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=32|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=35}} As a toddler, he briefly attended Orinoca's preparatory school, and at five began schooling at the single-room primary school in Isallawi.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=33\u201334|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=36}} Aged 6, he spent six months in northern Argentina with his sister and father. There, Dionisio harvested sugar cane while Evo sold ice cream and briefly attended a Spanish-language school.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=34|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=36|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3pp=62\u201363}} As a child, he regularly traveled on foot to [[Arani province]] in [[Cochabamba]] with his father and their llamas, a journey lasting up to two weeks, in order to exchange salt and potatoes for maize and coca. {{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=33|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=36\u201337}} A big fan of soccer, at age 13 he organised a community soccer team with himself as team captain. Within two years, he was elected training coach for the whole region, and thus gained early experience in leadership.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=34|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=40}}\n\nAfter finishing primary education, Morales attended the Agrarian Humanistic Technical Institute of Orinoca (ITAHO), completing all but the final year.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=37}} His parents then sent him to study for a degree in [[Oruro, Bolivia|Oruro]]; although he did poorly academically, he finished all of his courses and exams by 1977, earning money on the side as a brick-maker, day labourer, baker and a trumpet player for the Royal Imperial Band. The latter position allowed him to travel across Bolivia.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=34\u201335|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=37|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=63}} At the end of his higher education he failed to collect his degree certificate.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=37}} Although interested in studying journalism, he did not pursue it as a profession.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=35|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=37}}\nMorales served his mandatory [[conscription|military service]] in the Bolivian army from 1977 to 1978. Initially signed up at the Centre for Instruction of Special Troops (CITE) in Cochabamba, he was sent into the Fourth Ingavi Cavalry Regiment and stationed at the army headquarters in the Bolivian capital [[La Paz]].{{sfnm|1a1=Blackwell|1y=2002|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=35|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=37}} These two years were one of Bolivia's politically most unstable periods, with five presidents and two military coups, led by General [[Juan Pereda]] and General [[David Padilla]] respectively; under the latter's regime, Morales was stationed as a guard at the ''[[Palacio Quemado]]'' (Presidential Palace).{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=37\u201338}}\n\n===Early ''cocalero'' activism: 1978\u201383===\nFollowing his military service, Morales returned to his family, who had escaped the agricultural devastation of 1980's ''[[El Ni\u00f1o-Southern Oscillation|El Ni\u00f1o]]'' storm cycle by relocating to the Tropics of [[Cochabamba]] in the eastern lowlands.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=35}} Setting up home in the town of Villa 14 de Septiembre, [[Chapare Province|El Chapare]], using a loan from Morales's maternal uncle, the family cleared a plot of land in the forest to grow rice, oranges, grapefruit, papaya, bananas and later on [[coca]].{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=36|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=39}} It was here that Morales learned to speak [[Quechua languages|Quechua]], the indigenous local language.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=63}} The arrival of the Morales family was a part of a much wider migration to the region; in 1981 El Chapare's population was 40,000 but by 1988 it had risen to 215,000. Many Bolivians hoped to set up farms where they could earn a living growing coca, which was experiencing a steady rise in price and which could be cultivated up to four times a year; a traditional medicinal and ritual substance in Andean culture, it was also sold abroad as the key ingredient in [[cocaine]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=39}} Morales joined the local soccer team, before founding his own team, New Horizon, which proved victorious at the August 2 Central Tournament.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=39}} The El Chapare region remained special to Morales for many years to come; during his presidency he often talked of it in speeches and regularly visited.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=39}}\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Folha de coca.jpg\n| width1 = 200\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = \n| image2 = Mate de coca Peru.jpg\n| width2 = 198\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = \n| footer =  Morales policy was \"Coca Yes, Cocaine No\". A Bolivian man holding a coca leaf, (left); [[Coca tea]], a traditional Andean [[infusion]] (right).\n}}\nIn El Chapare, Morales joined a trade union of ''[[cocalero]]s'' (coca growers), being appointed local Secretary of Sports. Organizing soccer tournaments, among union members he earned the nickname of \"the young ball player\" because of his tendency to organize matches during meeting recesses.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=39}} Influenced in joining the union by wider events, in 1980 the far-right General [[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza]] had seized power in a military coup, banning other political parties and declaring himself president; for Morales, a \"foundational event in his relationship with politics\" occurred in 1981, when a ''campesino'' (coca grower) was accused of cocaine trafficking by soldiers, beaten up, and burned to death.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=40\u201341}} In 1982 the leftist [[Hern\u00e1n Siles Zuazo]] and the [[Democratic and Popular Union]] (''Unidad Democr\u00e1tica y Popular'' \u2013 UDP) took power in [[representative democracy|representative democratic]] elections, before implementing [[neoliberalism|neoliberal capitalist]] reforms and privatizing much of the state sector with US support; hyperinflation came under control, but unemployment rose to 25%.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=40\u201341|2a1=Philip|2a2=Panizza|2y=2011|2pp=76&ndash;77}} Becoming increasingly active in the union, from 1982 to 1983, Morales served as the General Secretary of his local San Francisco syndicate.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}} However, in 1983, Morales's father Dionisio died, and although he missed the funeral he temporarily retreated from his union work to organize his father's affairs.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=40\u201341, 57\u201358}}\n\nFighting their [[War on Drugs]], the U.S. government hoped to stem the cocaine trade by preventing the production of coca; they pressured the Bolivian government to eradicate it, sending troops to Bolivia to aid the operation.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=41}} Bolivian troops would burn coca crops and in many cases beat up coca growers who challenged them.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=109}} Angered by this, Morales returned to ''cocalero'' campaigning; like many of his comrades, he refused the US$2,500 compensation offered by the government for each acre of coca he eradicated. Deeply embedded in Bolivian culture, the ''campesinos'' had an ancestral relationship with coca and did not want to lose their most profitable means of subsistence. For them, it was an issue of national sovereignty, with the U.S. viewed as [[imperialism|imperalists]]; activists regularly proclaimed \"Long live coca! Death to the Yankees!\" (\"''Causachun coca! Wa\u00f1uchun yanquis!''\").{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}}\n\n===General Secretary of the ''Cocalero'' Union: 1984\u201394===\n\nFrom 1984 to 1985 Morales served as Secretary of Records for the movement,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}} and in 1985 he became General Secretary of the August Second Headquarters.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}}\nFrom 1984 to 1991 the ''sindicatos'' embarked on a series of protests against the forced eradication of coca by occupying local government offices, setting up roadblocks, going on hunger strike, and organizing mass marches and demonstrations.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=42|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=109}} Morales was personally involved in this direct activism and in 1984 was present at a roadblock where 3 ''campesinos'' were killed.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=43}} In 1988, Morales was elected to the position of Executive Secretary of the Federation of the Tropics.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=42}} In 1989 he spoke at a one-year commemoratory event of the [[Villa Tunari massacre]] in which 11 coca farmers had been killed by agents of the [[UMOPAR|Rural Area Mobile Patrol Unit]] (''Unidad M\u00f3vil Policial para \u00c1reas Rurales'' \u2013 UMOPAR).{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=43}} The following day, UMOPAR agents beat Morales up, leaving him in the mountains to die, but he was rescued by other union members.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=43, 65}} To combat this violence, Morales concluded that an armed ''cocalero'' militia could launch a [[Guerrilla warfare|guerrilla war]] against the government, but he was soon persuaded on an electoral path to change instead.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=43\u201344, 49}} In 1992, he made various international trips to champion the ''cocalero'' cause, speaking at a conference in Cuba,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=52}} and also traveling to Canada, during which he learned of his mother's death.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=58}}\n\n[[File:Banner of the Qulla Suyu.svg|147px|left|thumb|The [[Wiphala]], flag of the Aymara.]]\n\nIn his speeches, Morales presented the coca leaf as a symbol of Andean culture that was under threat from the imperialist oppression of the U.S. In his view, the U.S. should deal with their domestic cocaine abuse problems without interfering in Bolivia, arguing that they had no right trying to eliminate coca, a legitimate product with many uses which played a rich role in Andean culture.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=74\u201377}} In a speech on this issue, Morales told reporters \"I am not a drug trafficker. I am a coca grower. I cultivate coca leaf, which is a natural product. I do not refine (it into) cocaine, and neither cocaine nor drugs have ever been part of the Andean culture.\"<ref name=\"BBC bio\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Bolivia's President Evo Morales |date=October 13, 2014 |publisher=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12166905 |access-date=June 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012080954/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-12166905 |archive-date=October 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On another, he asserted that \"We produce our coca, we bring it to the main markets, we sell it and that's where our responsibility ends.\"{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=44}}\n\nMorales presented the coca growers as victims of a wealthy, urban social elite who had bowed to U.S. pressure by implementing neoliberal economic reforms.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=74\u201377}} He argued that these reforms were to the detriment of Bolivia's majority, and thus the country's representative democratic system of governance failed to reflect the true democratic will of the majority.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=74\u201377}} This situation was exacerbated following [[1993 Bolivian general election|the 1993 general election]] when the centrist [[Revolutionary Nationalist Movement]] (''Movimiento Nacionalista Revolucionario'' \u2013 MNR) won the election and [[Gonzalo S\u00e1nchez de Lozada]] became President. He adopted a policy of \"[[Shock therapy (economics)|shock therapy]]\", implementing economic liberalization and widescale privatization of state-owned assets.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=97\u201399}} S\u00e1nchez also agreed with the U.S. DEA to relaunch its offensive against the Bolivian coca growers, committing Bolivia to eradicating {{convert|12500|acre|ha}} of coca by March 1994 in exchange for $20 million worth of US aid, something Morales claimed would be opposed by the cocalero movement.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=44\u201345}}\n\nIn August 1994 Morales was arrested; reporters present at the scene witnessed him being beaten and accosted with racial slurs by civil agents. Accused of sedition, in jail he began a dry hunger strike to protest his arrest.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=45}} The following day, 3000 ''campesinos'' began a {{convert|360|mi|km|adj=on}} march from [[Villa Tunari]] to La Paz. Morales would be freed on September 7, and soon joined the march, which arrived at its destination on September 19, where they covered the city with political graffiti.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=45\u201347}} He was again arrested in April 1995 during a sting operation that rounded up those at a meeting of the Andean Council of Coca Producers that he was chairing on the shores of Lake Titicaca. Accusing the group of plotting a coup with the aid of Colombia's [[FARC]] and Peru's [[Shining Path]], a number of his comrades were tortured, although no evidence of a coup was brought forth and he was freed within a week.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=47}} He proceeded to Argentina to attend a seminar on liberation struggles.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=47\u201349}}\n\n==Political rise==\n===The ASP, IPSP, and MAS: 1995\u201399===\nMembers of the ''sindicato'' social movement first suggested a move into the political arena in 1986. This was controversial, with many fearing that politicians would co-opt the movement for personal gain.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=83}} Morales began supporting the formation of a political wing in 1989, although a consensus in favor of its formation only emerged in 1993.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} On March 27, 1995, at the 7th Congress of the [[Unique Confederation of Rural Laborers of Bolivia]] (''Confederaci\u00f3n Sindical \u00danica de Trabajadores Campesinos de Bolivia'' \u2013 CSUTCB), a \"political instrument\" (a term employed over \"political party\") was formed, named the [[Assembly for the Sovereignty of the Peoples]] (''Asamblea por la Sobern\u00eda de los Pueblos'' \u2013 ASP).{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=84|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}} At the ASP's 1st Congress, the CSUTCB participated alongside three other Bolivian unions, representing miners, peasants and indigenous peoples.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} In 1996, Morales was appointed chairman of the Committee of the Six Federations of the Tropics of Cochabamba, a position that he retained until 2006.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=79}}\n\nBolivia's [[National Electoral Court of Bolivia|National Electoral Court]] (''Corte Nacional Electoral'' \u2013 CNE) refused to recognize the ASP, citing minor procedural infringements.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} The coca activists circumvented this problem by running under the banner of the [[United Left (Bolivia)|United Left]] (IU), a coalition of leftist parties headed by the [[Communist Party of Bolivia]] (''Partido Comunista Boliviano'' \u2013 PCB).{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=24|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=79|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=84|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=60}} They won landslide victories in those areas which were local strongholds of the movement, producing 11 mayors and 49 municipal councilors.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=84}} Morales was elected to the Chamber of Deputies in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|National Congress]] as a representative for El Chapare, having secured 70.1% of the local vote.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=79}} In the [[1997 Bolivian legislative election|national elections of 1997]], the IU/ASP gained four seats in Congress, obtaining 3.7% of the national vote, with this rising to 17.5% in the department of Cochabamba.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=85}} The election resulted in the establishment of a coalition government led by the right-wing [[Nationalist Democratic Action]] (''Acci\u00f3n Democr\u00e1tica Nacionalista'' \u2013 ADN), with [[Hugo Banzer]] as President; Morales lambasted him as \"the worst politician in Bolivian history\".{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=79\u201380}}\n\n[[File:MAS XVI Anniversary Celebration.jpg|thumb|MAS-IPSP partisans celebrate the 16th anniversary of the IPSP party's founding in [[Sacaba]], [[Cochabamba Department|Cochabamba]].]]\nRising electoral success was accompanied by factional in-fighting, with a leadership contest emerging in the ASP between the incumbent [[Alejo V\u00e9liz]] and Morales, who had the electoral backing of the social movement's bases.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=85}} The conflict led to a schism, with Morales and his supporters splitting to form their own party, the Political Instrument for the Sovereignty of the Peoples (''Instrumento Pol\u00edtico por la Soberan\u00eda de los Pueblos'' \u2013 IPSP).{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=85|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}} The movement's bases defected ''en masse'' to the IPSP, leaving the ASP to crumble and V\u00e9liz to join the centre-right [[New Republican Force]] (''Nueva Fuerza Republicana'' \u2013 NFR), for which Morales denounced him as a traitor to the ''cocalero'' cause.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=86}} Continuing his activism, in 1998 Morales led another ''cocalero'' march from El Chapare to la Paz,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=81}} and came under increasing criticism from the government, who repeatedly accused him of being involved in the cocaine trade and mocked him for how he spoke and his lack of education.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=81\u201382}}\n\nMorales came to an agreement with [[David A\u00f1ez Pedraza]], the leader of a defunct yet still registered party named the Movement for Socialism (MAS); under this agreement, Morales and the Six Federaci\u00f3nes could take over the party name, with Pendraza stipulating the condition that they must maintain its own acronym, name and colors. Thus the defunct right wing MAS became the flourishing left wing vehicle for the coca activist movement known as the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism \u2013 Political Instrument for the Sovereignty of the Peoples]].{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=86|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}} The MAS would come to be described as \"an indigenous-based political party that calls for the nationalization of industry, legalization of the coca leaf ... and fairer distribution of national resources.\"<ref name=\"In these times\">{{cite news | date=December 18, 2005 | title=Evo Morales Has Plans for Bolivia | author=America Vera-Zavala | work=In These Times | url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/site/main/article/2438/ |accessdate=February 7, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150303110107/http://inthesetimes.com/article/2438 |archivedate=March 3, 2015 }}</ref> The party lacked the finance available to the mainstream parties, and so relied largely on the work of volunteers in order to operate.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=89\u201390|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=87}} It was not structured like other political parties, instead operating as the political wing of the social movement, with all tiers in the movement involved in decision making; this form of organisation would continue until 2004.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=89\u201390}}\nIn the [[1999 Bolivian municipal elections|December 1999 municipal elections]], the MAS secured 79 municipal council seats and 10 mayoral positions, gaining 3.27% of the national vote, although 70% of the vote in Cochabamba.{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1p=86|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=60}}\n\n===Cochabamba protests: 2000\u201302===\nIn 2000, the Tunari Waters corporation doubled the price at which they sold water to Bolivian consumers, resulting in a backlash from leftist activist groups, including the ''cocaleros''. Activists clashed with police and armed forces, in what was dubbed \"[[2000 Cochabamba protests|the Water War]]\", resulting in 6 dead and 175 wounded. Responding to the violence, the government removed the contract from Tunari and placed the utility under cooperative control.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=82\u201383|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=112\u2013118|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=11}} In ensuing years further violent protests broke out over a range of issues, resulting in more deaths both among activists and law enforcement. Much of this unrest was connected with the widespread opposition to economic liberalization across Bolivian society, with a common perception that it only benefited a small minority.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=107, 117}}\n\nIn the Andean High Plateau, a ''cocalero'' group launched a guerrilla uprising under the leadership of [[Felipe Quispe]]; an ethnic separatist, he and Morales disliked each other, with Quispe considering Morales to be a traitor and an opportunist for his willingness to cooperate with [[White Bolivians]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=83\u201384}}\nMorales had not taken a leading role in these protests, but did use them to get across his message that the MAS was not a single-issue party, and that rather than simply fighting for the rights of the ''cocalero'' it was arguing for structural change to the political system and a redefinition of citizenship in Bolivia.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=126}}\n[[File:Evomorales.jpg|left|thumb|Evo Morales (right) with French labor union leader [[Jos\u00e9 Bov\u00e9]] in 2002]]\nIn August 2001, Banzer resigned due to terminal illness, and [[Jorge Quiroga]] took over as President.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=84}} Under U.S. pressure, Quiroga sought to have Morales expelled from Congress. To do so, he claimed that Morales's inflammatory language had caused the deaths of two police officers in [[Sacaba]] near Cochabamba, however was unable to provide any evidence of Morales's culpability. 140 deputies voted for Morales's expulsion, which came about in 2002. Morales asserted that it \"was a trial against Aymara and Quechas\", {{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=84\u201385}} while MAS activists interpreted it as evidence of the pseudo-democratic credentials of the political class.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=117}}\n\nThe MAS gained increasing popularity as a [[protest party]], relying largely on widespread dissatisfaction with the existing mainstream political parties among Bolivians living in rural and poor urban areas.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=95\u201396}} Morales recognized this, and much of his discourse focused on differentiating the MAS from the traditional political class.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=102}} Their campaign was successful, and in the [[2002 Bolivian presidential election|2002 presidential election]] the MAS gained 20.94% of the national vote, becoming Bolivia's second largest party, being only 1.5% behind the victorious MNR, whose candidate, [[Gonzalo S\u00e1nchez de Lozada]], became President.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=149|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=90|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=87|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=63|5a1=Farthing|5a2=Kohl|5y=2014|5pp=11\u201312}} They won 8 seats in the Senate and 27 in the Chamber of Deputies.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=87}} Now the leader of the [[Opposition (parliamentary)|political opposition]], Morales focused on criticising government policies rather than outlining alternatives. He had several unconstructive meetings with Lozada, but met with Venezuela's [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]] for the first time.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=94-96}}\n\nBolivia's U.S. embassy had become publicly highly critical of Morales; just prior to the election, the U.S. ambassador to Bolivia [[Manuel Rocha]] issued a statement declaring that U.S. aid to Bolivia would be cut if MAS won the election. However, [[exit poll]]s revealed that Rocha's comments had served to increase support for Morales.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=86\u201387|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=158|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=87}} Following the election, the U.S. embassy maintained this critical stance, characterising Morales as a criminal and encouraging Bolivia's traditional parties to sign a broad agreement to oppose the MAS; Morales himself began alleging that the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] was plotting to assassinate him.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=95, 98|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=159}}\n\n===Rise to prominence: 2003\u201305===\n[[File:Evo Morales y Garcia Linera en El Potosi.jpg|thumb|right|Morales with his Vice Presidential running mate, \u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera, in 2005]]\n\nIn 2003, the [[Bolivian gas conflict]] broke out as activists \u2013 including coca growers \u2013 protested against the privatization of the country's natural gas supply and its sale to U.S. companies below the market value. Activists blocked off the road into La Paz, resulting in clashes with police. 80 were killed and 411 injured, among them officers, activists, and civilians, including children.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1pp=164\u2013167|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=99\u2013103|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3pp=118\u2013124}} Morales did not take an active role in the conflict, instead traveling to Libya and Switzerland, there describing the uprising as a \"peaceful revolution in progress.\"{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=100}} The government accused Morales and the MAS of using the protests to overthrow Bolivia's parliamentary democracy with the aid of organised crime, [[FARC]], and the [[Far-left politics|far-left]] governments of Venezuela, Cuba, and Libya.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=122\u2013123}}\n\nMorales led calls for President S\u00e1nchez de Lozada to step down over the death toll, gaining widespread support from the MAS, other activist groups, and the middle classes; with pressure building, S\u00e1nchez resigned and fled to [[Miami]], [[Florida]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=167|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=101\u2013103|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3pp=122\u2013124}} He was replaced by [[Carlos Mesa]], who tried to strike a balance between U.S. and cocalero demands, but whom Morales mistrusted.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=167|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=137\u2013139|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=80}} In November, Morales spent 24 hours with Cuban President [[Fidel Castro]] in [[Havana]],{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=103\u2013104}} and then met Argentinian President [[Nestor Kirchner]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=138}} In the 2004 municipal election, the MAS became the country's largest national party, with 28.6% of all councilors in Bolivia. However, they had failed to win the mayoralty in any big cities, reflecting their inability to gain widespread support among the urban middle-classes.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=142|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=88}} In Bolivia's wealthy [[Santa Cruz Department (Bolivia)|Santa Cruz]] region, a strong movement for autonomy had developed under the leadership of the Pro Santa Cruz Committee (''Comite Pro Santa Cruz''). Favorable to neoliberal economics and strongly critical of the cocaleros, they considered armed insurrection to secede from Bolivia should MAS take power.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=141\u2013142}}\n\nIn March 2005, Mesa resigned, citing the pressure of Morales and the cocalero road blocks and riots.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=175|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=142\u2013145|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=14}} Amid fears of civil war,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=146}} [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] became President of a [[transitional government]], preparing Bolivia for a [[2005 Bolivian presidential election|general election in December 2005]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=175|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=147}} Hiring the Peruvian Walter Ch\u00e1vez as its campaign manager, the MAS electoral campaign was based on [[Salvador Allende]]'s successful campaign in the [[1970 Chilean presidential election]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=148\u2013149}} Measures were implemented to institutionalize the party structure, giving it greater independence from the social movement; this was done to allow Morales and other MAS leaders to respond quickly to new developments without the lengthy process of consulting the bases, and to present a more moderate image away from the bases' radicalism.{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1pp=140, 151|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=68}} Although he had initially hoped for a female running mate, Morales eventually chose Marxist intellectual [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] as his Vice Presidential candidate,{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1pp=179\u2013180|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=150\u2013151|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=88|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=64}} with some Bolivian press speculating as to a romantic relationship between the two.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=139}} MAS' primary opponent was [[Jorge Quiroga]] and his center-right [[Social and Democratic Power]], whose campaign was centered in Santa Cruz and which advocated continued neo-liberal reform; Quiroga accused Morales of promoting the legalization of cocaine and being a [[puppet state|puppet]] for Venezuela.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=177|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=152}}\n\nWith a turnout of 84.5%, the election saw Morales gain 53.7% of the vote, while Quiroga came second with 28.6%; Morales's was the first victory with an [[absolute majority]] in Bolivia for 40 years.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=178|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=155\u2013158|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=88|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=50}} Given that he was the sixth self-described leftist president to be elected in Latin America since 1998, his victory was identified as part of the broader regional [[pink tide]].{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1p=1|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=2|3a1=Pearce|3y=2011|3p=xv}} Becoming [[president elect]], Morales was widely described as Bolivia's first indigenous leader, at a time when around 62% of the population identified as indigenous; political analysts therefore drew comparisons with the election of [[Nelson Mandela]] to the [[1994 South African general election|South African Presidency in 1994]].{{sfnm|1a1=Harten|1y=2011|1pp=88\u201389|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=1, 70}} This resulted in widespread excitement among the approximately 40 million indigenous people in the Americas, particularly those of Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=1\u20132}} However, his election caused concern among the country's wealthy and landowning classes, who feared state expropriation and nationalisation of their property, as well as far-right groups, who claimed it would spark a [[race war]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=1\u20132}} He traveled to Cuba to spend time with Castro, before going to Venezuela, and then on tour to Europe, China, and South Africa; significantly, he avoided the U.S.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=156\u2013157|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=1}} In January 2006, Morales attended an indigenous spiritual ceremony at [[Tiwanaku]] where he was crowned [[Apu Mallku]] (''Supreme Leader'') of the Aymara, receiving gifts from indigenous peoples across Latin America. He thanked the goddess [[Pachamama]] for his victory and proclaimed that \"With the unity of the people, we're going to end the colonial state and the neo-liberal model.\"{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=117\u2013118|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=159|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=35}}\n\n==Presidency==\n{{main|Presidency of Evo Morales}}\n\n===First presidential term: 2006\u201309===\n\n{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=In the world there are large and small countries, rich countries and poor countries, but we are equal in one thing, which is our right to dignity and sovereignty.|source=\u2014 Evo Morales, Inaugural Speech, 22 January 2006.{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1p=133|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=161}} }}\n\nMorales's inauguration took place on January 22 in La Paz. It was attended by various heads of state, including Argentina's Kirchner, Venezuela's Ch\u00e1vez, Brazil's [[Lula da Silva]], and Chile's [[Ricardo Lagos]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=160}} Morales wore an Andeanized suit designed by fashion designer [[Beatriz Canedo Pati\u00f1o]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gutsch|1y=2006|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=158}} and gave a speech that included a minute silence in memory of cocaleros and indigenous activists killed in the struggle.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=160}} He condemned Bolivia's former \"colonial\" regimes, likening them to [[South Africa under apartheid]] and stating that the MAS' election would lead to a \"refoundation\" of the country, a term that the MAS consistently used over \"revolution\".{{sfn|Dunkerley|2007|p=146}} Morales repeated these views in his convocation of the Constituent Assembly.{{sfn|Dunkerley|2007|pp=146\u2013147}}\n\nIn taking office, Morales emphasized nationalism, anti-imperialism, and anti-neoliberalism, although did not initially refer to his administration as socialist.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=214\u2013215}} He immediately reduced both his own presidential wage and that of his ministers by 57% to $1,875 a month, also urging members of Congress to do the same.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=195|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=179|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3pp=35\u201336}}{{sfn|Gutsch|2006}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivian president slashes salary for public schools |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-01-28-morales-salary_x.htm |date=January 28, 2006 |website=USA Today |accessdate=January 5, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228201501/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2006-01-28-morales-salary_x.htm |archivedate=December 28, 2013 }}</ref> Morales gathered together a largely inexperienced [[Cabinet of Bolivia|cabinet]] made up of indigenous activists and leftist intellectuals,{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1p=134|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2p=195|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3pp=179\u2013180}} although over the first three years of government there was a rapid turnover in the cabinet as Morales replaced many of the indigenous members with trained middle-class leftist politicians.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=58}} By 2012 only 3 of the 20 cabinet members identified as indigenous.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=65}}\n\n====Economic program====\nAt Morales's election, Bolivia was South America's poorest nation.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=99}} Morales's government did not initiate fundamental change to Bolivia's economic structure,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=79}} and in their National Development Plan (PDN) for 2006\u201310, adhered largely to the country's previous liberal economic model.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=192}} Bolivia's economy was based largely on the extraction of [[natural resources]], with the nation having South America's second largest reserves of natural gas.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1pp=77\u201378|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=81}} As per his election pledge, Morales took increasing state control of this [[hydrocarbon]] industry with Supreme Decree 2870; previously, corporations paid 18% of their profits to the state, but Morales symbolically reversed this, so that 82% of profits went to the state and 18% to the companies. The oil companies threatened to take the case to the international courts or cease operating in Bolivia, but ultimately relented. Thus, where Bolivia had received $173 million from hydrocarbon extraction in 2002, by 2006 they received $1.3 billion.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=199\u2013203|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=180\u2013181|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3pp=80\u201381}} Although not technically a form of nationalization, Morales and his government referred to it as such, resulting in criticism from sectors of the Bolivian left.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=39}} In June 2006, Morales announced his desire to nationalize mining, electricity, telephones, and railroads, and in February 2007 nationalized the [[Vinto]] metallurgy plant, refusing to compensate [[Glencore]], which the government asserted had obtained the contract illegally.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=203\u2013204|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=74\u201375}} Although the FSTMB miners' federation called for the government to nationalise the mines, the government did not do so, instead stating that any transnational corporations operating in Bolivia legally would not be expropriated.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=107}}\n\n[[File:Morales 20060113 02.jpg|thumb|left|Evo Morales in 2006]]\n\nUnder Morales, Bolivia experienced unprecedented economic strength, resulting in the increase in value of its currency, the [[boliviano]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=85}} His first year in office ended with no [[fiscal deficit]]; the first time this had happened in Bolivia for 30 years,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=107}} while during the global [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]] it maintained some of the world's highest levels of economic growth.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=87}} Such economic strength led to a nationwide boom in construction,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=85}} and allowed the state to build up strong financial reserves.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=85}} Although the levels of social spending were increased, they remained relatively conservative, with a major priority being placed on constructing paved roads, as well as community spaces such as soccer fields and union buildings.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=198|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=85, 87}} In particular, the government focused on rural infrastructure improvement, to bring roads, running water, and electricity to areas that lacked them.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=98}}\n\nThe government's stated intention was to reduce Bolivia's most acute poverty levels from 35% to 27% of the population, and moderate poverty levels from 58.9% to 49% over five years.{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1pp=133\u2013134|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=205\u2013206}}\nThe welfare state was expanded, as characterized by the introduction of non-contributory old-age pensions and payments to mothers provided their babies are taken for health checks and that their children attend school. Hundreds of free tractors were also handed out. The prices of gas and many foodstuffs were controlled, and local food producers were made to sell in the local market rather than export. A new state-owned body was also set up to distribute food at subsidized prices. All these measures helped to curb inflation, while the economy grew (partly because of rising public spending), accompanied by stronger public finances which brought economic stability.<ref name=\"The explosive apex of Evo's power\">{{cite news| url=http://www.economist.com/node/15065929 |website=The Economist |title=The explosive apex of Evo's power |date=December 10, 2009 |accessdate=January 5, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406092712/http://www.economist.com/node/15065929 |archivedate=April 6, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring Morales's first term, Bolivia broke free of the domination of the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) which had characterised previous regimes by refusing their financial aid and connected regulations.{{clarify|date=June 2017}}{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2011|1p=145|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=73}} In May 2007, it became the world's first country to withdraw from the [[International Center for the Settlement of Investment Disputes]], with Morales asserting that the institution had consistently favored multinational corporations in its judgments; Bolivia's lead was followed by other Latin American nations.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=73}} Despite being encouraged to do so by the U.S., Bolivia refused to join the [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]], deeming it a form of U.S. imperialism.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=162}}\n\nA major dilemma faced by Morales's administration was between the desire to expand extractive industries in order to fund social programs and provide employment, and to protect the country's environment from the pollution caused by those industries.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=91}} Although his government professed an environmentalist ethos, expanding environmental monitoring and becoming a leader in the voluntary [[Forest Stewardship Council]], Bolivia continued to witness rapid deforestation for agriculture and illegal logging.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=91\u201392}}\nEconomists on both the left and right expressed concern over the government's lack of economic diversification.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=87}}\nMany Bolivians opined that Morales's government had failed to bring about sufficient job creation.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=79}}\n\n====ALBA and international appearances====\n[[File:F\u00f3rum Social Mundial 2008 - AL.jpg|thumb|Morales with regional allies, at the F\u00f3rum Social Mundial for Latin America: President of Paraguay [[Fernando Lugo|Lugo]], President of Brasil [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula]], President of Equador [[Rafael Correa|Correa]] and President of Venezuela [[Hugo Chavez|Chavez]].]]\n\nMorales's administration sought strong links with the far-left governments of Cuba and Venezuela.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2011|1p=63|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=40|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=75}} In April 2005 Morales traveled to [[Havana]] for knee surgery, there meeting with the two nations' presidents, Castro and Ch\u00e1vez.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=70}} In April 2006, Bolivia agreed to join Cuba and Venezuela in founding the [[Bolivarian Alliance for the Americas|Bolivarian Alternative for the Americas]] (ALBA), with Morales attending ALBA's conference in May, at which they initiated with a Peoples' Trade Agreement (PTA).{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=70|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=41|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=75}} Meanwhile, his administration became \"the least US-friendly government in Bolivian history\".{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=160}} In September Morales visited the U.S. for the first time to attend the [[UN General Assembly]], where he gave a speech condemning U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] as a terrorist for launching the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq War]], and called for the [[United Nations Headquarters|UN Headquarters]] to be moved out of the country. In the U.S., he met with former presidents [[Bill Clinton]] and [[Jimmy Carter]] and with [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly|Native American groups]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=180\u2013181, 187\u2013189}} Relations were further strained between the two nations when in December Morales issued a Supreme Decree requiring all U.S. citizens visiting Bolivia to have a visa.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=165}} His government also refused to grant legal immunity to U.S. soldiers in Bolivia; hence the U.S. cut back their military support to the country by 96%.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=162}}\n\nIn December 2006, he attended the first [[South\u2013South cooperation|South-South conference]] in [[Abuja]], Nigeria, there meeting Libyan leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]], whose government had recently awarded Morales the [[Al-Gaddafi International Prize for Human Rights]].{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=58\u201361}} Morales proceeded straight to Havana for a conference celebrating Castro's life, where he gave a speech arguing for stronger links between Latin America and the Middle East to combat U.S. imperialism.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=68\u201369}} Under his administration, diplomatic relations were established with Iran, with Morales praising [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] as a revolutionary comrade.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=167}} In April 2007 he attended the first [[South American Energy Summit]] in Venezuela, arguing with many allies over the issue of [[biofuel]], which he opposed.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=114\u2013115}} He had a particularly fierce argument with Brazilian President Lula over Morales's desire to bring Bolivia's refineries \u2013 which were largely owned by Brazil's [[Petrobr\u00e1s]] \u2013 under state control. In May, Bolivia purchased the refineries and transferred them to the [[YPFB|Bolivian State Petroleum Company]] (YPFB).{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=114\u2013115, 124\u2013125|2a1=Philip|2a2=Panizza|2y=2011|2pp=143&ndash;145}}\n\n====Social reform====\n[[File:Moraleslula 20060113 02.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Morales with Brazilian President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva|Lula]]]]\nMorales's government sought to encourage a model of development based upon the premise of ''vivir bien'', or \"to live well\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=99}} This entailed seeking social harmony, consensus, the elimination of discrimination, and wealth redistribution; in doing so, it was rooted in communal rather than individual values and owed more to indigenous Andean forms of social organization than Western ones.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=99}}\n\nUpon Morales's election, Bolivia's illiteracy rate was at 16%, the highest in South America.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=124\u2013125|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=104\u2013105}} Attempting to rectify this with the aid of far left allies, Bolivia launched a literacy campaign with Cuban assistance, while Venezuela invited 5000 Bolivian high school graduates to study in Venezuela for free.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=124\u201325|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=104\u201305}} By 2009, [[UNESCO]] declared Bolivia free from illiteracy,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=227}} although the World Bank claimed that it had only declined by 5%.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=105}} Cuba also aided Bolivia in the development of its medical care, opening ophthalmological centres in the country to treat 100,000 Bolivians for free per year, and offering 5000 free scholarships for Bolivian students to study medicine in Cuba.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=41|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=110}} The government sought to expand state medical facilities, opening twenty hospitals by 2014, and increasing basic medical coverage up to the age of 25.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=109\u2013110}} Their approach sought to utilise and harmonise both mainstream Western medicine and Bolivia's [[traditional medicine]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=109}}\n\nThe 2006 Bono Juancito Pinto program provided US$29 per month to poor families for every young child that they had,{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=198|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=102}} while 2008's Renta Dignidad initiative provided around $344 per month to low-income citizens over 60.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=200|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=101\u2013102}} 2009's Bono Juana Azurduy program offered cash transfers to uninsured mothers to improve their likelihood of seeking medical care.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=200}} Conservative critics of Morales's government claimed that these measures were simply designed to buy off the poor and ensure continued support for the government.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=112}}\n\nMorales announced that one of the top priorities of his government was to eliminate racism against the country's indigenous population.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=123}} To do this, he announced that all civil servants were required to learn one of Bolivia's three indigenous languages, Quechua, Aymara, or Guaran\u00ed, within two years.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1p=123|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=103}} His government encouraged the development of indigenous cultural projects,{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|pp=123\u2013124}} and sought to encourage more indigenous people to attend university; by 2008, it was estimated that half of the students enrolled in Bolivia's 11 public universities were indigenous,{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=124}} while three indigenous-specific universities had been established, offering subsidized education.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=107\u2013108}} In 2009, a Vice Ministry for Decolonization was established, which proceeded to pass the 2010 Law against Racism and Discrimination banning the espousal of racist views in private or public institutions.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=58, 65}}\nVarious commentators noted that there was a renewed sense of pride among the country's indigenous population following Morales's election.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=126}} Conversely, the opposition accused Morales's administration of aggravating racial tensions between indigenous, white, and mestizo populations,{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=123, 127}} with some non-indigenous Bolivians feeling that they were now experiencing racism.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1pp=115\u201316, 121|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=92}}\n\n[[File:Evo shoeshine.jpg|thumb|left|Morales and vice-president [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] in 2006 [[Shoeshiner|shining the shoes]] of shoeshine boys.]]\n\nOn [[International Workers' Day]] 2006, Morales issued a presidential decree undoing aspects of the informalization of labor which had been implemented by previous neoliberal governments; this was seen as a highly symbolic act for [[labor rights]] in Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=68}} In 2009 his government put forward suggested reforms to the 1939 labor laws, although lengthy discussions with trade unions hampered the reforms' progress.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=69}} Morales's government increased the legal minimum wage by 50%,{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1p=165|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=69}} and reduced the pension age from 65 to 60, and then in 2010 reduced it again to 58.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=102}}\n\nWhile policies were brought in to improve the living conditions of the working classes, conversely many middle-class Bolivians felt that they had seen their social standing decline,{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=121}} with Morales personally mistrusting the middle-classes, deeming them fickle.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=217}} A 2006 law reallocated state-owned lands,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=121}} with this agrarian reform entailing distributing land to traditional communities rather than individuals.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=165}} In 2010, a law was introduced permitting the formation of recognised indigenous territories, although the implementation of this was hampered by bureaucracy and contesting claims over ownership.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=124\u201325}} Morales's government also sought to improve women's rights in Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=66}} In 2010, it founded a Unit of Depatriarchalization to oversee this process.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=58}} Further seeking to provide legal recognition and support to [[LGBT rights]], it declared June 28 to be Sexual Minority Rights Day in the country,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=71}} and encouraged the establishment of a gay-themed television show on the state channel.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=155}}\n\nAdopting a policy known as \"Coca Yes, Cocaine No\",{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=128}} Morales's administration ensured the legality of coca growing, but also introduced measures to regulate the production and trade of the crop.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|pp=119\u2013200}} In 2007, they announced that they would permit the growing of 50,000 acres of coca in the country, primarily for the purposes of domestic consumption,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=133}} with each family being restricted to the growing of one ''cato'' (1600 metres squared) of coca.{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=164}}\n\nA social control program was implemented whereby local unions took on responsibility for ensuring that this quota was not exceeded; in doing so, they hoped to remove the need for military and police intervention, and thus stem the violence of previous decades.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=135\u2013136}} Measures were implemented to ensure the industrialization of coca production, with Morales inaugurating the first coca industrialization plant in [[Chulumani]], which produced and packaged coca and trimate tea; the project was primarily funded through a $125,000 donation from Venezuela under the PTA scheme.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|pp=119\u2013200}}\n\nThese industrialization measures proved largely unsuccessful given that coca remained illegal in most nations outside Bolivia, thus depriving the growers of an international market.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=137}} Campaigning against this, in 2012 Bolivia withdrew from the UN 1961 Convention which had called for global criminalisation of coca, and in 2013 successfully convinced the [[UN Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs]] to declassify coca as a narcotic.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=133\u201334}} The U.S. State Department criticised Bolivia, asserting that it was regressing in its counter-narcotics efforts, and dramatically reduced aid to Bolivia to $34 million to fight the narcotics trade in 2007.{{sfnm|1a1=Kozloff|1y=2008|1p=120|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=181\u201382}} Nevertheless, the number of cocaine seizures in Bolivia increased under Morales's government,{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=141}} as they sought to encourage coca growers to report and oppose cocaine producers and traffickers.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=140}} However, high levels of police corruption surrounding the illicit trade in cocaine remained a continuing problem for Bolivia.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=142}}\n\nMorales's government also introduced measures to tackle Bolivia's endemic corruption; in 2007, he used a presidential decree to create the Ministry of Institutional Transparency and Fight Against Corruption.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=43}} However, critics highlighted that MAS members were rarely prosecuted for the crime, the main exception being YPFB head [[Santos Ram\u00edrez]], who was sentenced to twelve years imprisonment for corruption in 2008. Conversely, a 2009 law that permitted the retroactive prosecution for corruption led to legal cases being brought against a number of opposition politicians for alleged corruption in the pre-Morales period; many fled abroad to avoid standing trial.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=44}}\n\n====Domestic unrest and the new constitution====\nDuring his presidential campaign, Morales had supported calls for regional autonomy for Bolivia's departments. As president, he changed his position, viewing the calls for autonomy \u2013 which came from [[Media Luna|Bolivia's four eastern departments]] of Santa Cruz, [[Beni Department|Beni]], [[Pando Department|Pando]], and [[Tarija]] \u2013 as an attempt by the wealthy bourgeoisie living in these regions to preserve their economic position.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=210}} He nevertheless agreed to a [[2006 Bolivian regional autonomy referendum|referendum on regional autonomy]], held in July 2006; the four eastern departments voted in favor of autonomy, but Bolivia as a whole voted against it by 57.6%.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=210|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=87|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=47}} In September, autonomy activists launched strikes and blockades across eastern Bolivia, resulting in violent clashes with MAS activists.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=212|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=96}} In January 2007, clashes in Cochabamba between activist groups led to fatalities, with Morales's government sending in troops to maintain the peace. The left-indigenous activists formed a Revolutionary Departmental Government, but Morales denounced it as illegal and continued to recognise the legitimacy of right-wing departmental head [[Manfred Reyes Villa]].{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=111\u2013124}}\n\nIn July 2006, an [[2006 Bolivian Constitutional Assembly election|election to form a Constitutional Assembly]] was held, which saw the highest ever electoral turnout in the nation's history. MAS won 137 of its 255 seats, after which the Assembly was inaugurated in August.{{sfnm|1a1=Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|1y=2008|1pp=182\u2013183|2a1=Sivak|2y=2010|2pp=210, 212|3a1=Harten|3y=2011|3p=181|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4pp=39\u201340}} The Assembly was the first elected parliamentary body in Bolivia which features strong campesino and indigenous representation.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|pp=23\u201324}} In November, the Assembly approved [[Constitution of Bolivia|a new constitution]], which converted the Republic of Bolivia into the Plurinational State of Bolivia, describing it as a \"plurinational communal and social unified state\". The constitution emphasized Bolivian sovereignty of natural resources, separated church and state, forbade foreign military bases in the country, implemented [[term limit|a two-term limit]] for the presidency, and permitted limited regional autonomy. It also enshrined every Bolivians' right to water, food, free health care, education, and housing.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=213, 219|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=182, 218\u2013219|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3pp=41\u201342}} In enshrining the concept of plurinationalism, one commentator noted that it suggested \"a profound reconfiguration of the state itself\" by recognising the rights to self-determination of various nations within a single state.{{sfn|Assies|2011|p=93}}\n\n[[File:Evo morales 2 year bolivia Joel Alvarez.jpg|left|thumb|Morales in 2008]]\nIn May 2008, the eastern departments pushed for greater autonomy, but Morales's government rejected the legitimacy of their position.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|pp=219\u2013220}} They called for a [[2008 Bolivian vote of confidence referendum|referendum on recalling Morales]], which saw an 83% turnout and in which Morales was ratified with 67.4% of the vote.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=220\u2013221|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=125|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=48}} Unified as the National Council for Democracy (CONALDE), these groups \u2013 financed by the wealthy agro-industrialist, petroleum, and financial elite \u2013 embarked on a series of destabilisation campaigns to unseat Morales's government.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=132\u2013133}}\n[[2008 unrest in Bolivia|Unrest then broke out across eastern Bolivia]], as radicalized autonomist activists established blockades, occupied airports, clashing with pro-government demonstrations, police, and armed forces. Some formed paramilitaries, bombing state companies, indigenous NGOs, and human rights organisations, also launching armed racist attacks on indigenous communities, culminating in the [[Porvenir Massacre|Pando Massacre]] of MAS activists.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1pp=221\u2013222|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2pp=182\u2013183|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3pp=133\u2013140|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4pp=47\u201349}} The autonomists gained support from some high-ranking politicians; Santa Cruz Governor [[Rub\u00e9n Costas]] lambasted Morales and his supporters with racist epithets, accusing the president of being an Aymara fundamentalist and a [[totalitarianism|totalitarian]] dictator responsible for [[state terrorism]].{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=221|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2pp=127\u2013128}} Amid the unrest, foreign commentators began speculating on the possibility of civil war.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=222|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=169|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=96}}\n\nAfter it was revealed that [[USAID]]'s [[Office of Transition Initiatives]] had supplied $4.5 million to the pro-autonomist departmental governments of the eastern provinces, in September 2008 Morales accused the U.S. ambassador to Bolivia, [[Philip Goldberg]], of \"conspiring against democracy\" and encouraging the civil unrest, ordering him to leave the country.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=222|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=132|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=49}}{{sfn|BBC News|2008a}}. The U.S. government responded by expelling Bolivian ambassador to the U.S., [[Gustavo Guzman]].{{sfn|BBC News|2008b}}. Bolivia subsequently expelled the U.S. [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] (DEA) from the country, while the U.S. responded by withdrawing their [[Peace Corps]].{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=72}} Ch\u00e1vez stood in solidarity with Bolivia by ordering the U.S. ambassador [[Patrick Duddy]] out of his country and withdrawing the Venezuelan ambassador to the U.S.{{sfnm|1a1=BBC News|1y=2008b|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=169|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=139|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4p=49}} The [[Union of South American Nations]] (UNASUR) convened a special meeting to discuss the Bolivian situation, expressing full support for Morales's government.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=222|2a1=Sivak|2y=2011|2p=169|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=141}}\n\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev 16 February 2009-1.jpg|thumb|right|Morales meeting with Russian President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] in 2009]]\nAlthough unable to quell the autonomist violence, Morales's government refused to declare a [[state of emergency]], believing that the autonomists were attempting to provoke them into doing so.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=134, 139}}\nInstead, they decided to compromise, entering into talks with the parliamentary opposition. As a result, 100 of the 411 elements of the Constitution were changed, with both sides compromising on certain issues.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=223|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=183|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=41}} Nevertheless, the governors of the eastern provinces rejected the changes, believing it gave them insufficient autonomy, while various Indianist and leftist members of MAS felt that the amendments conceded too much to the political right.{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=223}} The constitution was put to a [[2009 Bolivian constitutional referendum|referendum in January 2009]], in which it was approved by 61.4% of voters.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=223|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=183|3a1=Assies|3y=2011|3p=112|4a1=Webber|4y=2011|4p=153|5a1=Farthing|5a2=Kohl|5y=2014|5p=41}}\n\nFollowing the approval of the new Constitution, the [[2009 Bolivian general election|2009 general election]] was called. The opposition sought to delay the election by demanding a new [[biometric registry]] system, hoping that it would give them time to form a united front against MAS.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=184}} Many MAS activists reacted violently against the demands, and attempting to prevent this. Morales went on a five-day hunger strike in April 2009 to push the opposition to rescind their demands. He also agreed to allow for the introduction of a new voter registry, but insisted that it was rushed through so as not to delay the election.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=184\u2013185}} Morales and the MAS won with a landslide majority, polling 64.2%, while voter participation had reached an all-time high of 90%.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=226|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=185|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=153|4a1=Farthing|4a2=Kohl|4y=2014|4pp=50\u201351}} His primary opponent, Reyes Villa, gained 27% of the vote. The MAS won a two-thirds majority in both the [[National Congress of Bolivia|Chamber of Deputies]] and the [[National Congress of Bolivia|Senate]].{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=226|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=153|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3pp=50\u201351}} Morales notably increased his support in the east of the country, with MAS gaining a majority in Tarija.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=226|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=185|3a1=Webber|3y=2011|3p=153}}\nIn response to his victory, Morales proclaimed that he was \"obligated to accelerate the pace of change and deepen socialism\" in Bolivia, seeing his re-election as a mandate to further his reforms.{{sfnm|1a1=Friedman-Rudovsky|1y=2009|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=155}}\n\n===Second presidential term: 2009\u20132014===\nDuring his second term, Morales began to speak openly of \"communitarian socialism\" as the ideology that he desired for Bolivia's future.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=155}} He assembled a new cabinet which was 50% female, a first for Bolivia,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=228}} although by 2012, that had dropped to a third.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=66}} One of the main tasks that faced his government during this term was the aim of introducing legislation that would cement the extension of rights featured in the new constitution.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=25}} In April 2010, the departmental elections saw further gains for MAS.{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=154}} In 2013, the government passed a law to combat domestic violence against women.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=51}}\n\n[[File:Evo Morales in 2012.jpg|left|thumb|Morales at an international conference in 2012]]\n\nIn December 2009, Morales attended the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference]] in Copenhagen, Denmark, where he blamed climate change on capitalism and called for a [[financial transactions tax]] to fund climate change mitigation. Ultimately deeming the conference to have been a failure, he oversaw the World's People Conference on Climate Change and the Rights of Mother Earth outside of Cochabamba in April 2010.{{sfnm|1a1=Webber|1y=2011|1p=156|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2pp=75\u201376}}\n\nFollowing the victories of [[Barack Obama]] and the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 U.S. presidential election]], relations between Bolivia and the U.S. improved slightly, and in November 2009 the countries entered negotiations to restore diplomatic relations.{{sfnm|1a1=Friedman-Rudovsky|1y=2009|2a1=Farthing|2a2=Kohl|2y=2014|2p=73}} After the U.S. backed the [[2011 military intervention in Libya]] by [[NATO]] forces, Morales condemned Obama, calling for his [[Nobel Peace Prize]] to be revoked.{{sfn|Lovell|2011}} The two nations restored diplomatic relations in November 2011,{{sfn|BBC News|2011a}} although Morales refused to allow the DEA back into the country.{{sfn|BBC News|2011b}}\n\nIn October 2012, the government passed a Law of Mother Earth that banned [[genetically modified organisms]] (GMOs) being grown in Bolivia; although praised by environmentalists, it was criticised by the nation's [[soya bean|soya]] growers, who claimed that it would make them less competitive on the global market.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=93}}\n\nOn July 2, 2013, Bolivia's foreign minister said that [[Evo Morales grounding incident|the diversion of Morales's presidential plane]] (FAB-001, a [[Dassault Falcon 900]]EX), when Portuguese, French, Spanish and Italian authorities denied access to their airspace due to suspicions that [[Edward Snowden]] was on board the aircraft, had put the president's life at risk.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivia: Presidential plane forced to land after false rumors of Snowden onboard|date=July 3, 2013|author=Catherine E. Shoichet|website=CNN|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/07/02/world/americas/bolivia-presidential-plane|accessdate=January 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324023608/http://edition.cnn.com/2013/07/02/world/americas/bolivia-presidential-plane|archivedate=March 24, 2015}}</ref> Latin American leaders describe the incident as a \"stunning violation of national sovereignty and disrespect for the region\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Evo Morales, Bolivia President, Leaves Europe After Flight Delayed Over Snowden Suspicions|author1=Michael Weissenstein|author2=Angels Charlton|date=July 3, 2013|website=Huffington Post|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/03/bolivia-snowden_n_3539179.html|access-date=December 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210021721/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/03/bolivia-snowden_n_3539179.html|archive-date=February 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Morales himself described the incident as a \"hostage\" situation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivia's Morales says plane held 'hostage' because of Snowden rumors|date=July 3, 2013|agency=United Press International|url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2013/07/03/Bolivias-Morales-says-plane-held-hostage-because-of-Snowden-rumors/14561372850204|access-date=December 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101065353/http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2013/07/03/Bolivias-Morales-says-plane-held-hostage-because-of-Snowden-rumors/14561372850204/|archive-date=January 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> France apologized for the incident the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=France apologises to Bolivia over jet row|date=July 4, 2013|publisher=Al Jazeera|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2013/07/2013747914179924.html|access-date=July 4, 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6O7fPZHdM?url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2013/07/2013747914179924.html|archive-date=March 16, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The presidents of Argentina, Ecuador, Suriname, Uruguay and Venezuela, Morales's political allies in the region, gathered to demand an explanation of the incident.<ref>{{cite web|website=Bloomberg Business|date=July 5, 2013|author=Nathan Gill|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-05/bolivia-threatens-u-s-embassy-closure-after-search-for-snowden.html|title=Bolivia Threatens U.S. Embassy Closing After Snowden Search|access-date=March 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022153516/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-05/bolivia-threatens-u-s-embassy-closure-after-search-for-snowden.html|archive-date=October 22, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Morales became the oldest active professional soccer player in the world after signing a contract for $200 a month with [[Sport Boys Warnes]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivian President Evo Morales signed by football club|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-27463520|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=May 24, 2014|date=May 19, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524104439/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-27463520|archive-date=May 24, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2014, Morales condemned the [[2014 Israel\u2013Gaza conflict]] and declared Israel a \"terrorist state\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/07/30/bolivia-israel-terrorist-state/13384989|title=Bolivia declares Israel a 'terrorist state'|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=August 1, 2014|access-date=August 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012063209/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/07/30/bolivia-israel-terrorist-state/13384989/|archive-date=October 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Domestic protests====\n[[File:Bolivia evo-morales government Joel Alvarez.jpg|thumb|right|Morales addressing Bolivia's Parliament]]\nMorales's second term was heavily affected by infighting and dissent from within his support base, as indigenous and leftist activists rejected several government reforms.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=55}} In May 2010, his government announced a 5% rise in the minimum wage. The Bolivian Workers' Central (COB) felt this insufficient given the rising cost of living, calling a [[general strike]], while protesters clashed with police. The government refused to increase the rise, accusing protesters of being pawns of the right.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=216\u201325}} In August 2010, violent protests broke out in southern [[Potos\u00ed]] over widespread unemployment and a lack of infrastructure investment.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=51}} In December 2010, the government cut subsidies for gasoline and diesel fuels, which raised fuel prices and transport costs. Protests led Morales to nullify the decree, responding that he \"ruled by obeying\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=51\u201352}} In June 2012, [[Law enforcement in Bolivia|Bolivia's police]] launched protests against anti-corruption reforms to the police service; they burned disciplinary case records and demanded salary increases. Morales's government relented, cancelling many of the proposed reforms and agreeing to the wage rise.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=54\u201355}}\n\nIn 2011, the government announced it had signed a contract with a Brazilian company to construct a highway connecting Beni to Cochabamba, which would pass through the [[Isiboro S\u00e9cure National Park and Indigenous Territory]] (TIPNIS). This would better integrate the Beni and Pando departments with the rest of Bolivia and facilitate hydrocarbons exploration. The plan brought condemnation from environmentalists and indigenous communities living in the TIPNIS, who claimed that it would encourage deforestation and illegal settlement and that it violated the constitution and United Nations [[Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples]].{{sfnm|1a1=Farthing|1a2=Kohl|1y=2014|1pp=52\u201354|2a1=Crabtree|2a2=Chaplin|2y=2013|2p=17}} The issue became an international cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre and cast doubt on the government's environmentalist and indigenous rights credentials.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=18}} In August, 800 protesters embarked on [[2011 Bolivian indigenous protests|a protest march]] from [[Trinidad, Bolivia|Trinidad]] to La Paz; many were injured in clashes with police and supporters of the road.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=52\u201354}} Two government ministers and other high-ranking officials resigned in protest and Morales's government relented, announcing suspension of the road.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=52\u201354}} In October 2011, he passed Law 180, prohibiting further road construction, although the government proceeded with a consultation, eventually gaining the consent of 55 of the 65 communities in TIPNIS to allow the highway to be built, albeit with a variety of concessions; construction was scheduled to take place after the 2014 general election.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|pp=52\u201354}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Indigenous Bolivians march against Amazon road|date=August 15, 2011|publisher=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-14536163|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190813013212/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-14536163|archive-date=August 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivia's Long March Against Evo Morales: An Indigenous Protest|url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2097142,00.html|work=Time|date=October 17, 2011|access-date=December 13, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213032428/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2097142,00.html|archive-date=December 13, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In May 2013, the government announced that it would permit hydrocarbon exploration in Bolivia's 22 national parks, to widespread condemnation from environmentalists.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=93}}\n\n===Third presidential term: 2014\u20132019===\n[[File:Third GECF summit in Tehran 11.jpg|thumb|Morales with Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] during the [[Third GECF summit]].]]\nIn 2008, Morales had vowed that he would not stand for re-election in the 2014 general election.{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=119}}\nHowever, he successfully did so and after proclaiming victory in the election, Morales declared it \"a triumph of the anti-colonialists and anti-imperialists\" and dedicated his win to both Castro and Ch\u00e1vez.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolivia elects Evo Morales as president for third term|newspaper=The Guardian|date=October 13, 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|access-date=December 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218142814/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|archive-date=December 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Evo Morales Dedicates Electoral Victory to Fidel Castro and Hugo Chavez|publisher=CubaNews|date=October 13, 2014|url=http://www.cubanews.ain.cu/world/1657-evo-morales-dedicates-electoral-victory-to-fidel-castro-and-hugo-chavez|access-date=October 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141026041916/http://www.cubanews.ain.cu/world/1657-evo-morales-dedicates-electoral-victory-to-fidel-castro-and-hugo-chavez|archive-date=October 26, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Morales wins third term in Bolivian presidential election|date=October 13, 2014|publisher=Deutsche Welle|url=http://www.dw.de/morales-wins-third-term-in-bolivian-presidential-election/a-17989872|access-date=October 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013120101/http://www.dw.de/morales-wins-third-term-in-bolivian-presidential-election/a-17989872|archive-date=October 13, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the basis of this victory, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' remarked that Morales was \"one of the world's most popular leaders\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Andres Schipani|title=Bolivia's Evo Morales secures redistributionist mandate|newspaper=Financial Times|date=October 13, 2014|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/077a25b4-528f-11e4-b55e-00144feab7de.html|access-date=October 13, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021053122/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/077a25b4-528f-11e4-b55e-00144feab7de.html|archive-date=October 21, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On October 17, 2015, Morales surpassed [[Andr\u00e9s de Santa Cruz]]'s nine years, eight months, and twenty-four days in office and became Bolivia's longest serving president.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.paginasiete.bo/ideas/2015/10/11/andres-santa-cruz-morales-72985.html|title=Andr\u00e9s de Santa Cruz y Evo Morales|last=Quiroga T.|first=Jos\u00e9 Antonio|date=October 11, 2015|work=P\u00e1gina Siete|accessdate=June 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822150438/http://www.paginasiete.bo/ideas/2015/10/11/andres-santa-cruz-morales-72985.html|archive-date=August 22, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bolivia elects Evo Morales as president for third term|website=The Guardian|date=October 13, 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|access-date=December 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218142814/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/13/bolivia-evo-morales--president-third-term|archive-date=December 18, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Writing in ''The Guardian'', [[Ellie Mae O'Hagan]] attributes his enduring popularity not to anti-imperialist rhetoric but his \"extraordinary socio-economic reforms,\" which resulted in poverty and extreme poverty declining by 25% and 43% respectively.<ref>[[Ellie Mae O'Hagan]] (October 14, 2014). [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/oct/14/evo-morales-reelected-socialism-doesnt-damage-economies-bolivia Evo Morales has proved that socialism doesn't damage economies] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161218142813/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/oct/14/evo-morales-reelected-socialism-doesnt-damage-economies-bolivia |date=December 18, 2016 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''; retrieved October 18, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn early February 2016 there were rumors that Morales had had a child with a young woman, Gabriela Zapata Monta\u00f1o, and had granted favors to the Chinese company that she worked for.<ref name=\"Guardian-Monta\u00f1o\">{{cite news |last1=Collyns |first1=Dan |publisher=The Guardian |title=Sex, lies and paternity claims: Bolivia's president reels amid tumultuous scandal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jun/24/bolivia-evo-morales-press-freedom-gabriela-zapata-child |date=June 24, 2016}}</ref> Morales admitted that they had had a son (who he says died in infancy), but denied granting any favors and said he had not been in contact with Zapata Monta\u00f1o since 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gabriela Zapata Monta\u00f1o, la exnovia que puso en aprietos al presidente de Bolivia Evo Morales|url=http://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias/2016/02/160205_exnovia_evo_morales_bolivia_vs|agency=BBC|date=February 6, 2016|access-date=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209020810/http://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias/2016/02/160205_exnovia_evo_morales_bolivia_vs|archive-date=February 9, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The commission that investigated the issue concluded that Morales was not at fault. Zapata Monta\u00f1o was later sentenced to ten years in prison for illegal financial behavior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/Comision-legislativa-influencias-contratos-CAMC_0_2484951532.html|title=Comisi\u00f3n legislativa concluye que no hubo tr\u00e1fico de influencias en contratos del Estado con CAMC - La Raz\u00f3n|access-date=December 22, 2017|website=www.la-razon.com|language=es}}</ref>\n\nMorales attended the swearing-in ceremony of Venezuela's president [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] for his second term on January 10, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Venezuelan President Maduro sworn in for second term amid international boycott |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/10/venezuelan-president-maduro-sworn-second-term-amid-international/ |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=April 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402153411/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/01/10/venezuelan-president-maduro-sworn-second-term-amid-international/ |archive-date=April 2, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2019, Morales condemned the arrest by the [[United Kingdom]] of WikiLeaks founder [[Julian Assange]].<ref name=\"assangereactions\">{{cite news |title=Julian Assange's arrest draws fierce international reaction |url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/wikileaks-julian-assange-arrest-international-reaction |publisher=Fox News |date=April 11, 2019 |access-date=April 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413222042/https://www.foxnews.com/world/wikileaks-julian-assange-arrest-international-reaction |archive-date=April 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Term limit====\n{{See also|2016 Bolivian constitutional referendum}}\nThe [[Constitution of Bolivia|2009 Bolivian constitution]] prohibits more than two consecutive presidential terms.<ref name=\"2009-constitution\">{{Cite web |title=Bolivia (Plurinational State of)'s Constitution of 2009 |url=https://www.constituteproject.org/constitution/Bolivia_2009.pdf |publisher=Constitute Project}}</ref> Morales had been allowed to serve three consecutive terms as President due to a 2013 ruling by the [[Plurinational Constitutional Court]] that Morales' first term did not count towards the term limit because it had taken place prior to the ratification of the 2009 constitution.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia: New law backs President Evo Morales third term |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-22605030 |publisher=BBC |date=May 21, 2013}}</ref> Despite Morales' claim in 2014 that he would not attempt to alter the constitution so that he could serve a fourth term,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Evo Morales rules out fourth term |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-29613434 |publisher=BBC |date=October 14, 2014}}</ref> in February 2016 a [[2016 Bolivian constitutional referendum|referendum]] was held on a constitutional amendment to allow presidents to serve three consecutive terms, which would have allowed Morales to run for a fourth term (third under the new constitution).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dube |first1=Ryan |title=Bolivia\u2019s Evo Morales Faces Tough Vote on Referendum |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bolivias-evo-morales-faces-tough-vote-on-referendum-1455902404 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=February 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Valdez |first1=Carlos |title=AP Explains: Why is Evo Morales facing protests in Bolivia? |url=https://apnews.com/4fcd6a5f055b44299178d6573734eea0 |publisher=Associated Press |date=November 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia passes law to allow Morales to run for fourth term |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-presidency/bolivia-passes-law-to-allow-morales-to-run-for-fourth-term-idUSKCN0RQ0SL20150926 |publisher=Reuters |date=September 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Bolivia-Sets-Date-For-Referendum-On-Evo-Morales-Re-election-20151015-0021.html Bolivia Sets Date For Referendum On Evo Morales Re-election] Telesurv, October 15, 2015</ref> The amendment narrowly lost.<ref name=\"BBC-2016referendum\">{{Cite news| url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093| title=Bolivian leader 'loses' fourth term bid| work=BBC News| date=February 22, 2016| access-date=June 21, 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510094756/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093| archive-date=May 10, 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMorales blamed the referendum loss on [[American imperialism]] and a \"dirty war\" by the right-wing opposition.<ref name=\"Blair\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/03/evo-morales-bolivia-president-election-limits|title=Evo for ever? Bolivia scraps term limits as critics blast 'coup' to keep Morales in power|last1=Blair|first1=Laurence|date=December 3, 2017|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 1, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180101135426/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/03/evo-morales-bolivia-president-election-limits|archive-date=January 1, 2018|quote=This week, the country\u2019s highest court overruled the constitution, scrapping term limits altogether for every office. Morales can now run for a fourth term in 2019 \u2013 and for every election thereafter. ... the referendum results \u2013 which the government claims were invalid due to an opposition smear campaign directed by Washington ...}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Collyns |first1=Dan |last2=Watts |first2=Jonathan |title=Bolivia: tensions rise as Evo Morales's bid to extend presidency hangs in balance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/feb/22/bolivia-tensions-rise-as-evo-moraless-bid-to-extend-presidency-hangs-in-balance |publisher=The Guardian |date=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Daniel |last2=Machicao |first2=Monica |title=Bolivia's Morales accepts defeat in term limit referendum |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-referendum/bolivias-morales-accepts-defeat-in-term-limit-referendum-idUSKCN0VX09E |publisher=Reuters |date=February 23, 2016}}</ref> Morales' had maintained high approval ratings throughout his presidency, which saw extreme poverty reduced, but shortly before the referendum his popularity was damaged by allegations that his former girlfriend, Gabriela Zapata Monta\u00f1o, had helped secure US$500 million in government contracts for the Chinese engineering firm that employed her, as well as by claims that the government intimidated journalists who investigated the scandal.<ref name=\"Guardian-Monta\u00f1o\"/><ref name=\"BBC-2016referendum\"/> Further adding to the scandal, Zapata alleged that the child Morales had with her that he claimed had died in infancy was, in fact, alive.<ref name=\"Monta\u00f1o scandal NYT\">{{cite news |title=The Worst Boyfriend in Bolivia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/26/opinion/the-worst-boyfriend-in-bolivia.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=May 25, 2016}}</ref> She later changed her story, and said that the baby had died in 2009.<ref name =\"trt230517\" /> In June 2016 Bolivia's attorney general, Ramiro Guerrero, told reporters that Zapata had paid $5,000 to the parents of an unrelated child in return for the child pretending to be Morales' son. Five people were arrested in relation to the charade<ref name=\"Guardian-Monta\u00f1o\"/><ref name =\"trt230517\" /> and in May 2017 Bolivian courts concluded that the child was not alive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/05/17/the-saga-of-fidel-the-president-of-bolivias-illusory-secret-son/|title=The Saga of Fidel, the Bolivian President\u2019s Illusory Secret Son|last1=Soloway|first1=Benjamin|date=May 17, 2016|publisher=Foreign Policy}}</ref> Morales denied the allegations relating to the government contracts and ordered an inquiry into how the contracts were awarded.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bolivian President Evo Morales 'loses' fourth term bid|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093|agency=BBC|date=February 22, 2016|access-date=June 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510094756/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-35628093|archive-date=May 10, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The inquiry concluded that Morales was not at fault, while Zapata was arrested and ultimately sentenced to ten years in prison for influence peddling and laundering \"illicit earnings\".<ref name=\"Monta\u00f1o scandal NYT\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnespanol.cnn.com/2017/05/23/condenan-a-10-anos-de-carcel-a-gabriela-zapata-expareja-de-evo-morales/|title=Condenan a 10 a\u00f1os de c\u00e1rcel a Gabriela Zapata, expareja de Evo Morales|last1=Carrasco|first1=Gloria|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\"trt230517\">{{cite news|url=https://www.trtworld.com/americas/bolivian-president-s-ex-girlfriend-gets-10-year-jail-term-7235|title=Bolivian president's ex-girlfriend gets 10 year jail term|date=May 23, 2017|publisher=TRT World}}</ref> However, there was controversy over the fact that Zapata's defense lawyer and an aunt who had corroborated her claim that Morales' son was alive were both jailed.<ref name=\"Monta\u00f1o scandal NYT\" /> \n\nDespite the referendum loss and Morales' earlier claim that he would not seek a fourth term if he lost the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales loses referendum for fourth term |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/02/bolivia-morales-loses-referendum-term-160224035410165.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> in December 2016 MAS nominated Morales as their candidate for the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 presidential election]], stating that they would seek various avenues to ensure the legality of Morales' candidacy.<ref>{{cite article |title=Bolivia's President Evo Morales to Run Again Despite Referendum Ruling it Out |date=December 18, 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |access-date=December 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219073457/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2017, MAS asked the Plurinational Constitutional Court to rescind legal limits barring elected authorities from seeking re-election indefinitely.<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/> In its ruling one month later, the Court struck down term limits for all elected public offices, including the Presidency, stating that term limits are [[human rights]] violations under the [[American Convention on Human Rights]], a multilateral treaty signed by many countries in the Americas,<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\">{{cite news |title=Bolivian court clears way for Morales to run for fourth term |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivian-court-clears-way-for-morales-to-run-for-fourth-term-idUSKBN1DS2ZX |publisher=Reuters |date=November 28, 2017}}</ref> enabling Morales to run for a fourth term.<ref name=\"Blair\" /> In response to the decision, the Secretary General of the [[Organization of American States]], [[Luis Almagro]], stated that the clause in the [[American Convention on Human Rights]] cited by the Court \u201cdoes not mean the right to perpetual power\u201d;<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/> however, in 2019 he publicly supported Morales' participation in the 2019 election, arguing that \"presidents [in other countries]...have taken part in electoral processes on the grounds of a court ruling\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election/bolivias-morales-defies-term-limits-launches-bid-for-fourth-term-idUSKCN1SO0R3|title=Bolivia's Morales defies term limits, launches bid for fourth term|last1=Ramos|first1=Daniel|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021034143/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election/bolivias-morales-defies-term-limits-launches-bid-for-fourth-term-idUSKCN1SO0R3|archive-date=October 21, 2019|publisher=Reuters|agency=Reuters}}</ref> Opposition leader [[Samuel Doria Medina]] called the decision \"a blow to the constitution\".<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/>\n\n==== New presidential residence ====\n[[File:Plaza Murillo .jpg|thumb|The new [[Casa Grande del Pueblo]] presidential residence built by Morales in 2018]]\nControversy arose when a new $34 million presidential skyscraper residence, the [[Casa Grande del Pueblo]], was constructed in the historical [[Plaza Murillo]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/aug/16/bolivian-president-evo-morales-new-residence-is-as-imposing-as-it-is-divisive-la-paz|title=Bolivian president\u2019s new residence is as imposing as it is divisive|last=Collyns|first=Dan|date=August 16, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=December 7, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20180620-impoverished-bolivia-presidents-new-palace-eyesore|title=In impoverished Bolivia, president's new palace an eyesore for some|last=|first=|date=June 20, 2018|website=[[France 24]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> The proposal was initially declined due to municipal height restrictions in the historical district, though Morales' parliamentary majority in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] overrode the ban, permitting the tower's construction.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The Casa Grande del Pueblo was inaugurated by Morales on August 9, 2018.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-45229290|title=C\u00f3mo es la imponente y pol\u00e9mica \"Casa Grande del Pueblo\", la nueva sede del gobierno de Bolivia construida por Evo Morales|last=|first=|date=August 18, 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=December 7, 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe 29-story tower standing at {{Convert|120|m|ft|abbr=}} was the tallest building in the capital city of La Paz when completed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expreso.com.pe/mundo/bolivia-conozca-el-suite-presidencial-que-ocupo-evo-morales-en-la-casa-grande-del-pueblo/|title=Bolivia: conozca la suite presidencial que ocup\u00f3 Evo Morales en la Casa Grande del Pueblo|date=November 15, 2019|website=Expreso|language=es|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/america-latina/2019/11/15/las-fotos-de-la-suite-de-evo-morales-en-la-casa-del-pueblo-parece-una-habitacion-de-un-jeque-arabe/|title=Las fotos de la suite de Evo Morales en La Casa del Pueblo: \u201cParece una habitaci\u00f3n de un jeque \u00e1rabe\"|last=|first=|date=November 15, 2019|website=[[Infobae]]|language=es-ES|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> It was designed by Bolivian architects and decorated with indigenous motifs representing traditional Bolivian culture.<ref name=\":1\"/> The skyscraper was built to replace the former presidential palace, which Morales planned to turn into a museum.<ref name=\"bbc021114\">{{cite web |last1=BBC News |title=Bolivian palace: President Evo Morales signs contract |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-29868704 |website=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=November 20, 2019}}</ref> The building features a helipad and the top two floors were reserved for the president, featuring a gym, spa, Jacuzzi and private elevator.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> The presidential suite in total was {{Convert|1,068|m2|ft2|abbr=}}, with the bathroom and dressing room measuring at {{Convert|47|m2|ft2|abbr=}} while the bedroom was {{Convert|61|m2|ft2|abbr=}}.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/gente/2018/5/20/la-suite-de-evo-tiene-1068-m2-incluye-sauna-jacuzzi-sala-de-masajes-180564.html|title=La suite de Evo tiene 1.068 m2 e incluye sauna, jacuzzi y sala de masajes|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2018|website=Diario Pagina Siete|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> According to ''Diario Pagina Siete'', Morales' bedroom was the same size as the average home provided by his government housing project.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nMany analysts and critics of Morales denounced the spending due to the large levels of poverty in Bolivia.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[NPR]] described the new residence as \"a luxurious new skyscraper\" and that critics contend that \"Morales is acting more like an emperor than a president\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/14/767967304/how-bolivias-evo-morales-could-win-a-4th-term-as-president|title=How Bolivia's Evo Morales Could Win A 4th Term As President|last=|first=|date=October 14, 2019|website=[[NPR]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref> while [[Reuters]] wrote that Morales \"alienated those who once backed him, especially by building the ostentatious presidential palace\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-bolivia-election-palace-idUKKBN1XO2Y4|title=Andean textiles and bank bills: Inside Morales' home at Bolivia's Big House of the People|last=|first=|date=November 14, 2019|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=December 7, 2019|language=en}}</ref> Bolivian [[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] [[Toribio Ticona Porco]] dubbed the tower \"Evo Palace\" and criticized the opulence invested into it.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAfter signing the contract for the new building, Morales stated that it was \"not a luxury\" since it would also house cabinet meeting rooms, a centre for indigenous ceremonies and a 1,000-seat auditorium as well as rooms for exclusive presidential use.<ref name = \"bbc021114\"/> He also stated that the project would reduce government spending by $20 million per year as five other ministries would move into the building.<ref name=\":1\" /> He said the Casa Grande del Pueblo was a break with the past and described the previous residence, the [[Palacio Quemado]] or \"Burnt Palace\", as a vestige of colonialism and a symbol of neoliberal governments that stripped the State of its wealth, its heritage and its memory.<ref name=\":3\" />  Morales' communication minister [[G\u00edsela L\u00f3pez]] responded to criticism, stating that the tower was \"a necessity for the people\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== 2019 election controversy and resignation ===\n{{Main article|2019 Bolivian political crisis}}\n====Background====\nArticle 168 of the [[Constitution of Bolivia|2009 Bolivian constitution]] allows the President and Vice President to put themselves forward for re-election only once, limiting the number of terms to two.<ref name=\"2009-constitution\"/> As Evo Morales was approaching the end of his second consecutive term since the ratification of the 2009 constitution (his third consecutive term since first being elected\u2014in 2013 Bolivia's highest court ruled that Morales' first term did not count towards the term limit because it had taken place prior to the ratification of the 2009 constitution<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia: New law backs President Evo Morales third term |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-22605030 |publisher=BBC |date=May 21, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LaRazon6Nov15\">[http://la-razon.com/nacional/Referendum_constitucional-consulta-habilitar-Evo-marcha-MAS-juega_0_2376362395.html Consulta para habilitar a Evo est\u00e1 en marcha;  El MAS \u2018se juega la vida\u2019] La Raz\u00f3n, 6 November 2015</ref>), the governing party, the [[Movement for Socialism (Bolivia)|Movement for Socialism]] (MAS), sponsored an effort to amend this article. The referendum was authorized by a combined session of the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] on 26 September 2015, by a vote of 112 to 41.<ref name=\"ALP26Sep15\">[http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/La-ALP-sanciono-la-Ley-de-Reforma-parcial-de-la-CPE La ALP sancion\u00f3 la Ley de Reforma parcial de la CPE] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226052237/http://www.vicepresidencia.gob.bo/La-ALP-sanciono-la-Ley-de-Reforma-parcial-de-la-CPE |date=2015-12-26 }} Vice President of Bolivia</ref><ref name=\"R\">[https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/09/26/us-bolivia-presidency-idUSKCN0RQ0SL20150926 Bolivia passes law to allow Morales to run for fourth term] Reuters, 25 September 2015</ref> A successful 'yes' vote would have allowed President Evo Morales and Vice President [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] to run for a fourth term in office in 2019.\n\nThe referendum was held on Sunday, 21 February 2016. The proposed constitutional amendment was voted down by a 51% majority.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Nicholas |title=Bolivian President Concedes Defeat in Term-Limit Referendum |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/25/world/americas/bolivian-president-evo-morales-concedes-defeat-in-term-limit-referendum.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=24 February 2016}}</ref> \n\nDespite the referendum loss and Morales' earlier claim that he would not seek a fourth term if he lost the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales loses referendum for fourth term |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/02/bolivia-morales-loses-referendum-term-160224035410165.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=February 24, 2016}}</ref> in December 2016 MAS nominated Morales as their candidate for the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 presidential election]], stating that they would seek various avenues to ensure the legality of Morales' candidacy.<ref>{{cite article |title=Bolivia's President Evo Morales to Run Again Despite Referendum Ruling it Out |date=December 18, 2016 |website=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |access-date=December 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161219073457/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/dec/18/bolivias-president-evo-morales-to-run-again-despite-referendum-ruling-it-out |archive-date=December 19, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2017, MAS applied to the Plurinational Constitutional Court, which critics claim had been stacked with Morales allies after its creation under Morales by the [[Constitution of Bolivia|2009 constitution]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armario |first1=Christine |title=AP Explains: Did a coup force Bolivia\u2019s Evo Morales out? |url=https://apnews.com/6b2c94306089451d9761878c9f7ce2f1 |publisher=Associated Press |date=11 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=France-Presse |first1=Agence |title=Bolivia's Evo Morales faces second round run-off in bid for controversial fourth term |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/10/21/bolivias-evo-morales-faces-second-round-run-off-bid-controversial/ |publisher=The Telegraph |date=21 October 2019}}</ref> to abolish term limits. In November, the court ruled in favor of their abolition, stating that [[term limit]]s are [[human right]]s violations under the [[American Convention on Human Rights]].<ref name=\"Reuters-Fourth_Term\"/> The ruling enabled Morales to run for re-election in the [[2019 Bolivian general election|2019 elections]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Blair |first1=Laurence |title=Evo for ever? Bolivia scraps term limits as critics blast 'coup' to keep Morales in power |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/dec/03/evo-morales-bolivia-president-election-limits |publisher=The Guardian |date=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2019 election====\n{{See also|2019 Bolivian general election}}\n\n<!-- Summary of election results -->\nFollowing the court ruling eliminating term limits, on October 20, 2019 Morales won 47.1% of the vote in the first round of the [[2019 Bolivian general election]]. His closest rival was Carlos Mesa, with 35.5% of the vote. As the gap between Morales and Mesa was over 10%, Bolivian election law dictated that a second-round run-off between them would not be required.<ref name=\"aj291019\">{{cite news |title=Bolivia, OAS close to deal on election audit as protests continue |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/bolivia-oas-close-deal-election-audit-protests-continue-191028143828285.html |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=October 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116145048/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/10/bolivia-oas-close-deal-election-audit-protests-continue-191028143828285.html |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n<!-- Disputation of elecation and immediate aftermath -->\nThe results were immediately disputed as there was an unexplained break in transmission of the results, leading to widespread [[2019 Bolivian protests|protests across the country]]. Responding to the concerns and violent protests, Morales asked the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS) to conduct an audit of the vote count.<ref name=\"reuters231019\">{{cite news |title=Bolivian government seeks election audit, vows to respect result |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-foreign-minister/bolivian-government-seeks-election-audit-vows-to-respect-result-idUSKBN1X12FJ |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=October 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116145050/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-foreign-minister/bolivian-government-seeks-election-audit-vows-to-respect-result-idUSKBN1X12FJ |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morales said he would call for a second-round runoff vote with Mesa if the OAS' audit found evidence of fraud.<ref name=\"aj291019\"/> Morales asked the protesters to observe a truce while the OAS conducted the audit, while Mesa asked his supporters to maintain their strikes and street protests all over the country.<ref name=\"msm311019\">{{cite news |title=Morales calls for Bolivia violence 'truce' as OAS begins election audit |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/oas-begins-audit-of-disputed-bolivia-election-results/ar-AAJEH73 |accessdate=November 16, 2019 |agency=AFP |publisher=msm |date=October 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191116145050/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/oas-begins-audit-of-disputed-bolivia-election-results/ar-AAJEH73 |archive-date=November 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 8, 2019, police in a number of cities, including La Paz, Santa Cruz, Sucre and Cochabamba, joined in demonstrations against the government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/09/bolivian-police-in-la-paz-join-mutiny-against-evo-morales|title=Bolivian police in La Paz join 'mutiny' against Evo Morales|last=Collyns|first=Dan|date=November 9, 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110003802/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/09/bolivian-police-in-la-paz-join-mutiny-against-evo-morales|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/animal_electoral/bolivia-motin-policial-policias-rebelion-evo_0_3254074610.html|title=El mot\u00edn policial se extiende a cuatro capitales - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> \n\n<!-- Independent reports released prior to OAS preliminary report -->\nPrior to the release of the OAS audit preliminary report, a number of independent audits were conducted. On 5 November 2019, Professor [[Walter Mebane|Walter R. Mebane]] at the University of Michigan used his own \"eforensics\" model to detect and predict the level of fraud that occurred during the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pressenza.com/2019/11/studies-refute-oas-claims-of-irregularities-in-bolivian-elections/|title=Studies refute OAS claims of irregularities in Bolivian elections|last1=Swinden|first1=Silvia|date=15 November 2019|accessdate=16 November 2019|publisher=Pressenza - International Press Agency}}</ref><ref name=Mebane>{{Cite web|url=http://www-personal.umich.edu/~wmebane/Bolivia2019.pdf|title=Evidence Against Fraudulent Votes Being Decisive in the Bolivia 2019 Election\u2217|last=Mebane|first=Walter R.|date=13 November 2019|website=University of Michigan personal homepage server|url-status=live|access-date=2 January 2020|page=1}}</ref> He estimated that there were around 22500 fraudulent votes and initially determined that, although fraud existed, it would not have been enough to change the results of the elections. On 13 November, however, Mebane said that feedback from colleagues led him to believe that \"best formula\" for the model led to a new reallocation which indicated that Morales would have had a lead of 9.9% over Mesa, requiring a runoff election.<ref name=Mebane/> On 8 November 2019, Ethical Hacking, the tech security company hired by the TSE (under Morales) to audit the elections, stated that there were multiple irregularities and violations of procedure and that \"our function as an auditor security company is to declare everything that was found, and much of what was found supports the conclusion that the electoral process be declared null and void\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2019/11/8/ethical-hacking-las-elecciones-en-bolivia-estan-viciadas-de-nulidad-236759.html|title=Ethical Hacking: The elections in Bolivia are null and void|language=es}}</ref> In their official report, one source for the OAS, they stated \u2033We ''cannot'' attest to the integrity of the electoral results because the entire process is null and void due to the number of alterations to the TREP source code, the number of accesses and manual modifications with the maximum privileges to the databases being created during the electoral process and the inconsistencies of the software that arose in the TREP and Computo.\u2033 <ref>cite web | url=https://www.scribd.com/document/434031751/EHC-REP-Consolidado-Resumen|title=Ethical Hacking consolidated report|language=es</ref>\n\n<!-- OAS preliminary report and immediate political effects -->\nOn November 10, 2019, OAS published its preliminary report concluding that there were \"clear manipulations\" in the election.<ref>{{cite web |title=An\u00e1lisis de Integridad Electoral Elecciones Generales en el Estado Plurinacional de Bolivia 20 de octubre de 2019 |url=http://www.oas.org/documents/spa/press/Informe-Auditoria-Bolivia-2019.pdf |publisher=Organization of American States |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales to call fresh election after OAS audit |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50365340 |publisher=BBC |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Keith |title=Why Is Evo Morales Suddenly No Longer President of Bolivia? |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2019/11/11/evo-morales-resigns-president-bolivia/ |publisher=Foreign Policy |date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Krygier |first1=Rachelle |last2=Faiola |first2=Anthony |title=Bolivia\u2019s Morales resigns amid scathing election report, rising protests |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/bolivia-to-hold-new-elections-after-protests-and-international-criticism/2019/11/10/4778e842-03b2-11ea-ac12-3325d49eacaa_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=November 10, 2019}}</ref>  Within an hour of the release of the preliminary report, Morales announced that fresh elections would be held,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/animal_electoral/bolivia-elecciones-nuevas-convocatoria-evo-comicios_0_3255274455.html|title=Evo anuncia nuevas elecciones con nuevas autoridades electorales y nuevos actores pol\u00edticos - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> but this offer was rejected by the opposition party and civic leaders who demanded his resignation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia's Morales to call fresh election after OAS audit |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50365340 |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |date=November 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110130244/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50365340 |archive-date=November 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"reuters101119\">{{cite web |title=Bolivia's Morales agrees to new elections after damning OAS audit |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-oas/oas-finds-irregularities-in-disputed-bolivia-vote-calls-for-new-elections-idUSKBN1XK07T |website=Reuters |accessdate=November 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110152642/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-oas/oas-finds-irregularities-in-disputed-bolivia-vote-calls-for-new-elections-idUSKBN1XK07T |archive-date=November 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Executive Secretary of the Bolivian Workers' Center Juan Carlos Huarachi, the chief of police Commander Yuri Calder\u00f3n, and prominent right-wing activist [[Luis Fernando Camacho]] called for Morales' resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/evo-morales-cob-renuncia-reflexionar-pacificar-pais-bolivia_0_3255274472.html|title=COB : 'Si es por el bien del pa\u00eds, que renuncie nuestro Presidente' - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/animal_electoral/FFAA-sugieren-presidente-Morales-renunciar-bolivia_0_3255274480.html|title=Las FFAA y la Polic\u00eda le sugieren al presidente Morales renunciar - La Raz\u00f3n|website=www.la-razon.com|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> Afterwards, General [[Williams Kaliman]], a loyal supporter of Morales and commander-in-chief of Bolivia's army,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/seguridad/2019/12/1/fiel-evo-hasta-el-final-kaliman-saco-las-tropas-amenazado-por-su-estado-mayor-239081.html|title=Fiel a Evo hasta el final, Kaliman sac\u00f3 a las tropas amenazado por su Estado Mayor - Diario Pagina Siete|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> and other military chiefs suggested Morales step down to restore \"peace and stability and for the good of our Bolivia\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50369591|title=Bolivian army chief urges Morales to step down|date=November 10, 2019|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111084941/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50369591|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html|title=Bolivian Leader Evo Morales Steps Down|last=Londo\u00f1o|first=Ernesto|date=November 10, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110211008/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/americas/evo-morales-bolivia.html|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Morales announced his resignation. Other key figures in Morales' government also resigned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/seguridad/2019/12/4/kaliman-evo-como-puede-ser-golpe-de-estado-no-me-quede-de-presidente-239427.html|title=Kaliman a Evo: C\u00f3mo puede ser golpe de Estado, no me qued\u00e9 de Presidente - Diario Pagina Siete|last=|first=|date=|website=www.paginasiete.bo|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> On 12 November, Morales flew to Mexico where he was granted [[Right of asylum|political asylum]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia crisis: Evo Morales accepts political asylum in Mexico |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50383608 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=November 12, 2019 |work=BBC News |date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112091524/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50383608 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morales, along with the governments of [[Mexico]], [[Cuba]], [[Uruguay]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Venezuela]], and [[Argentina]], maintain that his removal was a [[Coup d'\u00e9tat|coup]].<ref name=\"BC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50370013|title=Bolivian President Evo Morales resigns|publisher=BBC News|date=November 11, 2019|access-date=November 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191110213149/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50370013|archive-date=November 10, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian101119\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/10/bolivian-president-evo-morales-resigns-after-election-result-dispute|title=Bolivian president Evo Morales resigns after election result dispute|date=November 10, 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|access-date=November 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111055233/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/nov/10/bolivian-president-evo-morales-resigns-after-election-result-dispute|archive-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"reutersmexico\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nicaragua-bolivia-idUSKBN1XL06O|title=Nicaraguan government denounces \"coup\" in Bolivia: statement|date=November 11, 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191111222822/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nicaragua-bolivia-idUSKBN1XL06O|archive-date=November 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mexico says Bolivia suffered coup due to military pressure on Morales |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=November 11, 2019 |access-date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112013317/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/12/world/americas/bolivia-evo-morales-coup.html|title=Bolivia Crisis Shows the Blurry Line Between Coup and Uprising|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=November 12, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mexico says Bolivia suffered coup due to military pressure on Morales |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |agency=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |date=November 11, 2019 |access-date=November 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191112013317/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-mexico-minister/mexico-says-bolivia-suffered-coup-due-to-military-pressure-on-morales-idUSKBN1XL1S5 |archive-date=November 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Bolivian opposition leaders and the governments of [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], the [[United Kingdom]], the [[United States]], and [[Canada]] recognized opposition senator [[Jeanine \u00c1\u00f1ez]] as the de facto interim president.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dyer |first1=Evan |title=Canada will 'support' Bolivian opposition government |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/bolivia-canada-anez-government-1.5360138 |publisher=CBC |date=November 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=de Haldevang |first1=Max |title=The world\u2019s as divided about Bolivia\u2019s alleged coup as Bolivians themselves |url=https://qz.com/1748281/experts-are-divided-on-evo-morales-and-bolivias-alleged-coup/ |publisher=Quartz |date=November 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/12/world/americas/bolivia-evo-morales-coup.html|title=Bolivia Crisis Shows the Blurry Line Between Coup and Uprising|last=Fisher|first=Max|date=November 12, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Final OAS report and corroborating reports -->\nOn 5 December 2019, the OAS released its final 96-page report on the integrity of the election. It found \"overwhelming evidence\" of vote-rigging in favor of Morales, including physical records with alterations, forged signatures, a \u201cparallel technological scheme\u201d of hidden servers, and evidence of wide-scale data manipulation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Final Report of the Audit of the Elections in Bolivia: Intentional Manipulation and Serious Irregularities Made it Impossible to Validate the Results |url=https://www.oas.org/en/media_center/press_release.asp?sCodigo=E-109/19 |publisher=Organization of American States |date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia election rigging in favor of Morales was 'overwhelming': OAS final report |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-oas/bolivia-election-rigging-in-favor-of-morales-was-overwhelming-oas-final-report-idUSKBN1Y9063 |publisher=Reuters |date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kurmanaev |first1=Anatoly |title=Election Fraud Aided Evo Morales, International Panel Concludes |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/world/americas/evo-morales-election.html |publisher=The New York Times |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Evo Morales: Overwhelming evidence of election fraud in Bolivia, monitors say |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-50685335 |publisher=BBC |date=December 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bolivia: 'overwhelming evidence' of vote-rigging in favor of Morales, OAS says |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/05/bolivia-election-evo-morales-vote-rigging-report-oas |publisher=The Guardian |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> The report was corroborated by a number of other independent analyses. For instance, the Technical Mission of Electoral Experts, sent by the European Union, published a 67-page report on 21 December that made similar observations and conclusions as the OAS's report. They noted that \"there were minutes with an unusually high number of null votes, blank votes and a hundred percent participation of voters in a series of polling stations\" and highlighted the general failure of the TSE to declare these irregularities.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.voanoticias.com/a/union-europea-detecto-errores-irregularidades-elecciones-bolivia/5215093.html|title=Informe de la UE detect\u00f3 \u201cnumerosos errores\u201d en elecciones de Bolivia|date=21 December 2019|work=Voice of America|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uetrabajandojuntos.org/documentos/|title=Informe Final de la Misi\u00f3n T\u00e9cnica de Expertos Electorales sobre las Elecciones Generales en Bolivia del 20 de octubre de 2019|last=|first=|date=21 December 2019|website=Trabajando Juntos|language=Spanish|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Analyses contradicting OAS report -->\nResponding to the OAS final report, a 27 February 2020 study published by independent contractors \u2014 commissioned by the [[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] and left-leaning <ref>{{cite web | url=https://fair.org/extra/the-incredible-shrinking-think-tank/ | title=The Incredible Shrinking Think Tank | last=Dolny | first=Michael | date=March 2008 | website=Fair | accessdate=17 April 2018 }}</ref><ref name=\"The Perils Of Petrocracy\">{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Tina|title=The Perils Of Petrocracy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/04/magazine/04oil-t.html?pagewanted=7|accessdate=5 October 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=4 November 2007|quote= \u2026 Mark Weisbrot, co-director of the Center for Economic and Policy Research, a left-leaning Washington policy group.}}</ref> think tank [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]] (CEPR) \u2014concluded that it was \"very likely\" that Morales' victory was legitimate.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Study Finds No Evidence of OAS Fraud Claims, \u201cVery Likely\u201d Evo Morales Won Bolivia\u2019s October Elections in the First Round |url=https://cepr.net/press-release/new-study-finds-no-evidence-of-oas-fraud-claims-very-likely-evo-morales-won-bolivias-october-elections-in-the-first-round/ |publisher=Center for Economic and Policy Research |date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=US centre: No evidence of fraud in Bolivia's October polls |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/centre-evidence-fraud-bolivia-october-polls-200228052717538.html |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=28 February 2020}}</ref> \"The media has largely reported the allegations of fraud as fact... However, as specialists in election integrity, we find that the statistical evidence does not support the claim of fraud in Bolivia's October election,\" the authors wrote in an article that was published by ''The Washington Post''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Curiel |first1=John |last2=Williams |first2=Jack R. |title=Bolivia dismissed its October elections as fraudulent. Our research found no reason to suspect fraud. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/02/26/bolivia-dismissed-its-october-elections-fraudulent-our-research-found-no-reason-suspect-fraud/ |work=The Washington Post |date=27 February 2020}}</ref>  As a rebuttal to this criticism of his work for the OAS, [[Georgetown University]] political scientist Irfan Nooruddin wrote a similar article in the Washington Post to back up his conclusions that there were unexplained massive swings to Morales that were \"unpredicted and unanticipated by any previous part of the election trends\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Nooruddin|first=Irfan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/10/yes-bolivias-2019-election-was-problematic-heres-why/|title=Yes, Bolivia's 2019 election was problematic. Here's why.|date=10 March 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> He also pointed to another study made by Diego Escobari, Associate Professor at University of Texas Rio Grande Valley, and Gary A. Hoover, Head of Economics at the University of Oklahoma, which \"concluded even more forcefully that the election was fraudulent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3492928|title=Evo Morales and Electoral Fraud in Bolivia: A Natural Experiment Estimate|last1=Escobari|first1=Diego|last2=Hoover|first2=Gary A.|date=12 December 2019|website=SSRN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Escobari |first1=Diego |last2=Valdivia |first2=Walter D. |title=Bolivia\u2019s Electoral Fraud Reckoning |url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/evo-morales-bolivia-presidential-election-fraud-by-walter-d-valdivia-and-diego-escobari-2020-03 |publisher=Project Syndicate |date=17 March 2020}}</ref> The 27 February report has received criticism from the OAS, who said it contained \"multiple falsehoods, inaccuracies and omissions\"; the interim Bolivian government, who called it \"lacking in scientific and academic value\"; and Bolivian newspaper, [[P\u00e1gina Siete]], who noted that one of the authors of the report, Jack Williams, had previously signed a letter to the US Congress to oppose the \"military coup\" in Bolivia and which supported a previous CEPR study claiming victory for Morales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/3/3/autor-de-analisis-del-cepr-firmo-peticion-favorable-evo-en-2019-248400.html|title=Author of CEPR analysis signed petition favouring Evo in 2019|last=Escobar|first=Luis|date=3 March 2020|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.la-razon.com/nacional/director-oea-analisis-expertos-mit_0_3323667654.html|title=OAS director observes 11 points in the MIT expert analysis|last=|first=|date=3 March 2020|website=La Raz\u00f3n|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2020/3/6/ven-que-analisis-del-cepr-quedo-desvirtuado-tras-la-carta-del-mit-248773.html|title=You can see that CEPR analysis was distorted after the MIT letter|last=Esc\u00f3bar|first=Luis|date=6 March 2020|website=P\u00e1gina Siete|language=es|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Morales' later activity -->\nIn December 2019, Morales moved from Mexico to Argentina, where he was also granted political asylum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/evo-morales-granted-refugee-status-argentina-191212145522052.html|title=Evo Morales granted refugee status in Argentina|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref> Later that month, an arrest warrant was issued for Morales by Bolivian prosecutors for alleged [[sedition]] and [[terrorism]]. The interim government alleged that Morales promoted violent clashes in the country before and after he left office.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/12/bolivia-prosecutors-order-arrest-president-evo-morales-191218181946003.html|title=Bolivia prosecutors order arrest of ex-President Evo Morales|date=18 December 2019|work=Al Jazeera|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/dec/18/warrant-for-arrest-of-evo-morales-issued-in-bolivia|title=Warrant for arrest of Evo Morales issued in Bolivia|date=18 December 2019|work=The Guradian|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2020, Morales announced that he would run for a seat in the [[Plurinational Legislative Assembly]] in the [[2020 Bolivian general election]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/04/world/americas/bolivia-evo-morales-senate.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 4, 2020 |title=Evo Morales, Now in Exile, to Run for Bolivia\u2019s Senate |first=Julie |last=Turkewitz |quote=Evo Morales, the former Bolivian president who fled his country in November amid violent protests over his bid to stay in power, will attempt to run for the Senate in the country\u2019s upcoming elections.}}</ref> On 20 February, however, the national electoral tribunal ruled that Morales was ineligible to run for Senate.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Reuters]] |title=Bolivia electoral body blocks Morales senate run |date=February 20, 2020 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/bolivia-politics-morales/bolivia-electoral-body-blocks-morales-senate-run-idUSL1N2AL014 |first=Daniel |last=Ramos |first2=Adam |last2=Jourdan |editor-first=Sanda |editor-last=Maler |quote=Salvador Romero, the head of the country\u2019s electoral tribunal, told reporters that Morales did not meet the requirements to be a Senate candidate for his Movement for Socialism (MAS) party, which is currently leading in the polls.}}</ref>\n\n==Political ideology==\n{{Quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=The worst enemy of humanity is capitalism. That is what provokes uprisings like our own, a rebellion against a system, against a neo-liberal model, which is the representation of a savage capitalism. If the entire world doesn't acknowledge this reality, that the national states are not providing even minimally for health, education and nourishment, then each day the most fundamental human rights are being violated.|source=\u2013 Evo Morales{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=12}} }}\n\nFigures in the Morales government have described the President's approach to politics as \"Evoism\" ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]: ''Evismo'').{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=210|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=65}} From 2009, Morales has advocated \"[[communitarianism|communitarian]] socialism\",{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=155}} while political scientist Sven Harten characterized Morales's ideology as \"eclectic\", drawing ideas from \"various ideological currents\".{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=40}} Harten noted that whilst Morales uses fierce anti-imperialist and leftist rhetoric, he is neither \"a hardcore [[anti-globalisation|anti-globalist]] nor a [[Marxism|Marxist]],\" not having argued for the violent and absolute overthrow of capitalism or U.S. involvement in Latin America.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=5}}\n\nEconomically, Morales's policies have sometimes been termed \"Evonomics\" and have focused on creating a [[mixed economy]].{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=222, 232}} Morales's presidential discourse has revolved around distinguishing between \"the people\", of whom he sees himself as a representative, and the oppressive socio-economic elite and the old political class, whom he believes have mistreated \"the people\" for centuries.{{sfn|Harten|2011|pp=154\u2013165}} Morales sought to make Bolivia's [[representative democracy]] more [[direct democracy|direct]] and [[communitarian]], through the introduction of referendums and a citizen-led legislative initiative.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=217}} George Philip and Francisco Panizza claimed that like his allies Correa and Ch\u00e1vez, Morales should be categorized as a populist,{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=68}} because he appealed \"directly to the people against their countries' political and economic order, divided the social field into antagonistic camps and promised redistribution and recognition in a newly founded political order.\"{{sfn|Philip|Panizza|2011|p=73}}\n\nVarious far left commentators have argued against categorizing the Morales administration as socialist. Bolivia's Marxist Vice President [[\u00c1lvaro Garc\u00eda Linera]] asserts that Bolivia lacks the sufficiently large industrialized working class, or [[proletariat]], to enable it to convert into [[Socialism (Marxism)|a socialist society]] in the Marxist understanding of the word. Instead, he terms the government's approach \"Andean and Amazonian capitalism\".{{sfnm|1a1=Dunkerley|1y=2007|1pp=159\u2013161|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=64|3a1=Farthing|3a2=Kohl|3y=2014|3p=87}} Marxist American sociologist [[James Petras]] has argued that Morales's government is neither socialist nor anti-imperialist, instead describing Morales as a \"[[paternalistic conservatism|radical conservative]]\" for utilizing socialist rhetoric while continuing to support foreign investment and the economic status of Bolivia's capitalist class,{{sfnm|1a1=Petras|1y=2007<!--|2a1=Petras|2y=2013 blacklisted source -->}} while British Trotskyist academic Jeffery R. Webber asserted that Morales was no socialist but that his government was \"reconstituting neoliberalism\", thereby rejecting \"neoliberal orthdoxy\" but retaining a \"core faith in the capitalist market as the principal engine of growth and industrialization.\"{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=232}} Similarly, Aymara activist Felipe Quispe characterised Morales's government as \"neoliberalism with an Indian [i.e. indigenous] face\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=148}}\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Esther Morales, hermana del presidente de Bolivia Evo Morales se reuni\u00f3 con el Canciller Ricardo Pati\u00f1o (8001318681).jpg|200px|thumb|right|First Lady Morales with the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Ecuador [[Ricardo Pati\u00f1o]].]]\nMorales is ethnically [[Aymara people|Aymara]], and has been widely described as Bolivia's first democratically-elected President from the indigenous majority.<ref name=\"oct17bbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-12166905|title=Evo Morales: Bolivian leader wants five more years in power|publisher=BBC News|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=October 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014115936/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-12166905|archive-date=October 14, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> Although Morales has sometimes been described as the first indigenous president to be democratically elected in Latin America, [[Benito Ju\u00e1rez]], a Mexican of the [[Zapotec peoples|Zapotec]] ethnic group, was elected President of Mexico in 1858.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=7}} Biographer Mart\u00edn Sivak described Morales as \"incorruptible, charismatic, and combative\",{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=95}} also noting that he had a \"friendly style\" and could develop a good rapport with journalists and photographers, in part because he could \"articulate his opinions with simplicity\".{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=45}} He places a great emphasis on trust,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=216}} and relies on his intuition, sometimes acting on what he considers omens in his dreams.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=215|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=167}} Harten said that Morales \"can be a forceful leader, one who instills great respect and, sometimes, a reluctance in others to contradict him, but he has also learnt to listen and learn from other people.\"{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=147}} Farthing and Kohl characterised Morales as a \"[[charisma]]tic [[populist]]\" of a kind common in Latin American history, who prioritized \"a direct relationship\" between the population and the leader.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=16}}\n\nMorales is not married and upon becoming president selected his older sister, [[Esther Morales Ayma]], to adopt the role of [[First Lady]]. He has two children from different mothers. They are his daughter Eva Liz Morales Alvarado and son \u00c1lvaro Morales Paredes.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |title=Hermana de Evo Morales sera primera dama |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/internacionales/505699.html |date=February 5, 2007 |work=[[Es M\u00e1s]] |language=es |access-date=July 18, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927015220/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/internacionales/505699.html |archive-date=September 27, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| title = Oposici\u00f3n pide investigar denuncia de periodista Valverde| work = Los Tiempos| location = Cochabamba| accessdate = February 6, 2016| date = February 4, 2016| url = http://www.lostiempos.com/diario/actualidad/nacional/20160204/oposicion-pide-investigar-denuncia-de-periodista-valverde_332040_737980.html| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160206084816/http://www.lostiempos.com/diario/actualidad/nacional/20160204/oposicion-pide-investigar-denuncia-de-periodista-valverde_332040_737980.html| archive-date = February 6, 2016| url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Layme| first = Beatriz| title = Evo afirma que tuvo un hijo con Zapata y que muri\u00f3 en 2007| work = La Raz\u00f3n| location = La Paz, Bolivia| accessdate = February 6, 2016| date = February 6, 2016| url = http://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2016/2/6/afirma-tuvo-hijo-zapata-murio-2007-85925.html| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160207055212/http://www.paginasiete.bo/nacional/2016/2/6/afirma-tuvo-hijo-zapata-murio-2007-85925.html| archive-date = February 7, 2016| url-status = live}}</ref> Politician [[Juan del Granado]] is Eva Liz's godfather.<ref name=\":0\"/> His children left Bolivia and travelled to [[Buenos Aires]] in late November 2019 .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/argentina/evo-morales-children-arrive-in-buenos-aires.phtml|title=Buenos Aires Times {{!}} Evo Morales' children arrive in Buenos Aires|website=www.batimes.com.ar|access-date=November 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMorales has commented that he is only a [[Roman Catholic]] in order \"to go to weddings\", and when asked if he believed in [[God]], responded that \"I believe in the land. In my father and my mother. And in ''[[wikt:cuchi cuchi|cuchi-cuchi]]'' (sexual activity).\"{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=66}} According to some, Evo lives an [[ascetic]] life, with little interest in material possessions.{{sfnm|1a1=Sivak|1y=2010|1p=218|2a1=Harten|2y=2011|2p=179}} Morales is  an [[association football]] enthusiast and plays the game frequently, often with local teams.<ref>{{cite news | title=Footballing president breaks nose | date=July 31, 2006 | accessdate=July 31, 2006 | publisher=BBC News | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5230572.stm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060816011715/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5230572.stm | archive-date=August 16, 2006 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=La fiesta de gala de los 15 a\u00f1os de Eva Liz Morales |work=El D\u00eda |accessdate=September 25, 2010 |date=November 27, 2009 |url=http://eldia.com.bo/?cat=181&pla=3&id_articulo=20491 |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706150427/http://eldia.com.bo/?cat=181&pla=3&id_articulo=20491 |archive-date=July 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMorales's unorthodox behavior contrasts with the usual manners of dignitaries and other political leaders in Latin America. During speeches he made use of personal stories and anecdotes,{{sfn|Sivak|2010|p=111}} and used [[coca]] as a political symbol, wearing a coca leaf garland around his neck and a hat with coca leaves in it when speaking to crowds of supporters.{{sfn|Kozloff|2008|p=119}} Following his election, he wore striped jumpers rather than the [[men's suit|suits]] typically worn by politicians. It became a symbol of Morales, with copies of it selling widely in Bolivia.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=169}}<ref>{{cite news | date=January 20, 2006 | title='Evo Fashion' arrives in Bolivia | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4630370.stm |website=BBC News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315182825/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4630370.stm |archivedate=March 15, 2008 }} Retrieved on February 1, 2007.</ref> \n\nOn July 4, 2018, Morales underwent emergency surgery at a private clinic in La Paz in order to remove a [[tumor]].<ref name=\"reutershealth\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivian-president-morales-has-emergency-surgery-for-tumor-idUSKBN1JV051 |publisher=Reuters |title=Bolivian President Morales has emergency surgery for tumor |first=Aislinn |last=Laing |first2=Daniel |last2=Ramos |editor-first=Leslie |editor-last=Adler |access-date=July 8, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708225416/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-politics/bolivian-president-morales-has-emergency-surgery-for-tumor-idUSKBN1JV051 |archive-date=July 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Influence and legacy==\n[[File:Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto, Justin Trudeau, and Evo Morales - Lima, Peru - 2018 (40563707215).jpg|thumb|right|Morales with [[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]] and [[Justin Trudeau]], Lima, Peru, 2018]]\n\nMorales has been described as \"the most famous Bolivian ever\",{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=1}} whose personality has become \"fixed in the global imagination\".{{sfn|Pearce|2011|p=xv}} Morales's government has been seen as part of the [[pink tide]] of left-leaning Latin American governments, becoming particularly associated with the hard left current of Venezuela and Cuba.{{sfnm|1a1=Pearce|1y=2011|1p=xv|2a1=Webber|2y=2011|2p=1}} It has been praised for its pro-socialist stance among the international left,{{sfn|Webber|2011|p=154}} who have taken an interest in Bolivia under his leadership as a \"political laboratory\"{{sfn|Mu\u00f1oz-Pogossian|2008|p=1}} or \"a living workshop\" for the development of an alternative to capitalism.{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=5}} Domestically, Morales's support base has been among Bolivia's poor and indigenous communities.<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> For these communities, who had felt marginalized in Bolivian politics for decades, Morales \"invokes a sense of dignity and destiny\" in a way that no other contemporary politician has done.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=227}} He has received the support of many [[democratic socialism|democratic socialists]] and [[social democracy|social democrats]], as well as sectors of Bolivia's liberal movement, who have been critical of Morales but favoured him over the right-wing opposition.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=157\u201358}}\n\nBased on interviews conducted among Bolivians in 2012, John Crabtree and Ann Chaplin described the previous years of Morales's rule with the observation that: \"for many\u2014perhaps most\u2014Bolivians, this was a period when ordinary people felt the benefits of policy in ways that had not been the case for decades, if ever.\"{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} Crabtree and Chaplin added that Morales's administration had made \"important changes... that will probably be difficult to reverse\", including poverty reduction, the removal of some regional inequalities, and side-lining of some previously dominant political actors in favor of others who had been encouraged and enabled by his government.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}}\n\nCritics, particularly in the U.S. government, have varyingly termed him \"a left-wing radical, a partner of narco-traffickers and a terrorist\".{{sfn|Sivak|2011|p=173}} Opposition to Morales's governance has centered in the wealthy eastern lowland province of Santa Cruz.<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> His policies often antagonized middle-class Bolivians, who deemed them too radical and argued that they threatened private property.<ref name=\"BBC bio\"/> His most vociferous critics have been from Bolivia's conservative movement, although he has also received criticism from the country's far left, who believe his reformist policies have been insufficiently radical or socialist.{{sfn|Webber|2011|pp=157\u201358}} Many of these leftist critics were unhappy that Morales's government did not make a total break with global capitalism.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} His government has also faced many of the same complaints directed at previous Bolivian administrations, revolving around such issues as \"concentration of power, corruption, incompetent bureaucracies, and disrespect for civil liberties\".{{sfn|Farthing|Kohl|2014|p=144}}\n\nCrabtree and Chaplin's study led them to conclude that while Morales's initial election had brought \"huge expectations\" from many Bolivians, especially in the social movements, there had been \"inevitable frustrations\" at his administration's inability to deliver on everything that they had hoped.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=vii}} They thought that the \"heady optimism\" that had characterized Morales's first term in office had given way to \"a climate of questioning and growing criticism of the government and its policies\".{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} Although the Bolivian economy had grown, the material benefits had not been as high as many Bolivians had hoped.{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=ix}} Crabtree and Chaplin argued that the experiences of his administration had \"drawn attention to the difficulties involved in bringing change in the patterns of development in one of Latin America's poorest and most unequal nations\".{{sfn|Crabtree|Chaplin|2013|p=vi}} Similarly, Harten thought that Morales's discourse of \"the people\" against the socio-economic elites has brought a spotlight on the deep social polarization in Bolivia.{{sfn|Harten|2011|p=229}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Domestic policy of Evo Morales]]\n* [[Foreign policy of Evo Morales]]\n* [[Evo Morales and the Roman Catholic Church]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite contribution |contribution=Bolivia's New Constitution and its Implications |title=Evo Morales and the Movimiento Al Socialismo in Bolivia: The First Term in Context, 2005\u20132009 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6xIYgEACAAJ&dq=The+Rise+of+Evo+Morales+and+the+MAS&hl=en&ei=3B4aTuHLDYrB8QOy5KgH&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDUQ6AEwAw |last=Assies|first=William|others=Adrian J. Pearce (ed.)|year=2011|publisher=Institute for the Study of th