ttlement_type        = [[Village development committee (Nepal)|Village development committee]]\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  -->\n|image_skyline          =\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             =\n|image_seal             =\n|image_map              = <!-- NepalMakwanpurDistrictmap.png -->\n|mapsize                = 300px\n|map_caption            = Map of the village development committees in Makwanpur District\n|pushpin_map            = Nepal\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Nepal\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Nepal}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Zones of Nepal|Zone]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Narayani Zone]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Makwanpur District]]\n|<!-- Politics -->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|leader_title1          = <!-- for places with, say, both a mayor and a city manager -->\n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      = <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       =\n<!-- Area    -->\n|unit_pref                =  <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = <!-- ALL fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   -->\n|population_as_of               = 1991\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               = 3884\n|population_density_km2         = auto\n|population_blank1_title        = Ethnicities\n<!-- General information  -->\n|timezone               = [[Nepal Time]]\n|utc_offset             = +5:45\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         =\n|coordinates            = {{coord|27.39|85.30|type:adm2nd_region:NP_source:unmaps-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''Shikharpur''' ([[Nepali language|Nepali]]: \u0936\u093f\u0916\u0930\u092a\u0941\u0930) is a [[Village development committee (Nepal)|village development committee]] in [[Makwanpur District]] in the [[Narayani Zone]] of southern [[Nepal]]. At the time of the [[1991 Nepal census]] it had a population of 3884 people living in 667 individual households.<ref>{{Cite web| url=http://www.digitalhimalaya.com/collections/nepalcensus/form.php?selection=1|title=Nepal Census 2001|work=Nepal's Village Development Committees|publisher=[[Digital Himalaya]]|accessdate=9 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 August 2010, an [[Agni Air Flight 101]] flight crashed and 14 people along with the crew died here.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/25/world/asia/25nepal.html Plane Crashes Near Everest..] retrieved 25 August 2010</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Makwanpur District}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Makwanpur District]]\n\n{{Narayani-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pegship", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Narayani-geo-stub}}, +{{Bagmati-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shikharpur,_Makwanpur"}
{"title_page": "Alan Charles Kors", "text_new": "{{short description|American academic}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image=alan kors.jpg\n|caption=President George W. Bush (right) and Laura Bush (left) stand with 2005 National Humanities Medal recipient Alan Charles Kors (center).\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1943|07|18|mf=yes}}\n|nationality=American\n|occupation=Professor\n|alma_mater=[[Harvard University]]\n}}\n'''Alan Charles Kors''' (born July 18, 1943)<ref name=\"FrohnenBeer2014\">{{cite book|author1=Bruce Frohnen|author2=Jeremy Beer|author3=Nelson O. Jeffrey|title=American Conservatism: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T1yOAwAAQBAJ|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=20 May 2014|publisher=Intercollegiate Studies Institute|isbn=978-1-4976-5157-9}}</ref> is Henry Charles Lea Professor Emeritus of History at the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref>[http://www.history.upenn.edu/people/emeritus/alan-charles-kors \"Alan Charles Kors.\" Department of History, University of Pennsylvania. Accessed 23 July 2017.]</ref> where he taught the intellectual history of the 17th and 18th centuries. He has received both the Lindback Foundation Award and the Ira Abrams Memorial Award for distinguished college teaching. Kors graduated A.B. [[summa cum laude]] at [[Princeton University]] in 1964, and received his M.A. (1965) and Ph.D. (1968) in European history at [[Harvard University]].\n==Career==\nKors has written on the history of [[skepticism|skeptical]], [[atheism|atheistic]], and [[materialism|materialist]] thought in 17th and 18th-century [[France]], on the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] in general, on the history of European [[witchcraft]] beliefs, and on academic freedom. He was also the Editor-in-Chief of the Encyclopedia of the Enlightenment, which was published in four volumes by [[Oxford University Press]] in 2002.<ref>http://global.oup.com/academic/product/encyclopedia-of-the-enlightenment-9780195104301?cc=us&lang=en&</ref>\n\nKors co-founded \u2013 with [[civil rights]] advocate [[Harvey A. Silverglate]] \u2013 and served from 2000 to 2006{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} as chairman of the board of directors of the [[Foundation for Individual Rights in Education]] (FIRE).\n\nHe writes pieces for both [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] and conservative journals on political matters.  He is an occasional contributor to ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]''.<ref>[http://www.reason.com/contrib/show/202.html \"Alan Charles Kors.\" ''Reason''. Accessed 14 March 2008.]</ref> His essay \"Can There Be An After Socialism?\" was published by the journal ''Social Philosophy & Policy''.<ref>\"Social Philosophy & Policy,\" 2003: Cambridge University Press, pp. 1\u201317</ref>\n\nKors has also been active in the defense of [[free speech]] since his arrival at [[University of Pennsylvania|Penn]]. In the widely covered 1993 \"[[water buffalo incident]]\", he defended [[Eden Jacobowitz]] against charges that he harassed a group of black sorority sisters. In the early morning hours, as the sorority was celebrating loudly outside the dorms, multiple students yelled from their windows, in various ways, for the sorority to cease. When the police came to question students, Jacobowitz volunteered that he yelled \"Shut up, you water buffalo\", a slur that was characterized as racist. The sorority members eventually dropped the charges.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} Kors later defended another University of Pennsylvania student in 2005 during a controversy surrounding the student's right to take a photo of other university students having sex against a dorm window.<ref>[[University of Pennsylvania controversy]]</ref><ref>[http://www.erinoconnor.org/archives/2005/12/more_on_penn_fr.html Critical Mass]</ref>\n\nIn 1992 President [[George H. W. Bush]] named him to the Council of the National Endowment of the Humanities. He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] and served on the committee for six years.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nIn 2005, President [[George W. Bush]] awarded Kors the [[National Humanities Medal]] for his \"scholarship, devotion to the Humanities, and...defense of academic freedom.\" In 2006, he was the T.B. Davie Memorial Lecturer on academic freedom at the [[University of Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].\n\nHe has served on the boards of The Historical Society and the [[American Society for Eighteenth-Century Studies]] and currently serves as a [[Visitor]] of [[Ralston College]].<ref>[http://www.ralston.ac/ Ralston College]</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''Witchcraft in Europe, 400\u20131700: A Documentary History'' (Middle Ages Series) by Alan Charles Kors (Editor), Edward Peters (Editor) {{ISBN|0-8122-1751-9}} (1972, revised edition 2001)\n* ''D'Holbach's Coterie: An Enlightenment in Paris'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|0-691-05224-7}} (1976, reissued 2015)\n* ''Atheism in France, 1650\u20131729: The Orthodox Sources of Disbelief'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|0-691-05575-0}} (1990, reissued 2015)\n* ''The Shadow University: The Betrayal Of Liberty On America's Campuses'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author), [[Harvey A. Silverglate]] (Author) {{ISBN|0-06-097772-8}} (1999)\n* ''Encyclopedia of the Enlightenment'' (4 vol. set) by Alan Charles Kors (Editor) {{ISBN|0-19-510433-1}} (2002)\n* ''Naturalism and Unbelief in France, 1650-1729'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|978-1107106635}} (2016)\n* ''Epicureans and Atheists in France, 1650-1729'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|978-1107132641}} (2016)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080312175552/http://www.thefire.org/index.php/ Foundation for Individual Rights in Education]\n* [http://www.history.upenn.edu/people/emeritus/alan-charles-kors Faculty page at the University of Pennsylvania ]\n* {{C-SPAN|alankors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kors, Alan Charles}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Free speech activists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:National Humanities Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American academic}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image=alan kors.jpg\n|caption=President George W. Bush (right) and Laura Bush (left) stand with 2005 National Humanities Medal recipient Alan Charles Kors (center).\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1943|07|18|mf=yes}}\n|nationality=American\n|occupation=Professor\n|alma_mater=[[Harvard University]]\n}}\n'''Alan Charles Kors''' (born July 18, 1943)<ref name=\"FrohnenBeer2014\">{{cite book|author1=Bruce Frohnen|author2=Jeremy Beer|author3=Nelson O. Jeffrey|title=American Conservatism: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T1yOAwAAQBAJ|accessdate=13 July 2016|date=20 May 2014|publisher=Intercollegiate Studies Institute|isbn=978-1-4976-5157-9}}</ref> is Henry Charles Lea Professor Emeritus of History at the [[University of Pennsylvania]],<ref>[http://www.history.upenn.edu/people/emeritus/alan-charles-kors \"Alan Charles Kors.\" Department of History, University of Pennsylvania. Accessed 23 July 2017.]</ref> where he taught the intellectual history of the 17th and 18th centuries. He has received both the Lindback Foundation Award and the Ira Abrams Memorial Award for distinguished college teaching. Kors graduated A.B. [[summa cum laude]] at [[Princeton University]] in 1964, and received his M.A. (1965) and Ph.D. (1968) in European history at [[Harvard University]].\n==Career==\nKors has written on the history of [[skepticism|skeptical]], [[atheism|atheistic]], and [[materialism|materialist]] thought in 17th and 18th-century [[France]], on the [[Age of Enlightenment|Enlightenment]] in general, on the history of European [[witchcraft]] beliefs, and on academic freedom. He was also the Editor-in-Chief of the Encyclopedia of the Enlightenment, which was published in four volumes by [[Oxford University Press]] in 2002.<ref>http://global.oup.com/academic/product/encyclopedia-of-the-enlightenment-9780195104301?cc=us&lang=en&</ref>\n\nKors co-founded \u2013 with [[civil rights]] advocate [[Harvey A. Silverglate]] \u2013 and served from 2000 to 2006{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} as chairman of the board of directors of the [[Foundation for Individual Rights in Education]] (FIRE).\n\nHe writes pieces for both [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] and conservative journals on political matters.  He is an occasional contributor to ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]''.<ref>[http://www.reason.com/contrib/show/202.html \"Alan Charles Kors.\" ''Reason''. Accessed 14 March 2008.]</ref> His essay \"Can There Be An After Socialism?\" was published by the journal ''Social Philosophy & Policy''.<ref>\"Social Philosophy & Policy,\" 2003: Cambridge University Press, pp. 1\u201317</ref>\n\nKors has also been active in the defense of [[free speech]] since his arrival at [[University of Pennsylvania|Penn]]. In the widely covered 1993 \"[[water buffalo incident]]\", he defended [[Eden Jacobowitz]] against charges that he harassed a group of black sorority sisters. In the early morning hours, as the sorority was celebrating loudly outside the dorms, multiple students yelled from their windows, in various ways, for the sorority to cease. When the police came to question students, Jacobowitz volunteered that he yelled \"Shut up, you water buffalo\", a slur that was characterized as racist. The sorority members eventually dropped the charges.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}} Kors later defended another University of Pennsylvania student in 2005 during a controversy surrounding the student's right to take a photo of other University students having sex against a dorm window.<ref>[[University of Pennsylvania controversy]]</ref><ref>[http://www.erinoconnor.org/archives/2005/12/more_on_penn_fr.html Critical Mass]</ref>\n\nIn 1992 President [[George H. W. Bush]] named him to the Council of the National Endowment of the Humanities. He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] and served on the committee for six years.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\nIn 2005, President [[George W. Bush]] awarded Kors the [[National Humanities Medal]] for his \"scholarship, devotion to the Humanities, and...defense of academic freedom.\" In 2006, he was the T.B. Davie Memorial Lecturer on academic freedom at the [[University of Cape Town]], [[South Africa]].\n\nHe has served on the boards of The Historical Society and the [[American Society for Eighteenth-Century Studies]] and currently serves as a [[Visitor]] of [[Ralston College]].<ref>[http://www.ralston.ac/ Ralston College]</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* ''Witchcraft in Europe, 400\u20131700: A Documentary History'' (Middle Ages Series) by Alan Charles Kors (Editor), Edward Peters (Editor) {{ISBN|0-8122-1751-9}} (1972, revised edition 2001)\n* ''D'Holbach's Coterie: An Enlightenment in Paris'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|0-691-05224-7}} (1976, reissued 2015)\n* ''Atheism in France, 1650\u20131729: The Orthodox Sources of Disbelief'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|0-691-05575-0}} (1990, reissued 2015)\n* ''The Shadow University: The Betrayal Of Liberty On America's Campuses'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author), [[Harvey A. Silverglate]] (Author) {{ISBN|0-06-097772-8}} (1999)\n* ''Encyclopedia of the Enlightenment'' (4 vol. set) by Alan Charles Kors (Editor) {{ISBN|0-19-510433-1}} (2002)\n* ''Naturalism and Unbelief in France, 1650-1729'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|978-1107106635}} (2016)\n* ''Epicureans and Atheists in France, 1650-1729'' by Alan Charles Kors (Author) {{ISBN|978-1107132641}} (2016)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080312175552/http://www.thefire.org/index.php/ Foundation for Individual Rights in Education]\n* [http://www.history.upenn.edu/people/emeritus/alan-charles-kors Faculty page at the University of Pennsylvania ]\n* {{C-SPAN|alankors}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kors, Alan Charles}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Free speech activists]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:National Humanities Medal recipients]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:replaced: University \u2192 university", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Charles_Kors"}
{"title_page": "Rajkumar Sah", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=November 2016}}\n}}\n{{Member Of Legislative Assembly- 124 Lalganj (Bihar)\nPolitical Party- Lok Janshakti Party\nIn Office- Nov. 2015 to Present\n\n}}\n'''Rajkumar Sah''' (born 1 January 1964) is an Indian politician. He is elected as a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] in 2015 on the ticket of  [[Lok Janshakti Party]] from [[Lalganj, Bihar (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]] with a huge margin of 20,293 votes against Bahubali [[Vijay Kumar Shukla]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/elections/bihar/lalganj-mla-results |title=Live: Lalganj Election Result 2016, Leading Candidate, Previous Winner, Lalganj MLA, Bihar - NDTV.com |publisher=[[NDTV]] |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.in/bihar/assembly-constituencies/lalganj.html |title=Lalganj (Bihar) Assembly Election Results 2015 - Winner and Runner-up Candidates |publisher=Elections.in |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref> He is active in social service when he was 20 years old. In 2000 he fought an election against Bahubali [[Vijay Kumar Shukla|Munna Shukla]] on the ticket of [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]]. Total vote collected by Rajkumar Sah is 80842 created history in lalganj vidhansabha. He is the son of a farmer Rajendra Pd. Sah.\n\n'''Political Carrier:'''\n\nRajkumar sah active in social service since he was 20 years old and got the party ticket from Rashtriya Janta Dal in 2000 to fight election from lalganj constituency. In 2005 again he fought on the ticket of RJD and in 2010 fought election independent from the same constituency and got huge public support and earn approx 40000 votes.  In 2015 got the ticket from LJP and won the election with huge margin and earn 83000 votes and create history in lalganj constituency. By seeing his performance and honest political character r Mr. Chirag Paswan ( Party president LJP)  appoint him as the vice president of the party in Bihar state. \n\n<br />\n\n==Personal life==\nHe belongs to a farmer family and his father Late Sri Rajendra Prasad Sahu was a farmer and a vegetable seed business man. Mr. Sah completed his education in bihar and is active in politics from 1995. Apart from politics he is a farmer and active in farming and seed industry. His native town is Lalganj (Vaishali) village Sahpur Kashim.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sah, Rajkumar}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 2015\u2013]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lok Janshakti Party politicians]]\n\n\n{{Bihar-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=November 2016}}\n}}\n{{Member Of Legislative Assembly- 124 Lalganj (Bihar)\nPolitical Party- Lok Janshakti Party\nIn Office- Nov. 2015 to Present\n\n}}\n'''Rajkumar Sah''' (born 1 January 1964) is an Indian politician. He is elected as a [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Legislative Assembly]] in 2015 on the ticket of  [[Lok Janshakti Party]] from [[Lalganj, Bihar (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]] with a huge margin of 20,293 votes against Bahubali [[Vijay Kumar Shukla]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/elections/bihar/lalganj-mla-results |title=Live: Lalganj Election Result 2016, Leading Candidate, Previous Winner, Lalganj MLA, Bihar - NDTV.com |publisher=[[NDTV]] |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.elections.in/bihar/assembly-constituencies/lalganj.html |title=Lalganj (Bihar) Assembly Election Results 2015 - Winner and Runner-up Candidates |publisher=Elections.in |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref> He is active in social service when he was 20 years old. In 2000 he fought an election against Bahubali [[Vijay Kumar Shukla|Munna Shukla]] on the ticket of [[Rashtriya Janata Dal]]. Total vote collected by Rajkumar Sah is 80842 created history in lalganj vidhansabha. He is the son of a farmer Rajendra Pd. Sah.\n\n'''Political Carrier:'''\n\nRajkumar sah active in social service since he was 20 years old and got the party ticket from Rashtriya Janta Dal in 2000 to fight election from lalganj constituency. In 2005 again he fought on the ticket of RJD and in 2010 fought election independent from the same constituency and got huge public support and earn approx 40000 votes.  In 2015 got the ticket from LJP and won the election with huge margin and earn 83000 votes and create history in lalganj constituency. By seeing his performance and honest political characte r Mr. Chirag Paswan ( Party president LJP)  appoint him as the vice president of the party in Bihar state. \n\n<br />\n\n==Personal life==\nHe belongs to a farmer family and his father Late Sri Rajendra Prasad Sahu was a farmer and a vegetable seed business man. Mr. Sah completed his education in bihar and is active in politics from 1995. Apart from politics he is a farmer and active in farming and seed industry. His native town is Lalganj (Vaishali) village Sahpur Kashim.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sah, Rajkumar}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Bihar MLAs 2015\u2013]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lok Janshakti Party politicians]]\n\n\n{{Bihar-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lee Vilenski", "label": "safe", "comment": "characte->character -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rajkumar_Sah"}
{"title_page": "2019\u201320 Oberliga (ice hockey) season", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports season\n| title            \t= 2019\u201320 Oberliga season\n| league          \t= [[Oberliga (ice hockey)|Oberliga]]\n| sport           \t= [[Ice Hockey]]\n| logo           \t= \n| pixels         \t= \n| caption      \t  \t=\n| color          \t= #c7bf98\n| color_text     \t= black\n| duration         \t= 28 September 2019 \u2013 11 March 2020\n| no_of_teams      \t= 24\n| no_of_games      \t= \n| attendance       \t= \n| TV               \t= Sprade TV <small>(select teams)</small>\n| season           \t= Regular season\n| season_champs    \t= [[Tilburg Trappers]] <small>(North)</small> <br> [[EV Regensburg|Eisb\u00e4ren Regensburg]] <small>(South)</small> \n| top_scorer       \t= Brad Snetsinger <small>(North)</small> <br> Ian McDonald <small>(South)</small>\n| top_scorer_link  \t= \n| promote               = N/A (no promotion playoffs <br> due to COVID-19)\n| promote_from          = <br>[[DEL2]]\n| relegate         \t= ERC Sonthofen Bulls <br> <small>(bankruptcy)</small>\n| relegate_to      \t= [[Regionalliga (ice hockey)|Regionalliga]]\n| finals           \t= Playoffs\n| finals_link      \t=\n| finals_champ     \t= No champion <br> <small>(Championship playoffs not contested)</small>\n| seasonslist      \t= Oberliga seasons\n| seasonslistnames \t= Oberliga\n| prevseason_link  \t= 2018\u201319 Oberliga (ice hockey) season\n| prevseason_year \t= 2018\u201319\n| nextseason_link  \t= 2020\u201321 Oberliga (ice hockey) season\n| nextseason_year  \t= 2020\u201321\n}}\n\nThe 2019/20 [[Oberliga (ice hockey)|Oberliga]] season was the 61st season of the Oberliga, the third-tier of [[Germany|German]] [[ice hockey]]. The Oberliga operated with two regional leagues, North and South. 24 teams competed in the season that spanned from 28 September 2019 till 11 March 2020. The regular season and championship playoff qualifyers was completed, but the season was then cut short due to the [[Coronavirus pandemic]] ([[COVID-19]]) and the remainder of the Oberliga season was cancelled by [[Deutscher Eishockey-Bund|DEB]].<ref name=\"DEBEARLYEND\">{{cite web | url=https://www.deb-online.de/2020/03/11/vorzeitiges-saisonende-aller-ligen-des-deb-spielbetriebs/ | title=Vorzeitiges Saisonende aller Ligen des DEB-Spielbetriebs | publisher=[[Deutscher Eishockey-Bund]] | first= | last= | date=11 March 2020 | accessdate=12 April 2020 | language=German | trans-title=Early season end to all DEB sanctioned leagues}}</ref> The championship playoffs were not contested so no Oberliga champion was named. There was also no sporting promotion or relegation, with ERC Sonthofen the only team to be relegated due to the club entering insolvency. [[Tilburg Trappers]] were crowned Oberliga North premiers, while [[EV Regensburg|Eisb\u00e4ren Regensburg]] were crowned Oberliga South premiers.\n\n==Teams==\n\n{{Location map+|Germany|width=400|float=right\n |alt=Oberliga (ice hockey)\n |caption=2019/20 German teams in Oberliga\n |places=\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 51.434406 |long= 6.762329 |mark = Blue pog.svg |label_size=80 |position = left |label=[[F\u00fcchse Duisburg|Duisburg]]}}\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 50.984768 |long= 11.029880 |mark = Blue pog.svg |label_size=80 |position = bottom |label=[[Black Dragons Erfurt|Erfurt]]}}\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 51.455643 |long= 7.011555 |mark = Blue pog.svg |label_size=80 |position = bottom |label=[[Moskitos Essen|Essen]]}}\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 51.482170 |long= 11.965800 |mark = Blue pog.svg |label_size=80 |position = left |label=[[Saale Bulls Halle|Halle]]}}\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 53.551086 |long= 9.993682 |mark = Blue pog.svg |label_size=80 |position = top |label=[[Hamburg Crocodiles|Hamburg]]}}\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 52.533333 |long= 9.716667 |mark = Blue pog.svg |label_size=80 |position = top |label=[[Hannover Indians|Indians]]}}\n  {{Location map~|Germany|lat= 52.533333 |long= 9.716667 |mark 